{"title_page": "William Gerard Hamilton", "text_new": "{{short description|18th-century Anglo-Irish politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific-prefix   = <small>[[Privy Council of Ireland|The Right Honourable]]</small>\n | name               = William Gerard Hamilton\n | native_name        = <!--The person's name in their own language, if different.-->\n | native_name_lang   = <!--ISO 639-1 code, e.g., \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} in |native_name= instead.-->\n | honorific-suffix   = <small>[[Privy Council of Ireland|PC (Ire)]]</small>\n | image              = Right Honourable William Gerard Hamilton, one of his Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council and chancellor of the Exchequer, in Ireland.jpg\n | image_size         = \n | smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n | alt                = \n | caption            = \n | order              = \n | office             = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Haslemere (UK Parliament constituency)|Haslemere]] (1790\u20131796)<br />{{small|[[Wilton (UK Parliament constituency)|Wilton]] (1780\u20131790)}}<br>{{small|[[Wareham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wareham]] (1774\u20131780)}}<br>{{small|[[Old Sarum (UK Parliament constituency)|Old Sarum]] (1768\u20131774)}}<br>{{small|[[Pontefract (UK Parliament constituency)|Pontefract]] (1761\u20131768)}}<br>{{small|[[Petersfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Petersfield]] (1754\u20131761)}}\n | term_start         = 1754\n | term_end           = 1796\n | alongside          = <!--For two or more people serving in the same position from the same district.  (e.g. United States Senators.)-->\n | monarch            =\n\n | order2             =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | office2            =  [[Chancellor of the Exchequer of Ireland]]\n | term_start2        =  1763\n | term_end2          =  1784\n | predecessor2       =  [[Sir William Yorke, 1st Baronet|Lord Yorke]]\n | successor2         =  [[John Foster, 1st Baron Oriel|John Foster]]\n\n | order3             =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | office3            =  [[Chief Secretary for Ireland]]\n | term_start3        =  1761\n | term_end3          =  1764\n\n | order4             =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | office4            =  [[Member of parliament#Ireland|Member of Parliament]] for [[Killybegs (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Killybegs]]\n | term_start4        =  1761\n | term_end4          =  1768\n\n | pronunciation   = \n | birth_name      = \n | birth_date      = 28 January 1729\n | birth_place     = [[London]], [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]]\n | death_date      = 16 July 1796 (aged 67)\n | death_place     = [[London]], [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]]\n | death_cause     = \n | resting_place   = [[St Martin-in-the-Fields]], [[City of Westminster]], [[London]]\n | resting_place_coordinates = \n | party           = \n | otherparty      =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n | height          =  <!-- \"X cm\", \"X m\"  or \"X ft Y in\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n | spouse          = \n | partner         =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n | relations       = \n | children        = \n | parents         =  <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n | mother          =  <!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n | father          =  <!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n | relatives       = \n | residence       = \n | education       = [[Winchester College]]\n | alma_mater      = [[Oriel College, Oxford]]\n | occupation      = \n | profession      = \n | known_for       = \n | salary          = \n | net_worth       =  <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n | cabinet         = \n | committees      = \n | portfolio       = \n | awards          =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n | signature       = \n | signature_alt   = \n<!--Military service-->\n | nickname        = \n | allegiance      = \n | branch          = \n | serviceyears    = \n | rank            = \n | unit            = \n | commands        = \n | battles         = \n | mawards         =  <!-- for military awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |awards= is not set -->\n}}\n'''William Gerard Hamilton''' (28 January 1729 &ndash; 16 July 1796), was an English [[politician|statesman]] and [[Ireland|Irish]] politician, popularly known as \"Single Speech Hamilton\".\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in [[London]], the son of William Hamilton, a Scottish bencher of [[Lincoln's Inn]], and succeeded his father in 1754. He was educated at [[Winchester College|Winchester]], [[Lincoln's Inn]] and [[Oriel College, Oxford]]. With his father's fortune he entered political life and became Member of Parliament for [[Petersfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Petersfield]] in [[Hampshire]]. His [[maiden speech]], delivered on 13 November 1755, during the debate on the address, which excited [[Robert Walpole|Walpole]]'s admiration, is generally supposed to have been his only effort in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]]. But the nickname \"Single Speech\" is undoubtedly misleading, and Hamilton is known to have spoken with success on other occasions, both in the House of Commons and in the Irish parliament.\n\n===Political offices===\nIn 1756 he was appointed one of the commissioners for trade and plantations, and in 1761 he became chief secretary to [[George Montague-Dunk, 2nd Earl of Halifax|Lord Halifax]], the [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland]], as well as [[Member of Parliament (pre-Union Ireland)|MP]] of the [[Irish House of Commons]] for [[Killybegs (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Killybegs]] (until 1768) and English MP for [[Pontefract (UK Parliament constituency)|Pontefract]].\n\nHe was appointed [[Irish Chancellor of the Exchequer]] in 1763, and subsequently filled various other administrative offices. Hamilton was thought very highly of by [[Samuel Johnson]], and it is certain that he was strongly opposed to the British taxation of [[United States|America]]. He was close to the [[George IV of the United Kingdom|Prince Regent]], serving as a trusted adviser.<ref name=\"HoP\"/> In 1784 he exchanged his office as Chancellor of the Exchequer for a pension of \u00a32,000 p.a.<ref name=\"HoP\"/> Hamilton had held the office for over 20 years, although had treated the role as a largely ceremonial position. He was succeeded by [[John Foster, 1st Baron Oriel|John Foster]], who went on to bring in changes credited with greatly boosting the rural Irish economy.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=b68UBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA75&lpg=PA75&dq=grattan+junta+1783&source=bl&ots=WvSRloWVcY&sig=NWdAx9-lh9pTJOMFsEwe-jEXdqM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjcnf_lzu_RAhXHJ8AKHZOYDasQ6AEIJjAC#v=onepage&q=grattan%20junta%201783&f=false Ireland: A History from the Twelfth Century to the Present Day p.75]</ref>\n\n===Ill health and death===\nHe suffered from a severe paralytic stroke in the winter of 1791\u201392. This had not been his first, and by August 1792 he remained in a poor state. On 4 March 1793 he received a leave of absence from the House of Commons due to his ill health. He died in [[London]] on 16 July 1796, and was buried in the chancel vault of [[St Martins-in-the-Fields]]. His death came \"just in time to save him from absolute poverty.\"<ref name=\"HoP\">[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1790-1820/member/hamilton-william-gerard-1729-96 HAMILTON, William Gerard (1729-96), of Hampton Court, Mdx., The History of Parliament]</ref> He was unmarried.\n\nTwo of his speeches in the [[Irish House of Commons]], and some other miscellaneous works\u2014including previously unpublished notes on the [[Corn Laws]] by Johnson\u2014were published by [[Edmond Malone]] after his death under the title ''Parliamentary Logick''.{{sfn|Martin|2005|p=7}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Hamilton, William Gerard}}\n*{{cite book |title = Edmond Malone, Shakespearean Scholar: A Literary Biography\n  |last = Martin\n  |first = Peter\n  |year = 2005\n  |publisher = Cambridge University Press\n  |isbn = 0-521-61982-3\n  |ref=harv\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.eighteenthcenturypoetry.org/authors/pers00227.shtml William Gerard Hamilton] at the [http://www.eighteenthcenturypoetry.org/ Eighteenth-Century Poetry Archive (ECPA)]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|ie}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Henry Gore]] <br/> [[Francis Conyngham, 2nd Baron Conyngham|Francis Pierpoint Burton]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Killybegs (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Killybegs]]\n       | with   = [[Richard Jones (politician)|Richard Jones]]\n       | years  = 1761\u20131768 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Sir Henry Hamilton, 1st Baronet|Henry Hamilton]] <br/> [[Thomas Allan (politician)|Thomas Allan]] }}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[John Jolliffe (of Petersfield)|John Jolliffe]] <br /> [[William Conolly (died 1754)|William Conolly]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Petersfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Petersfield]]\n       | with   = [[John Jolliffe (of Petersfield)|John Jolliffe]] 1754\n       | with2  = [[William Beckford (politician)|William Beckford]] 1754\n       | with3  = [[Sir John Philipps, 6th Baronet|Sir John Philipps]] 1754\u20131761\n       | years  = 1754\u20131761 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[John Jolliffe (of Petersfield)|John Jolliffe]] <br /> [[Richard Pennant, 1st Baron Penrhyn|Richard Pennant]]}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Sambrooke Freeman]]<br />[[William Monckton-Arundell, 2nd Viscount Galway|The Viscount Galway]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Pontefract (UK Parliament constituency)|Pontefract]]\n       | with   = [[William Monckton-Arundell, 2nd Viscount Galway|The Viscount Galway]]\n       | years  = 1761\u20131768 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[William Monckton-Arundell, 2nd Viscount Galway|The Viscount Galway]]<br />[[Sir Rowland Winn, 5th Baronet|Sir Rowland Winn]]}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Howell Gwynne (MP)|Howell Gwynne]]<br />[[Thomas Pitt, 1st Baron Camelford|Thomas Pitt]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Old Sarum (UK Parliament constituency)|Old Sarum]]\n       | with   = [[John Craufurd]]\n       | years  = 1768\u20131774 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Pinckney Wilkinson]]<br />[[Thomas Pitt, 1st Baron Camelford|Thomas Pitt]]}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Robert Palk]]<br />[[Thomas de Grey, 2nd Baron Walsingham|Thomas de Grey]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wareham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wareham]]\n       | with   = [[Christopher D'Oyly]]\n       | years  = 1774\u20131780}}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Sir John Boyd, 2nd Baronet|John Boyd]]<br />[[Thomas Farrer (MP)|Thomas Farrer]]}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Henry Herbert, 1st Earl of Carnarvon|Henry Herbert]]<br />[[Charles Herbert (1743-1816)|Charles Herbert]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wilton (UK Parliament constituency)|Wilton]]\n       | with   = [[George Herbert, 11th Earl of Pembroke|Lord Herbert]] 1780\u20131785, 1788\u20131790\n       | with2  = [[Philip Goldsworthy]] 1785\u20131788\n       | years  = 1780\u20131790}}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[George Herbert, 11th Earl of Pembroke|Lord Herbert]]<br />[[Richard FitzWilliam, 7th Viscount FitzWilliam|The Viscount FitzWilliam]]}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[John Baynes-Garforth]]<br />[[Sir John Lowther, 1st Baronet, of Swillington|John Lowther]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Haslemere (UK Parliament constituency)|Haslemere]]\n       | with   = [[James Lowther (1753\u20131837)|James Lowther]] 1790\n       | with2  = [[Richard Penn (governor)|Richard Penn]] 1790\u20131791\n       | with3  = [[James Clarke Satterthwaite]] 1791\u20131796\n       | years  = 1790\u20131796 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[James Clarke Satterthwaite]]<br />[[James Lowther (1753\u20131837)|James Lowther]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Chief Secretary for Ireland]] | before=[[Richard Rigby]] | after=[[Charles Moore, 1st Marquess of Drogheda|The Earl of Drogheda]] | years=1761\u20131764}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Sir William Yorke, 1st Baronet|Sir William Yorke]] | title=[[Chancellor of the Exchequer of Ireland]] | years=1763\u20131784 | after=[[John Foster, 1st Baron Oriel|John Foster]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamilton, William Gerard}}\n[[Category:1729 births]]\n[[Category:1796 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Winchester College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Oriel College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Members of Lincoln's Inn]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1754\u20131761]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1761\u20131768]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1768\u20131774]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1774\u20131780]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1780\u20131784]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1784\u20131790]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1790\u20131796]]\n[[Category:Irish MPs 1761\u20131768]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Ireland (pre-1801) for County Donegal constituencies]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the Exchequer of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Chief Secretaries for Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|18th-century Anglo-Irish politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific-prefix   = <small>[[Privy Council of Ireland|The Right Honourable]]</small>\n | name               = William Gerard Hamilton\n | native_name        = <!--The person's name in their own language, if different.-->\n | native_name_lang   = <!--ISO 639-1 code, e.g., \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} in |native_name= instead.-->\n | honorific-suffix   = <small>[[Privy Council of Ireland|PC (Ire)]]</small>\n | image              = Right Honourable William Gerard Hamilton, one of his Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council and chancellor of the Exchequer, in Ireland.jpg\n | image_size         = \n | smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n | alt                = \n | caption            = \n | order              = \n | office             = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Haslemere (UK Parliament constituency)|Haslemere]] (1790\u20131796)<br />{{small|[[Wilton (UK Parliament constituency)|Wilton]] (1780\u20131790)}}<br>{{small|[[Wareham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wareham]] (1774\u20131780)}}<br>{{small|[[Old Sarum (UK Parliament constituency)|Old Sarum]] (1768\u20131774)}}<br>{{small|[[Pontefract (UK Parliament constituency)|Pontefract]] (1761\u20131768)}}<br>{{small|[[Petersfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Petersfield]] (1754\u20131761)}}\n | term_start         = 1754\n | term_end           = 1796\n | alongside          = <!--For two or more people serving in the same position from the same district.  (e.g. United States Senators.)-->\n | monarch            =\n\n | order2             =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | office2            =  [[Chancellor of the Exchequer of Ireland]]\n | term_start2        =  1763\n | term_end2          =  1784\n | predecessor2       =  [[Sir William Yorke, 1st Baronet|Lord Yorke]]\n | successor2         =  [[John Foster, 1st Baron Oriel|John Foster]]\n\n | order3             =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | office3            =  [[Chief Secretary for Ireland]]\n | term_start3        =  1761\n | term_end3          =  1764\n\n | order4             =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | office4            =  [[Member of parliament#Ireland|Member of Parliament]] for [[Killybegs (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Killybegs]]\n | term_start4        =  1761\n | term_end4          =  1768\n\n | pronunciation   = \n | birth_name      = \n | birth_date      = 28 January 1729\n | birth_place     = [[London]], [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]]\n | death_date      = 16 July 1796 (aged 67)\n | death_place     = [[London]], [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]]\n | death_cause     = \n | resting_place   = [[St Martin-in-the-Fields]], [[City of Westminster]], [[London]]\n | resting_place_coordinates = \n | party           = \n | otherparty      =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n | height          =  <!-- \"X cm\", \"X m\"  or \"X ft Y in\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n | spouse          = \n | partner         =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n | relations       = \n | children        = \n | parents         =  <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n | mother          =  <!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n | father          =  <!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n | relatives       = \n | residence       = \n | education       = [[Winchester College]]\n | alma_mater      = [[Oriel College, Oxford]]\n | occupation      = \n | profession      = \n | known_for       = \n | salary          = \n | net_worth       =  <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n | cabinet         = \n | committees      = \n | portfolio       = \n | awards          =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n | signature       = \n | signature_alt   = \n<!--Military service-->\n | nickname        = \n | allegiance      = \n | branch          = \n | serviceyears    = \n | rank            = \n | unit            = \n | commands        = \n | battles         = \n | mawards         =  <!-- for military awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |awards= is not set -->\n}}\n'''William Gerard Hamilton''' (28 January 1729 &ndash; 16 July 1796), was an English [[politician|statesman]] and [[Ireland|Irish]] politician, popularly known as \"Single Speech Hamilton\".\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in [[London]], the son of William Hamilton, a Scottish bencher of [[Lincoln's Inn]], and succeeded his father in 1754. He was educated at [[Winchester College|Winchester]], [[Lincoln's Inn]] and [[Oriel College, Oxford]]. With his father's fortune he entered political life and became Member of Parliament for [[Petersfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Petersfield]] in [[Hampshire]]. His [[maiden speech]], delivered on 13 November 1755, during the debate on the address, which excited [[Robert Walpole|Walpole]]'s admiration, is generally supposed to have been his only effort in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]]. But the nickname \"Single Speech\" is undoubtedly misleading, and Hamilton is known to have spoken with success on other occasions, both in the House of Commons and in the Irish parliament.\n\n===Political offices===\nIn 1756 he was appointed one of the commissioners for trade and plantations, and in 1761 he became chief secretary to [[George Montague-Dunk, 2nd Earl of Halifax|Lord Halifax]], the [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland]], as well as [[Member of Parliament (pre-Union Ireland)|MP]] of the [[Irish House of Commons]] for [[Killybegs (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Killybegs]] (until 1768) and English MP for [[Pontefract (UK Parliament constituency)|Pontefract]].\n\nHe was appointed [[Irish Chancellor of the Exchequer]] in 1763, and subsequently filled various other administrative offices. Hamilton was thought very highly of by [[Samuel Johnson]], and it is certain that he was strongly opposed to the British taxation of [[United States|America]]. He was close to the [[George IV of the United Kingdom|Prince Regent]], serving as a trusted adviser.<ref name=\"HoP\"/> In 1784 he exchanged his office as Chancellor of the Exchequer for a pension of \u00a32,000 p.a.<ref name=\"HoP\"/> Hamilton had held the office for over 20 years, although had treated the role as a largely ceremonial position. He was succeeded by [[John Foster, 1st Baron Oriel|John Foster]], who went on to bring in changes credited with greatly boosting the rural Irish economy.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=b68UBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA75&lpg=PA75&dq=grattan+junta+1783&source=bl&ots=WvSRloWVcY&sig=NWdAx9-lh9pTJOMFsEwe-jEXdqM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjcnf_lzu_RAhXHJ8AKHZOYDasQ6AEIJjAC#v=onepage&q=grattan%20junta%201783&f=false Ireland: A History from the Twelfth Century to the Present Day p.75]</ref>\n\n===Ill health and death===\nHe suffered from a severe paralytic stroke in the winter of 1791-92. This had not been his first, and by August 1792 he remained in a poor state. On 4 March 1793 he received a leave of absence from the House of Commons due to his ill health. He died in [[London]] on 16 July 1796, and was buried in the chancel vault of [[St Martins-in-the-Fields]]. His death came \"just in time to save him from absolute poverty.\"<ref name=\"HoP\">[http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1790-1820/member/hamilton-william-gerard-1729-96 HAMILTON, William Gerard (1729-96), of Hampton Court, Mdx., The History of Parliament]</ref> He was unmarried.\n\nTwo of his speeches in the [[Irish House of Commons]], and some other miscellaneous works\u2014including previously unpublished notes on the [[Corn Laws]] by Johnson\u2014were published by [[Edmond Malone]] after his death under the title ''Parliamentary Logick''.{{sfn|Martin|2005|p=7}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n