446_1.html|title=Coronavirus: Tamil Nadu closes schools, malls and theatres till March 31|date=15 March 2020|work=Business Standard India|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-schools-colleges-malls-movie-theatres-to-be-closed-in-telangana-until-31-march-11584186142495.html|title=Coronavirus: Schools, movie theatres to be closed in Telangana until 31 March|date=14 March 2020|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> [[Ministry of Culture (India)|Ministry of Culture]] shut down all monuments and museums under [[Archaeological Survey of India]] till 31 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/all-asiprotected-monuments-central-museums-across-india-to-be-shut-till-march-31-govt/1763377|title=All ASI-protected monuments, central museums across India to be shut till March 31: Govt|date=|work=Outlook|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* '''On 17 March''', schools, colleges and multiplexes in [[Uttar Pradesh]] were shut down till 2 April and on-going examinations were postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=All schools, colleges, cinema halls in UP closed till April 2 amid coronavirus pandemic| url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/schools-colleges-cinema-halls-in-uttar-pradesh-closed-till-april-2-amid-coronavirus-pandemic-598922|website=indianews|author=| date=17 March 2020}}</ref> [[Brihanmumbai Municipal Corporation|BMC]] ordered private firms in [[Mumbai]] to function \"only at 50% of their staff capacity or face action under section 188 of the [[Indian Penal Code|IPC]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/bmc-orders-private-firms-to-work-only-at-50-of-their-capacity/articleshow/74661516.cms|title=BMC orders private companies to work only at 50% of capacity as coronavirus count rises|date=|work=Economic Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Rajasthan]] government banned the gathering of more than 50 people in public places till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus outbreak: Rajasthan bans all 50-plus gathering in public places till March 31, says official| url=https://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/coronavirus-outbreak-rajasthan-bans-all-50-plus-gathering-in-public-places-till-march-31-says-official/1900701/|website=financial express|author=| date=17 March 2020}}</ref> Important tourist destinations in [[Tamil Nadu]] were locked down. Authorities in [[Nilgiris]] district ordered the closure of tourist sites including [[Ooty]] and the tourists staying in hotels and resorts were given 24 hours to leave the city.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Tourist centres in TN under lockdown; Visitors in| url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/coronavirus-tourist-centres-in-tn-under-lockdown-visitors-in/1768933|website=outlookindia|author=}}</ref> In [[Maharashtra]], government offices were closed down for seven days.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Maharashtra to shut government offices for next 7 days| url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/coronavirus-uddhav-thackeray-maharashtra-government-offices-shut-7-days-598998|website=indiatv|author=| date=17 March 2020}}</ref> [[Chandigarh]] administration ordered the closure of shopping malls, cinema halls, gyms, nightclubs, swimming pools, coaching centres, spas, creches and video game parlours till 31 March. It also banned gatherings of more than a 100 people and census work was postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Covid-19: Malls, cinema halls, gyms closed in Chandigarh| url=https://m.hindustantimes.com/cities/malls-clubs-discotheques-and-gyms-closed-in-chandigarh-till-march-31-to-check-coronavirus-spread/story-SlWceuV22oQXG5RKxODz4M.html|website=Hindustan times|author=| date=16 March 2020}}</ref> At the same time, [[Dera]] chiefs were asked to postpone all religious events till 31 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Punjab malls, gyms, restaurants deserted after advisory on coronavirus| url=https://wap.business-standard.com/multimedia/video-gallery/general/punjab-malls-gyms-restaurants-deserted-after-advisory-on-coronavirus-101227.htm|newspaper=Business Standard India|author=}}</ref> The GoM has also directed that no more than 50 people are allowed to gather at any place other than [[weddings]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Punjab: Malls, shopping complexes shut till March 31; curbs on gatherings at marriage palaces| url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/north-and-central/punjab-malls-shopping-complexes-shut-till-march-31-curbs-on-gatherings-at-marriage-palaces-814691.html|website=Deccan herald|author=| date=17 March 2020}}</ref> [[Pondicherry]] shut down schools, colleges, cinemas and gyms till 31 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/coronavirus-live-updates-number-of-coronavirus-cases-in-india-mumbai-hyderabad-kerala-pune-delhi/liveblog/74664459.cms|title=Coronavirus outbreak live updates: Railways cancels 76 trains as coronavirus precautionary measure, non-occupancy|date=|work=Times of India|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mumbai Police]] ordered the closure of pubs, bars and discotheques till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/coronavirus-in-mumbai-eatery-industry-seeks-financial-relief-from-government/articleshow/74682915.cms |website=Times of India |accessdate=18 March 2020|date=18 March 2020|title=Coronavirus in Mumbai: Pubs, bars closed |first1=Reeba |last1=Zachariah |first2=S Ahmed |last2=Ali}}</ref>\n* '''On 18 March''', [[District magistrate|district magistrate and deputy commissioner]] of [[Srinagar district]] in [[Jammu and Kashmir (union territory)|Jammu and Kashmir]] said that the entry of all foreign tourists has been banned in the entire union territory.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Foreign tourists' entry banned in Kashmir| url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/coronavirus-foreign-tourists-entry-banned-in-kashmir20200318043955/|website=ANI|author=}}</ref> On the other hand, the Directorate of Floriculture, Parks and Horticulture of the state has also extended the [[Bahu Fort|Bagh-e-Bahu Garden]] to the general public from 18 to 31 March to keep the situation under control in the Union Territory.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Entry of foreign tourists banned in Kashmir| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/coronavirus-entry-of-foreign-tourists-banned-in-kashmir/amp_articleshow/74680062.cms|website=timesofindia|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Foreign tourists' entry banned in Kashmir| url=https://in.news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-foreign-tourists-entry-banned-kashmir-230952993.html?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAAsTPJ7Iu8cHV2-xuPg420W0USOlXiZxrTxRaDzUOSe5JdhiIz3IZSoNue88uIJ6prDuoXqZJARg2C8LnSYSxIymW9gjjnnnAAptcCa3E3BOPUOfZxHBFR2hFOPpN5U7HP3MFvt6wIV-_j4WcRlVUxq_FjHwkZKTOgU_NrfcszhK|website=Yahoo india|author=}}</ref> [[Government of Andhra Pradesh]] announced closure of all educational institutions till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/education/news/andhra-pradesh-educational-institutions-remain-closed-till-march-31-due-to-coronavirus/articleshow/74694735.cms|title=AP educational institutions to remain closed till March 31 due to Coronavirus outbreak|website=The Times of India|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''On 23 March''', [[Chief Minister of Maharashtra]] announced that borders of all the districts will be closed, and a strict curfew will be implemented statewide.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/uddhav-thackeray-imposes-curfew-in-entire-maharashtra/articleshow/74775886.cms?from=mdr|title=Uddhav Thackeray imposes curfew in entire Maharashtra|date=23 March 2020|newspaper=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n\n===Lockdown===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus lockdown in India}}\nOn 22 March, the [[Government of India]] decided to completely lockdown 82 districts in 22 states and Union Territories of country where confirmed cases have been reported till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/82-districts-under-lockdown-over-covid-19-what-s-open-and-what-is-shut/story-c1AEMZXuuXN6FvmrAdRvsJ.html|title=82 districts under lockdown over Covid-19: What is shut and where|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> At 6 am on 23 March Delhi was put under lockdown till at least 31 March. Essential services and commodities were to continue.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jagannath |first1=J. |title=Delhi lockdown to start at 6 am Monday, until 31 March: Kejriwal |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/delhi-lockdown-to-start-at-6-am-monday-until-31-march-kejriwal-11584881955813.html |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Livemint |date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/lockdown-in-west-bengal-from-5pm-today-government-to-shut-down-non-essentials/articleshow/74766599.cms|title=Lockdown in West Bengal: From 5pm today, government to shut down non-essentials|date=23 March 2020|work=The Times of India|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> 80 cities including major cities such as Bengaluru, Chennai, Mumbai,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marpakwar |first1=Prafulla |title=Poor public response pushed govt to declare lockdown in Mumbai |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/poor-public-response-pushed-govt-to-declare-lockdown-in-mumbai/articleshow/74766049.cms |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Times of India |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Chandigarh<ref>{{cite news |title=Chandigarh orders lock down till March 31 |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/chandigarh-orders-lock-down-till-march-31/article31135191.ece |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> and Kolkata were also put under lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gunasekar |first1=Arvind |last2=Bhattacharji |first2=Chetan |title=Coronavirus: 80 Cities Across India Go Into Lockdown Till March 31. What It Means |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-covid-19-80-cities-across-india-go-into-lockdown-till-march-31-what-it-means-2198894 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=NDTV |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Inter-state movements are allowed during the lockdown period. However some states have closed their borders.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-outbreak-lockdown-in-delhi-uttar-pradesh-rajasthan-telangana-andhra-nagaland-full-details-1658523-2020-03-22|title=Coronavirus outbreak: States impose lockdown in battle against Covid-19 {{!}} All you need to know|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, [[Government of India|union]] and [[State government in india|state governments]] announced the lockdown of 75 districts where cases were reported.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus update: 75 cities across India under lockdown. Full list across states| url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-update-75-cities-across-india-under-lockdown-full-list-across-states-11584931492672.html|website=Livemint|author=| date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, [[Prime Minister of India|PM]] [[Narendra Modi]] announced a complete nationwide lockdown, starting from midnight for 21 days.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/narendra-modi-on-coronavirus-speech-live-updates-streaming-watch-india-pm-address-to-nation-on-covid-19-today-latest-news-lockdown-janata-curfew-8182241.html|title=Narendra Modi on Coronavirus Outbreak LIVE Updates: India under complete shutdown for 21 days starting 12 pm tonight, says PM|date=|work=Firstpost|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, in Telangana, the chief minister suggested that the lockdown should be extended by two weeks after April 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/india/news/lockdown-in-telangana-extended-till-june-3/articleshow/75014509.cms|title=Telangana CM suggests lockdown extension by two weeks|date=|website=Business Insder|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date= 6 April 2020}}</ref> On 8 April, the [[Government of Uttar Pradesh|Yogi government]] has ordered the hot spot areas of 15 districts of [[Uttar Pradesh]] to be sealed till 15 April.<ref>[https://www.timesnownews.com/india/article/up-15-district-name-uttar-pradesh-lockdown-latest-news-15-districts-sealed-list-and-what-it-means/575560t]{{dead link |date=April 2020}}</ref> [[Government of Odisha|Odisha]], [[Government of Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[Government of Maharashtra|Maharashtra]], and [[Government of West Bengal|West Bengal]] governments have extended the lockdown in their states till 30 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/odisha-becomes-first-state-to-extend-covid-19-lockdown-sets-april-30-as-new-date/story-MLEr0Zie3fXZWufT1lC2QM.html|title=Odisha becomes first state to extend Covid-19 lockdown; sets 30 April as new date|date=2020-04-09|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/punjab-extends-lockdown-till-april-30/articleshow/75082850.cms|title=Covid-19: Punjab extends lockdown till April 30|date=10 April 2020|work=Economictimes|access-date=10 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web |title=Maharashtra, West Bengal Extend Coronavirus Lockdown Till April 30 After Video-Meet With PM Narendra Modi| url=https://www.latestly.com/india/news/maharashtra-west-bengal-extend-coronavirus-lockdown-till-april-30-after-video-meet-with-pm-narendra-modi-1675139.html|website=Latestly|date= 11 April 2020|language=en|url-status=live|access-date= 11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April, [[Prime Minister of India|PM]] [[Narendra Modi]] extended nationwide lockdown till 3 May, and he also announced that after 20 April a conditional relaxation in lockdown will be given in some areas of the country where spread have been prevented or contained. <ref name=\"lockdownext\">{{cite web |title=PM Modi announces extension of lockdown till 3 May| url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/pm-modi-announces-extension-of-lockdown-till-3-may-11586839412073.html|website=Livemint|author=| date= April 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date= 14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Communication===\n{{Quote box\n| width = 24%\n| align = right\n| quote = 'Prepare, but don't panic' has been India's guiding mantra in dealing with the virus outbreak. Our region has reported less than 150 coronavirus cases, but we need to remain vigilant. Step-by-step approach helped avoid panic, made special efforts to reach out to vulnerable groups.\n| source = \u2014 Prime Minister Narendra Modi during the video conference with SAARC nations, 15 March 2020.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |title=India offers $10 mn for coronavirus emergency fund: PM Modi to SAARC leaders| url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/saarc-video-conference-live-we-evacuated-1-400-indians-from-different-countries-says-modi-11584273185030.html|website=Livemint|author=| date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n[[File:PM Modi\u2019s address to the nation on Corona Virus.webm|right|thumb|Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi's televised address about Coronavirus on 19 March 2020]]\n[[File:PM Modi's address to the nation on vital aspects relating to COVID-19 menace.webm|right|thumb|Modi's address about COVID-19 on 24 March 2020]]\nOn 19 March, during a 30-minute live telecast, [[Prime Minister of India|Indian Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] asked all citizens to observe '[[Janata Curfew]]' (people's curfew) on 7 am to 9 pm on 22 March. During this curfew he asked everyone, except those involved in essential services, to stay at home. He also asked people to avoid routine checkups and [[Elective surgery|elective surgeries]] to reduce the burden on the health system. He announced the formation of a [[COVID-19 Economic Response Task Force]]. To acknowledge the work being done by various sectors during the outbreak, he urged people to gather in front of their own doors, windows or balconies at 5 pm and applaud them for five minutes. State and local authorities were told to blow the siren to remind people about the same.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/-janata-curfew-and-other-highlights-from-pm-modi-s-address-to-the-nation-11584632651166.html|title='Janata Curfew' and other highlights from PM Modi's address to the nation|date=|work=Livemint|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 24 March, Modi announced a nationwide lockdown from midnight of that day, for a period of 21 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/india/covid-19-indian-pm-modi-announces-complete-lock-down-starting-march-25-1.1585060911566|title=COVID-19: Indian PM Modi announces complete lock down starting March 25|author=|website=gulfnews}}</ref> He also announced a {{INRConvert|15000|c}} aid for the healthcare sector. This money would be used for developing testing facilities, [[Personal protective equipment|PPEs]], [[Intensive care unit|ICUs]], [[Ventilators]] and for training medical workers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/rs-15000-crore-alloted-for-healthcare-to-fight-coronavirus-says-pm-modi/story/399119.html|title=Rs 15,000 crore allotted for healthcare to fight coronavirus, says PM Modi|website=www.businesstoday.in}}</ref> On 3 April, PM Modi addressed the nation to turn off the lights for nine minutes and lighting the [[candle]]s on 5 April.<ref>{{cite web |title=PM Modi urges countrymen to dispel the darkness spread by coronavirus by lighting a candles on April 5| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-modi-urges-countrymen-to-dispel-the-darkness-spread-by-coronavirus-by-lighting-a-candle-on-april-5/articleshow/74959545.cms|website=Economic Times|author=| date= 3 April 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date= 3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Legal announcements ====\n{{see also|Essential Services Maintenance Act|Essential Commodities Act}}\nOn 11 March 2020, the [[Cabinet Secretary of India]], [[Rajiv Gauba]], announced that all states and UTs should invoke provisions of Section 2 of the [[Epidemic Diseases Act, 1897]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/the-123-year-old-law-that-india-may-invoke-as-more-and-more-coronavirus-cases-emerge/articleshow/74593639.cms|title=The 123-year-old law that India may invoke to counter coronavirus|date=12 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/to-combat-coronavirus-india-invokes-provisions-of-colonial-era-epidemic-act-all-you-need-to-know-8142601.html|title=To combat coronavirus, India invokes provisions of colonial-era Epidemic Diseases Act: A look at what this means|last=|first=|date=12 March 2020|website=Firstpost|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, the union government declared the pandemic as a \"notified disaster\" under the [[Disaster Management Act, 2005]], enabling states to spend a larger part of funds from the State Disaster Response Fund to fight the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/india-declares-coronavirus-a-notified-disaster-lists-compensation-2194915|title=India Declares Coronavirus A Notified Disaster|last=|first=|date=14 March 2020|editor-last=Srinivasan|editor-first=Chandrashekar|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/india-declares-coronavirus-outbreak-as-a-notified-disaster-11584184739353.html|title=India declares coronavirus outbreak as a notified disaster|date=14 March 2020|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Evacuations===\n[[File:Minister visiting the Coronavirus Quarantine Centre 2.jpg|thumb|The Minister of State for Home Affairs, [[Nityanand Rai]] visiting evacuees at the Coronavirus Quarantine Centre, after completion of their requisite quarantine period, at the ITBP Chhawla Centre, in New Delhi on 13 March 2020.]]\nThe [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]] under [[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Minister]] [[Subrahmanyam Jaishankar]], [[Air India]] and the [[Indian Air Force]] have been successful in evacuating many Indian nationals and certain foreign nationals from the virus effected areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-special-flights-land-in-delhi-after-evacuation-from-japan-china-11582773171379.html|title=Coronavirus: Special flights land in Delhi after evacuation from Japan, China|first=Elizabeth|last=Roche|date=27 February 2020|website=Livemint|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228151542/https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-special-flights-land-in-delhi-after-evacuation-from-japan-china-11582773171379.html|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/india-extended-offer-of-evacuating-people-from-wuhan-to-all-its-neighbours-jaishankar-in-rajya-sabha/story-eoa4XVzKN3WGQFAsAEJP2H.html|title=India offered to evacuate students of all neighbours, says Jaishankar on Pak students in Wuhan|date=7 February 2020|website=Hindustan Times|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223060302/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/india-extended-offer-of-evacuating-people-from-wuhan-to-all-its-neighbours-jaishankar-in-rajya-sabha/story-eoa4XVzKN3WGQFAsAEJP2H.html|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/iaf-air-india-flights-evacuate-indians-foreigners-wuhan-japan-ship-1650379-2020-02-27|title=IAF evacuates 112 from coronavirus-hit Wuhan; Air India repatriates Indian crew from cruise ship|first1=|date=27 February 2020|website=India Today|access-date=2 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228162735/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/iaf-air-india-flights-evacuate-indians-foreigners-wuhan-japan-ship-1650379-2020-02-27|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* On 1 February, India evacuated 324 people which included three minors, 211 students and 110 working professionals from Wuhan region on its first [[Air India]] flight [[Emergency evacuation|evacuation]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://scroll.in/video/951794/its-empty-air-india-crews-first-reaction-to-landing-in-wuhan-airport-in-china-for-evacuation |title='It's empty': Air India crew's first reaction to landing in Wuhan airport in China for evacuation |date=1 February 2020 |access-date=4 February 2020 |work=scroll |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202175816/https://scroll.in/video/951794/its-empty-air-india-crews-first-reaction-to-landing-in-wuhan-airport-in-china-for-evacuation |archive-date=2 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/324-indians-leave-coronvirus-hit-wuhan-in-air-india-flight/article30707329.ece |title=Coronovirus outbreak: People flown in from China quarantined |date=1 February 2020 |access-date=4 February 2020 |work=The Hindu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204043752/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/324-indians-leave-coronvirus-hit-wuhan-in-air-india-flight/article30707329.ece |archive-date=4 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* On 2 February, India evacuated a second Air India flight carrying 323 Indians and seven [[Maldivians]] from Wuhan region.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/second-air-india-plane-evacuates-323-indians-from-coronavirus-hit-wuhan-in-china-2173454 |title=India Evacuates Second Batch Of 323 People From Coronavirus Epicentre |date=1 February 2020 |access-date=4 February 2020 |work=ndtv |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204103827/https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/second-air-india-plane-evacuates-323-indians-from-coronavirus-hit-wuhan-in-china-2173454 |archive-date=4 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/air-indias-2nd-flight-lands-in-delhi-with-323-indians-7-maldivians-from-coronavirus-hit-wuhan/article30718676.ece |title=Air India's 2nd flight lands in Delhi with 323 Indians, 7 Maldivians from coronavirus-hit Wuhan |date=1 February 2020 |access-date=4 February 2020 |work=The Hindu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203152544/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/air-indias-2nd-flight-lands-in-delhi-with-323-indians-7-maldivians-from-coronavirus-hit-wuhan/article30718676.ece |archive-date=3 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* On 7 February, [[Brazil]] evacuated 34 Brazilians, four Poles, a Chinese and an Indian national from Wuhan by Air Force planes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/2020/02/07/avioes-decolam-de-wuhan-na-china-com-40-passageiros-repatriados-ao-brasil-e-a-polonia.ghtml|title=Avi\u00f5es decolam de Wuhan, na China, com 40 passageiros repatriados ao Brasil e \u00e0 Pol\u00f4nia|website=G1|access-date=7 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208144310/https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/2020/02/07/avioes-decolam-de-wuhan-na-china-com-40-passageiros-repatriados-ao-brasil-e-a-polonia.ghtml|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* On 27 February, [[Indian Air Force]] evacuated 112 people from Wuhan, which included 76 Indian nationals and 36 foreign nationals (23 nationals from Bangladesh, 6 from China, 2 each from Myanmar and Maldives and one each from South Africa, USA and [[Madagascar]]). This was the third evacuation flight sent by India to Wuhan. India also provided 15 tonnes of medical assistance comprising masks, gloves and other emergency medical equipment to China through the same IAF flight.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Chaudhury|first=Dipanjan Roy|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-india-brings-back-36-foreigners-and-76-nationals-from-wuhan/articleshow/74328899.cms|title=Coronavirus: India brings back 36 foreigners and 76 nationals from Wuhan|date=27 February 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/iaf-air-india-flights-evacuate-indians-foreigners-wuhan-japan-ship-1650379-2020-02-27|title=IAF evacuates 112 from coronavirus-hit Wuhan; Air India repatriates Indian crew from cruise ship|last=DelhiFebruary 27|first=India Today Web Desk New|last2=February 27|first2=2020UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=28 February 2020|last3=Ist|first3=2020 09:34|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228162735/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/iaf-air-india-flights-evacuate-indians-foreigners-wuhan-japan-ship-1650379-2020-02-27|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day, 124 people \u2013 119 Indians and five nationals from Sri Lanka, Nepal, [[South Africa]] and [[Peru]] were evacuated from Japan by an Air India flight.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://pib.gov.in/PressReleseDetail.aspx?PRID=1606408|title=Press Information Bureau|website=pib.gov.in|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 10 March, Indian Air Force's [[Boeing C-17 Globemaster III|C-17 Globemaster]] transport aircraft evacuated 58 Indian pilgrims from Iran, the flight took off from [[Hindan Air Force Station|Hindon Air Base]], [[Ghaziabad, India|Ghaziabad]] on the evening of 9 March. It also brought back another 44 passengers on 11 March from Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/indian-air-force-to-fly-c-17-globemaster-to-evacuate-indians-from-coronavirus-affected-iran-1654005-2020-03-09|title=Coronavirus: IAF's C-17 Globemaster takes flight from Hindon airport to evacuate Indians from Iran|last=|first=|last2=|first2=|date=9 March 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 March 2020|last3=|first3=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-58-indians-evacuated-from-virus-hit-iran-more-to-come-foreign-minister-2192585|title=58 Indians Evacuated From Virus-Hit Iran, More To Come: Foreign Minister|website=NDTV.com|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n* On 11 March, 83 people were evacuated from Italy by [[Air India]]. The evacuees were 74 Indian citizens and 9 US citizens of Indian origin. All evacuees were placed under quarantine for 14 days in an army facility.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-83-evacuated-from-italy-put-in-army-s-manesar-quarantine-facility-1654529-2020-03-11|title=Coronavirus: 83 evacuated from Italy, put in Army's Manesar quarantine facility|first=Manjeet |last=Negi |date=11 March 2020|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 15 March, 218 Indians from Italy were evacuated by a special Air India flight. The evacuees brought to New Delhi will be shifted to Indo-Tibetan Border Police's camp in [[Chhawla]] area where they will be quarantined for 14 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/218-indians-from-coronavirus-hit-italy-land-in-delhi-will-be-quarantined-for-14-days/story-vYY3hbhcVC6F8wCW8kScGN.html|title= 218 Indians from coronavirus-hit Italy land in Delhi, will be quarantined for 14 days|date=15 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Later, 234 Indian nationals including 131 students and 103 pilgrims were evacuated from [[Iran]] who were quarantined for 14 days in Indian Army's wellness centre facility in [[Jaisalmer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/covid-19-234-indians-stranded-in-coronavirus-hit-iran-arrive-in-india/story-HePm2t2E3DYh2fZe1DfgIM.html|title=Covid-19: 234 Indians from coronavirus-hit Iran reach India|date=15 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/indians-brought-back-from-iran-reach-jaisalmer-coronavirus-quarantine-camp/story-TQ3PGtg97fgWQ9W9c1RXoJ.html|title=Indians brought back from Iran reach Jaisalmer coronavirus quarantine camp|date=15 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 16 March, 53 Indians which includes 52 students and 1 teacher were evacuated from [[Tehran]] and [[Shiraz]] cities of Iran and were then quarantined at Army wellness centre, Jaisalmer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-another-batch-of-53-indians-from-iran-arrives-to-be-moved-to-army-facility-in-jaisalmer-1655870-2020-03-16|title=Coronavirus: Another batch of 53 stranded in Iran return home, moved to Army facility in Jaisalmer|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 22 March, 263 Indians were evacuated by [[Air India]] from [[Rome]], [[Italy]] and then were quarantined at Indo-Tibetan Border Police's camp near [[Delhi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-263-indians-evacuated-from-italy-sent-to-itbp-quarantine/articleshow/74756441.cms|title=Coronavirus: 263 Indians evacuated from Italy sent to ITBP quarantine|date=22 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 29 March, 275 Indians who were evacuated from Iran landed in [[Jodhpur]], and after preliminary screening they were quarantined at Army Wellness Centre Jodhpur.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/another-batch-of-275-indians-evacuated-from-iran-reach-jodhpur-1660895-2020-03-29|title=Another batch of 275 Indians evacuated from Iran reach Jodhpur|work=India Today|agency=PTI|date=29 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Legal action ===\nOn 9 March, an [[First information report|FIR]] was lodged against a man in [[Arunachal Pradesh]] for allegedly posting misleading information on social media regarding the outbreak.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.hindustantimes.com/india-news/man-booked-for-sharing-misleading-info-on-coronavirus/story-5F2mcz6opjqWFVya6J9eUK.html|title=Man booked for sharing misleading info on coronavirus|date=|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 16 March, the father of a woman, whose husband had tested positive for coronavirus in [[Bangalore|Bengaluru]], was booked by [[Agra]] police for allegedly misleading authorities about the whereabouts of his daughter, who was a suspected patient.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2020/03/16/india-first-coronavirus-fir-father-of-techie-wife-who-fled-agra-booked.html|title=India's first coronavirus FIR: Father of infected techie's wife booked for 'misleading authorities'|date=|work=The Week|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 18 March, a case was registered against the owner of a furniture shop at [[Bhiwandi]] in [[Thane district]], [[Maharashtra]] for issuing a misleading advertisement which claimed that mattresses sold at his shop cured the disease.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/mar/18/fir-in-maharashtras-thane-over-advertisement-of-coronavirus-curing-mattress-2118380.html|title=FIR in Maharashtra's Thane over advertisement of 'coronavirus-curing' mattress|date=|work=The New Indian Express|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Lucknow]] police lodged an [[First information report|FIR]] against [[Bollywood]] singer, [[Kanika Kapoor]] for alleged negligence in compliance of necessary directives post her return from [[London]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.hindustantimes.com/lucknow/kanika-kapoor-booked-for-negligence-after-leaving-a-trail-of-quarantined-vips/story-QfNRessOzhF4Ieqks9Zz5N.html|title=Kanika Kapoor booked for negligence after leaving a trail of quarantined VIPs|date=|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 21 March, a chemist was booked for allegedly selling [[N95 mask]]s at over four times higher than the fixed price in [[Himachal Pradesh]]'s [[Kangra district]].<ref>{{cite news |title=FIR against Chemist for Selling N95 Masks at Four Times of Fixed Price in HP's Kangra |url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/fir-against-chemist-for-selling-n95-masks-at-four-times-of-fixed-price-in-hps-kangra-2545919.html |accessdate=28 March 2020 |publisher=News18 India |date=28 March 2020}}</ref> On 24 March, a 54-year-old man from [[Ernakulam]], who landed from [[Chennai]] at the [[Cochin International Airport]] on 23 March, was arrested for refusing to follow instructions given by doctors.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/coronavirus-india-latest-updates-almost-all-of-india-is-in-lockdown/articleshow/74785133.cms|title=Domestic air passenger arrested in Kochi for refusing to follow norms to check coronavirus spread|date=|work=Times of India|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> A case was registered against a [[Coca-Cola]] plant in [[Himachal Pradesh]] for operating in violation of lockdown order.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/fir-against-coca-cola-factory-in-hp-for-violation-of-coronavirus-lockdown-11585029163888.html|title=FIR against Coca Cola factory in HP for violation of coronavirus lockdown|date=|work=Livemint|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> 255 people in [[West Bengal]] were arrested for violating restriction order and were prosecuted under [[Indian Penal Code|IPC]] section 188.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.huffingtonpost.in/entry/coronavirus-west-bengal-2-new-cases_in_5e799776c5b62f90bc506514|title=2 New Coronavirus Cases In West Bengal, 255 Arrested For Violating Restriction Orders While s|date=|work=Huffington Post|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> A man was arrested for hosting a party during the lockdown in [[Andhra Pradesh]]'s [[West Godavari district]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsmeter.in/man-arrested-for-hosting-party-during-lockdown-in-aps-west-godavari-district/|title=Man arrested for hosting party during lockdown in AP's West Godavari district|last=Network|first=Newsmeter|date=24 March 2020|website=NewsMeter|language=en-US|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> Hyderabad traffic police seized 2,480 vehicles for violating the lockdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsmeter.in/hyderabad-traffic-police-seize-2480-vehicles-for-violating-lockdown/|title=Hyderabad traffic police seize 2,480 vehicles for violating lockdown|last=Network|first=Newsmeter|date=24 March 2020|website=NewsMeter|language=en-US|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> On 25 March, two people were booked under sections 353, 188 and other relevant provisions of the [[Indian Penal Code|IPC]] and [[Disaster Management Act, 2005]] for allegedly abusing and manhandling policemen during the lockdown at [[Kalyan]] in [[Maharashtra]]'s [[Thane district]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/maha-two-booked-for-manhandling-cops-during-covid19-lockdown/1779337|title=Maha: Two booked for manhandling cops during COVID-19 lockdown|date=|work=Outlook India|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 March, [[Delhi]] police arrested a 40-year-old man and seized his [[scooty]] for allegedly calling a [[Northeast India|northeastern]] woman \"coronavirus\" and spitting [[paan]] at her.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.ndtv.com/delhi-news/man-arrested-for-calling-northeast-woman-corona-spitting-on-her-delhi-police-2200793|title=Man Arrested For Calling Northeast Woman \"Corona\", Spitting On Her: Delhi Police|date=|work=NDTV|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 27 March, an [[Infosys]] employee from [[Bengaluru]] was arrested for his social media post that encouraged people to venture out and spread the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Infosys Employee Arrested Over \"Spread-The-Virus\" Post, Company Sacks Him |url=https://www.ndtv.com/karnataka-news/coronavirus-lockdown-india-infosys-employee-arrested-over-spread-the-virus-post-company-sacks-him-2201926 |accessdate=28 March 2020 |publisher=NDTV |date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Three people were arrested for circulating a fake audio clip which suggested that 59 fresh cases were reported in [[Nagpur]], [[Maharashtra]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Three arrested for making fake audio clip of Nagpur reeling with '59 positive' cases |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/three-arrested-for-making-fake-audio-clip-of-nagpur-reeling-with-59-positive-cases/articleshow/74841275.cms |accessdate=27 March 2020 |publisher=Times of India |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> A 29-year-old woman was arrested in [[Kolkata]] for allegedly spreading rumours related to the outbreak by posting fake news on social media.<ref>{{cite news |title=In Kolkata, woman arrested for spreading coronavirus rumours on social media |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/woman-arrested-in-kolkata-for-spreading-rumours-on-coronavirus-on-social-media/story-Oo9qJYBQhOwcAfN9HwUjTN.html |accessdate=28 March 2020 |publisher=Hindustan Times |date=28 March 2020}}</ref> [[Patna]] police arrested three policemen for allegedly shooting at a driver of a vehicle carrying potatoes and asking for a bribe of {{INRConvert|5000||lk=|year=2020}}.<ref>{{cite news |title=Covid-19 lockdown: Three Bihar policemen arrested for shooting at van driver, demanding bribe |url=https://scroll.in/latest/957396/covid-19-lockdown-three-bihar-policemen-shoot-at-van-driver-demand-bribe-arrested |accessdate=28 March 2020 |publisher=Scroll |date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== State government response ===\n{{Main|Indian local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic}}\nState governments took various measures to contain the spread of the virus.\n\n===International relations===\nOn 26 February, India sent 15 tons of [[Surgical mask|masks]], gloves and other emergency medical equipment by an Indian Air Force jet to [[China]]. The medical supplies sent to China include one hundred thousand masks, five hundred thousand pairs of gloves, 75 infusion pumps, and 30 internal feeding pumps.<ref>{{cite web |title=India provided 15 tonnes of medical supplies worth Rs 2.11 crore to coronavirus-hit China: Government| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-provided-15-tonnes-of-medical-supplies-worth-rs-2-11-crore-to-coronavirus-hit-china-government/amp_articleshow/74693578.cms|website=Economic times|author=|date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, Modi proposed that [[SAARC]] nations jointly fight the pandemic, an idea that was welcomed by the leaders of [[Nepal]], [[Maldives]], [[Sri Lanka]] [[Bhutan]], [[Bangladesh]], and [[Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/pm-modi-bats-for-joint-saarc-strategy-to-fight-coronavirus-gets-prompt-support-from-neighbours/articleshow/74616095.cms|title=PM Modi bats for joint Saarc strategy to fight coronavirus, gets prompt support from neighbours |last=13 Mar|agency=PTI |last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=14 March 2020|last3=Ist|first3=20:51}}</ref> On 15 March, after a video conference of [[SAARC]] leaders,<ref name=\":5\"/> he allocated {{INRConvert|74|c|lk=on|year=2020}} of funds classified as COVID-19 Emergency Fund for the SAARC countries.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOn 4 April, the Government of India banned the export of [[hydroxychloroquine]] \"without any exception\", in order to stockpile supplies for domestic use.<ref name=\"Caravan HCQ\">\nVidya Krishnan, [https://caravanmagazine.in/healt/covid-19-hydroxychloroquine-hcq-export-ban-lifted-donald-trump Stuck in a policy haze, government takes back export ban on COVID-19 related drug HCQ], The Caravan, 7 April 2020.\n</ref>\nThe United States, which imports half its supply of the drug from India and expects to use it for treating COVID patients, grew concerned. The US President [[Donald Trump]] called Prime Minister Modi the next day, and hinted at possible retaliation in a press conference. India agreed to allow its export on \"humanitarian grounds\".<ref name=\"LA Times HCQ\">\nShashank Bengali, Vidya Krishnan, [https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-04-07/india-ship-hydroxychloroquine-u-s India says it will ship hydroxychloroquine to U.S. after Trump threatens retaliation], Los Angeles Times, 7 April 2020.\n</ref>{{refn|group=note|Apart from the US, India had outstanding orders for Hydroxychloroquine from some 30 countries, including Brazil, Spain, France, UK, Germany, Australia, the Gulf countries and the SAARC neighbours. The decision to partially lift the ban preceded President Trump's comment on possible retaliation.<ref>Nayanima Basu, [https://theprint.in/diplomacy/india-partially-lifts-ban-on-export-of-hydroxychloroquine-hours-after-trumps-threat/396792/ India partially lifts ban on export of hydroxychloroquine to help US, others fight Covid-19], The Print, 7 April 2020.</ref>}}\n\nOn 11 April, India sent a team of 15 doctors and health care professionals to [[Kuwait]] to assist in its fight against coronavirus, following a telephone conversion between prime minister Modi and the Kuwaiti prime minister [[Sabah Al-Khalid Al-Sabah]]. Kuwait was facing 1,154 COVID-19 cases at this time.<ref>[https://www.livemint.com/news/india/covid-19-india-sends-a-team-of-doctors-medical-staff-to-kuwait-11586618621306.html Covid-19: India sends a team of doctors, medical staff to Kuwait], livemint, 11 April 2020.</ref><ref> [https://gulfnews.com/world/gulf/kuwait/rapid-response-team-from-india-reaches-kuwait-to-combat-covid-19-1.1586619932751 Rapid response team from India reaches Kuwait to combat COVID-19], Gulf News, 11 April 2020.</ref>\n\n===Aarogya Setu===\nThe Indian Government launched a smart phone application called '''Aarogya Setu''' to help in \"contact tracing and containing the spread\" of COVID-19 pandemic in the nation. The [[World Bank]] lauded the early deployment of such technology to combat the pandemic. Global technology giants Apple and Google announced on 11 April, that they will taken up the building of software for smartphones which would help in contact tracing, just as the Aarogya Setu application does.<ref> https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/with-aarogya-setu-app-india-has-shown-the-way-says-world-bank/articleshow/75113753.cms </ref><ref> https://m.economictimes.com/tech/software/how-to-use-aarogya-setu-app-and-find-out-if-you-have-covid-19-symptoms/articleshow/75023152.cms </ref>\n\n== Testing and countermeasures ==\n=== Testing ===\n[[File:Covid-testing kiosk.jpg|thumb|A sample collection kiosk for COVID-19 testing in Kerala]]\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float:right; clear:right;\"\n|+Summary of test results\n!Samples tested\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |217,554\n|-\n!Tests per 1 million people\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |{{formatnum:{{#expr:217554/1352642280*1000000 round 0}}}}\n|-\n!Tested individuals\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |202,551\n|-\n!Tested positive\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |9,341\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:right;\" |{{As of|2020|April|12}}<ref name=\"ICMRtests\"/>\n|}\nThe Union Health Ministry's war room and policy making team in New Delhi consists of the ministry's Emergency Medical Response Unit, the [[Integrated Disease Surveillance Programme|Central Surveillance Unit (IDSP)]], the [[National Centre for Disease Control|National Centre for Disease Control (NCDC)]] and experts from three government hospitals.<ref name=\":0a\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/coronavirus-war-room-india-in-mission-mode/story-NHYzzcrmFUDg19lPUSbjVM.html|title=How conference hall at health ministry emerged as coronavirus-control war-room|last=Sharma|first=Sanchita|date=5 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307150726/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/coronavirus-war-room-india-in-mission-mode/story-NHYzzcrmFUDg19lPUSbjVM.html|archive-date=7 March 2020|accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref> They are part of policy decisions to decide how coronavirus should be tackled in the country.<ref name=\":0a\" /> A cluster-containment strategy is mainly being adopted, similar to how India contained previous epidemics, as well as \"breaking the chain of transmission\".<ref name=\":0a\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2020/03/13/delhi-declares-coronavirus-as-epidemic-as-india-reports-first-death-from-infection.html|title=Delhi declares coronavirus as epidemic as India reports first death from infection|website=The Week|language=en|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/04/812013578/covid-19-we-can-push-this-virus-back-who-leader-says-of-coronavirus|title=COVID-19: 'We Can Push This Virus Back,' WHO Leader Says Of Coronavirus|website=NPR.org|language=en|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> 15 labs across India led by the [[National Institute of Virology|National Institute of Virology (NIV), Pune]], are testing for the virus, with more labs being trained.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Biswas|first=Soutik|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51747932|title=Is India prepared for a coronavirus outbreak?|date=7 March 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=7 March 2020|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307055219/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51747932|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 14 March [[Viral Research and Diagnostic Laboratories#Labs|65 labs]] were named capable for testing for the virus (though as of 17 March not all are fully functional).<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=We need to ramp up testing facilities|date=17 March 2020|work=The Times of India (print edition)|access-date=|url-status=live|page=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/pulse/956110/is-india-testing-enough-for-coronavirus-cases|title=Is India testing enough for coronavirus cases?|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus test in India: Complete list of testing sites for coronavirus in India|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/52-testing-sites-for-coronavirus-in-india/articleshow/74547684.cms |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, scientists at the National Institute of Virology isolated a strain of the novel coronavirus. By doing so, India became the fifth country to successfully obtain a pure sample of the virus after China, Japan, Thailand and the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/fewer-cases-but-india-becomes-5th-country-to-isolate-coronavirus/articleshow/74620323.cms|title=Coronavirus cases in India: Fewer cases, but India becomes 5th country to isolate coronavirus {{!}} India News - Times of India|first=N|last=Durgesh|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Indian Council of Medical Research]] (ICMR) said that isolation of the virus will help towards expediting the development of drugs, vaccines and rapid diagnostic kits in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/covid-19-india-becomes-5th-country-globally-to-isolate-virus-strain-11584102221498.html|title=India becomes fifth country to isolate Covid-19 virus strain|last=Sharma|first=Neetu Chandra|date=13 March 2020|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> NIV has shared two SARS-CoV-2 genome sequences with [[GISAID]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Prasad|first=R.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/science/coronavirus-india-shares-two-sars-cov-2-genome-sequences/article31007227.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} India shares two SARS-CoV-2 genome sequences|date=7 March 2020|work=The Hindu|access-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307064132/https://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/science/coronavirus-india-shares-two-sars-cov-2-genome-sequences/article31007227.ece|archive-date=7 March 2020|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nInitially, the labs tested samples only from those with a travel history to 12 countries designated as high-risk, or those who have come in contact with anyone testing positive for the coronavirus, or showing symptoms as per the government guidelines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/testing-must-be-done-on-war-footing/story-4gI2HWQ2WLhVLFOm5rsioM.html|title=India needs a more aggressive testing regimen for coronavirus: Experts|date=15 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://caravanmagazine.in/health/public-health-experts-raise-concerns-about-india-restricted-testing-covid-19|title=Public-health experts raise concerns about India's restricted testing for COVID-19|last=Krishnan|first=Vidya|website=The Caravan|language=en|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> On 20 March, the government decided to also include all pneumonia cases, regardless of travel or contact history after the country saw a sharp increase in the number of cases.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/coronavirus/covid-19-india-test-coronavirus-pneumonia-6324733/|title=Covid-19 testing in India extended to all pneumonia cases: Govt|date=21 March 2020|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> The first and second confirmatory tests for the virus has been made free by the government.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/first-and-second-confirmatory-tests-for-covid-19-are-free-sanjeeva-kumar20200315173303/|title=First and second confirmatory tests for COVID-19 are free: Sanjeeva Kumar|website=ANI News|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 9 April, ICMR further revised the testing strategy and allowed testing of the people showing symptoms for a week in the hotspot areas of the country, regardless of travel history or local contact to a patient.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-testing-strategy-revised-in-india-ambit-widened-2209126|title=Coronavirus Testing Strategy Revised In India, Ambit Widened|website= NDTV.com|date=2020-04-09|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> As of 14 March, the [[National Institute of Virology]] (NIV) has tested around 5,900 samples from individuals across the country. The number of tests per million in the country was 5 as of 14 March. In comparison, it is 26 in US, 76 in Japan, 1,005 in Italy and 4,099 in South Korea.<ref name=\":3\" /> There are concerns that testing for the virus in India is being inadequately conducted and the need for ramping up the scale of testing is a necessity to understand the real scope of the number of people affected.<ref name=\":9\">{{cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/latest/trends/india-grossly-under-tested-on-coronavirus-urgent-steps-needed-to-ramp-up-testing/story/398488.html|title=India grossly under-tested on coronavirus; urgent steps needed to ramp up testing|last=Sharma|first=Kumar|date=17 March 2020|website=[[Business Today (India)|Business Today]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Ministry of Health said that only 10 per cent of test capacity has been utilised per day as of 15 March,<ref name=\":6\" /> claiming that the amount of tests were enough. However experts thought they were not, saying that [[Transmission (medicine)|community transmission]] may go undetected without adequate testing.<ref name=\":3\" /> They also wanted to add more testing centres by inclusion of private laboratories.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> In mid-March the government authorised accredited private labs to test for the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/accredited-private-labs-to-be-allowed-to-test-for-covid-19/articleshow/74664414.cms|title=Coronavirus testing lab: Accredited private labs to be allowed to test for Covid-19|last=Jha|first=Durgesh Nandan|date=17 March 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nTesting for community transmission began on 15 March. 65 laboratories of the Department of Health Research and the [[Indian Council of Medical Research]] (DHR-ICMR) have started testing random samples of people who exhibit flu-like symptoms and samples from patients without any travel history or contact with infected persons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/icmr-to-test-for-community-transmission-of-covid-19-6313521/|title=ICMR to test for community transmission of Covid-19|date=14 March 2020|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Thacker|first=Teena|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/will-know-if-indias-going-through-community-transmission-icmr/articleshow/74663239.cms|title=Will know if India is going through community transmission of Covid-19: ICMR|date=17 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> As of 18 March, no evidence of community transmission was found after results of 500 random samples tested negative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-still-in-phase-2-of-coronavirus-outbreak-confirms-icmr/articleshow/74673951.cms|title=Covid-19 outbreak: No evidence of community transmission, says ICMR|date=18 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> Between February 15 and April 2, 5,911 SARI (Severe Acute Respiratory Illnesses) patients were tested throughout the country of which, 104 tested positive (1.8%) in 20 states and union territories. About 40% of the identified patients did not have travel history or any history of contact with a positive patient.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-india-second-icmr-report-random-sampling-test-results-shows-possible-community-transmission-1665290-2020-04-10|title=Coronavirus: Second ICMR report on random sampling test results shows possible community transmission|last=Sharma|first=Milan|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The ICMR advised to prioritise containment in the 36 districts of 15 states which had reported positive cases among SARI patients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/icmr-suggests-containment-36-districts-after-many-with-respiratory-infection-test-covid19-positive-1665278-2020-04-10|title=ICMR suggests containment in 36 districts after many with respiratory infection test Covid-19 positive|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, The [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare|Union Ministry of Health]] has decided to allow private pathology labs to test for COVID-19. The ministry official said that only the government lab is allowed to test the coronavirus. By allowing private labs, the work of testing can be doubled. The ministry said that about 60 private labs may soon be allowed for this.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web |title=Metropolis among private labs short-listed for coronavirus testing| url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/metropolis-among-private-labs-short-listed-for-coronavirus-testing/article31090208.ece|website=thehindu|author=}}</ref> Once set up, a person can get COVID-19 test done at a private lab after a qualified physician in a government facility recommends it.<ref>{{cite web |title=Health Ministry to allow accredited private labs to conduct tests for coronavirus|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/health-ministry-to-allow-accredited-private-labs-to-conduct-tests-for-coronavirus-814595.html|website=Deccan herald|author=|date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The ICMR has appealed to the private labs to offer the tests for free as the government labs do.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nOn 18 March, A top health ministry official said that a Swiss private company named [[Roche Diagnostics]] has been given the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) emergency approval to conduct tests for coronavirus. The Indian regulator has given them a licence to conduct diagnostic tests of the virus on 17 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Roche Diagnostics India first private firm to get COVID-19 test approval| url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/india/story/roche-diagnostics-india-first-private-firm-to-get-covid-19-test-approval-1656965-2020-03-18|website=indiatoday|author=}}</ref> The [[Drug Controller General of India]] (DCGI) was assessing giving another firm license while two Indian diagnostic companies have also sought approval for the coronavirus testing kits developed by them.<ref>{{cite web |title=Roche Diagnostics India First Private Firm to Get COVID-19 Test Approval| url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/roche-diagnostics-india-first-private-firm-to-get-covid-19-test-approval-2541493.html|website=news18|author=}}</ref> The government has also issued guidelines to cap the cost of sample testing by private labs at {{Indian Rupee|4500}}.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-test-should-not-cost-more-than-rs-4500-government-to-private-labs/articleshow/74753826.cms|title=Coronavirus test should not cost more than Rs 4,500: Government to private labs|date=22 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, Ramanan Laxminarayan, director of the [[Center for Disease Dynamics, Economics & Policy]] stated that India could be facing a \"tsunami of cases within a few weeks\" as testing increases and the reason for the low number of confirmed cases currently is due to under-testing. He also said that according to mathematical models applied in the US or UK at least 20%-60% of the population will be affected. Applying the same models in India means that at the lower end of the estimate there could be 300 million cases of which 4-8 million could be severe.<ref>{{cite web |title=India must prepare for a tsunami of cases| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-asia-india-51962813/india-must-prepare-for-a-tsunami-of-coronavirus-cases|website=www.bbc.com|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n111 additional labs for testing became functional on 21 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/111-labs-for-testing-coronavirus-will-be-functional-across-india-from-today-health-ministry-1658235-2020-03-21|title=111 labs for testing coronavirus will be functional across India from today: Health Ministry|date=|work=India Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, [[Pune]]-based [[Molecular diagnostics|molecular diagnostic]] company [[Mylab Discovery Solutions]] became the first Indian company to have received validation for its [[Reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction|RT-PCR]] tests from [[National Institute of Virology]] and the [[Indian Council of Medical Research]] (ICMR). The test takes 2.5 hours and the company is looking to price it at around {{INRConvert|1200||lk=|year=2020}}, or Rs 80,000 for a 100 test kit.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pune based Mylab becomes first Indian company to get Covid-19 test kits validated | url=https://m.economictimes.com/industry/healthcare/biotech/healthcare/pune-based-mylab-becomes-first-indian-co-to-get-its-covid-19-test-kits-validated/articleshow/74785575.cms|website=Economic times|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=India can double coronavirus test kits to 200,000 in a week, thanks to Pune-based Mylabs| url=https://www.businessinsider.in/india/news/india-can-double-coronavirus-test-kits-to-200000-in-a-week-thanks-to-pune-based-mylabs/articleshow/74787231.cms|website=Business Standard|author=}}</ref>\n\nTill April, [[Institute of Genomics and Integrative Biology]] of Delhi had developed low cost paper-strip test that could detect COVID within an hour. Each test would cost {{INRConvert|500||lk=|year=2020}} and method could fulfill India's rapid need of testing.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Srishti Choudhury|title=India's first paper-strip test for Covid-19, CSIR lab makes a breakthrough|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/india-s-first-paper-strip-test-for-covid-19-csir-lab-makes-a-breakthrough-11585832200999.html|publisher=LiveMint|date=2020-04-02|accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ICMR, 217,554 samples from 202,551 individuals have been tested as of 13 April and 9,341 individuals have been confirmed positive.<ref name=\"ICMRtests\">{{cite web|url=https://icmr.nic.in/sites/default/files/whats_new/ICMR_testing_update_13April_9PM_IST.pdf|title=SARS-CoV-2 (COVID-19) Testing: Status Update 13 April 2020 9:00 PM IST|last=|first=|date=13 April 2020|website=[[Indian Council of Medical Research]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India testing data}}\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Treatment ===\nIn Rajasthan, a combination of anti-malaria, anti-Swine flu and anti-HIV drugs resulted into recovery of three patients in March.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Combination of two anti-HIV drugs proved crucial in Coronavirus treatment, Rajasthan official|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/combination-of-two-anti-hiv-drugs-proved-crucial-in-coronavirus-treatment-rajasthan-official/articleshow/74653762.cms|newspaper=The Economic Times|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> In same month, [[Indian Institute of Chemical Technology]], [[Council of Scientific and Industrial Research]] and [[Cipla]] corporation, launched a joint venture to develop anti-COVID-19 drugs.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Health: CSIR-IICT ties up with Cipla to develop anti-COVID-19 drug|url=https://health.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/pharma/csir-iict-ties-up-with-cipla-to-develop-anti-covid-19-drug/74693465|newspaper=The Economic Times|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Another Indian firm Stempeutics plans to introduce a stem-based agent for treating COVID patients in critical situation.<ref>{{Cite news|author=K Giriprakash|title=Stempeutics ties up with a consortium of stem cell firms for end-stage Covid-19 treatment|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/stempeutics-ties-up-with-a-consortium-of-stem-cell-firms-for-end-stage-covid-19-treatment/article31290232.ece|publisher=Business Line|date=2020-04-09|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March, Pune based SciTech Park'startup incubatee introduced ''Airon'', a negative ion generator capable of reducing a room's viral load by 99.7%.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Indian Ministry of Science and Technology|title=Technology by Pune based Startup incubatee of Scitech Park to disinfect Maharashtra hospitals in Covid 19 fight|url=https://pib.gov.in/PressReleseDetail.aspx?PRID=1609269|publisher=Press Information bureau|date=2020-03-30|accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref> Following early April, funds for a  number of preventive agents were released to initiate research.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Indian Ministry of Science and Technology|title=DST approves funding for developing a gel for nasal passage as prevention for COVID 19|url=https://pib.gov.in/PressReleseDetail.aspx?PRID=1612161|publisher=Press Information bureau|date=2020-04-08|accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=Indian Ministry of Science and Technology|title=SCTIMST scientists design super absorbent material for safe management of infected respiratory secretions|url=https://pib.gov.in/PressReleseDetail.aspx?PRID=1612412|publisher=Press Information bureau|date=2020-04-09|accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, the National Task Force for COVID19 constituted by [[Indian Council of Medical Research]] recommended the use of [[hydroxychloroquine]] for treatment of COVID19 for high-risk cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abplive.com/news/india/coronavirus-india-live-updates-covid-19-confirmed-cases-nears-400-mark-narendra-modi-1180287|title=Coronavirus Live Updates: Total Count Of Positive Covid-19 Cases Jump To 562; Ten Deaths Reported So Far|last=Bureau|first=ABP News|date=22 March 2020|website=news.abplive.com|language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nVarious Indian [[Public Sector Undertaking|PSUs]], firms and start ups including [[DRDO]] and [[ISRO]], have repurposed their production lines to manufacture general PPEs, full body suits and ventilators and designing low cost or mobile medical equipment.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Nikita Prasad|title=Kudos! Indian Railways manufactures low-cost ventilator prototype for COVID-19 patients in a week\u2019s time|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/infrastructure/railways/kudos-indian-railways-manufactures-low-cost-ventilator-prototype-for-covid-19-patients-in-a-weeks-time/1919953/|publisher=Financial Express|date=2020-04-06|accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=Sharmishte Datti|title=ISRO Puts Rockets, Satellites On Hold To Develop Ventilators For Coronavirus|url=https://www.gizbot.com/news/coronavirus-effect-isro-shifts-focus-to-ventilators-066694.html|publisher=GizBot|date=2020-03-31|accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=Manu Pubby|title=Low cost, high volume products being developed; DRDO chief says scientists rising to the occasion|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/defence/local-defence-technology-helps-fight-covid-19/articleshow/74958610.cms|publisher=The Economic Times|date=2020-04-04|accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=Archana Shukla|title=Bengaluru-based Skanray aims to make 1 lakh ventilators, opens up design IP|url=https://www.cnbctv18.com/healthcare/bengaluru-based-skanray-aims-to-make-1-lakh-ventilators-opens-up-design-ip-5540741.htm|publisher=CNBC TV18|date=2020-03-23|accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref> The focus remains to attain innovation and increased production of low cost, compact and portable and multi patient ventilators. Milestones included realisation of world's smallest and cheapest ventilators.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Kundan Jha|title=\u2018India using innovation as arsenal to fight coronavirus\u2019|url=https://www.sundayguardianlive.com/business/india-using-innovation-arsenal-fight-coronavirus|publisher=The Sunday Guardian|date=2020-04-11|accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n[[Centre for Cellular and Molecular Biology]] has been working on [[genome sequencing]] of COVID 19.<ref>{{Cite news|author=M Ramesh|title=CSIR lab working on genome sequencing of Covid-19|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/science/csir-lab-working-on-genome-sequencing-of-covid-19/article31175131.ece|publisher=Business Line|date=2020-03-26|accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nPune-based [[Serum Institute of India]] is expected to apply for clinical trials of certain strains from [[Drug Controller General of India]]. As per company president [[Adar Poonawalla]], a vaccine for COVID-19 will be delivered within an year, however, it may not be effective on 20 to 30% people.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Coronavirus vaccine within a year but it won't be 100% effective|url=https://m.economictimes.com/industry/healthcare/biotech/healthcare/coronavirus-vaccine-within-a-year-but-it-wont-be-100-effective/articleshow/74704452.cms|newspaper=The Economic Times|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Of other two companies trying to develop COVID 19 vaccine in India, one being [[Zydus Cadila]], replicating [[viral vector]] and developing [[DNA vaccination|DNA plasmid vaccine]]<ref>{{Cite news|author=PB Jayakumar|title=Zydus Cadila, Serum Institute too in the hunt for coronavirus vaccine|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/mail-today/story/zydus-cadila-serum-institute-too-in-the-hunt-for-coronavirus-vaccine-1663434-2020-04-05|publisher=India Today|date=2020-04-05|accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> and other being Hyderabad based Bharat Biotech in collaboration with US based FluGen, expecting first clinical trials of a nasal vaccine by late 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Hyderabad-based biotech firm working on nasal vaccine for Covid-19|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/india/story/hyderabad-based-working-on-nasal-vaccine-for-covid-19-1662976-2020-04-03|publisher=India Today|date=2020-04-03|accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Till early second half of February, [[Serum Institute of India]] had begun animal trials of it COVID vaccine candidates<ref>{{Cite news|author=Pankaj P. Khelkar|title=Indian company first to test coronavirus vaccine on animals, human trials expected in 6 months|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/indian-company-serum-institute-india-pune-1st-develop-novel-coronavirus-vaccine-1648128-2020-02-19|publisher=India Today|date=2020-02-19|accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref> followed by [[Zydus Cadila]] in March.<ref>{{Cite news|title=The experiment of coronavirus vaccine on animals started in India, hopefully desired results will come in 4-6 months|url=https://www.inventiva.co.in/stories/inventiva/the-experiment-of-coronavirus-vaccine-on-animals-started-in-india-hopefully-desired-results-will-come-in-4-6-months/|publisher=Inventia|date=2020-04-08|accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\n===Commercial establishments===\nOn 19 March, [[Delhi]] chief minister [[Arvind Kejriwal]] announced the closure of all restaurants in the capital by 31 March in view of the ever increasing case of coronavirus. He said that there will be a ban on eating in restaurants but food delivery will continue. He also said that 20 or more people will not be allowed to unite anywhere in the state.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kejriwal govt orders Delhi restaurants to shut shop with immediate effect until 31 March| url=https://theprint.in/india/kejriwal-govt-orders-delhi-restaurants-to-shut-shop-with-immediate-effect-until-31-march/384034/|website=theprint|author=}}</ref> On 20 March, in [[Lucknow]] all restaurants, hotels, sweet shops have been closed till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: All eateries in Lucknow to be closed till March 31| url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/coronavirus-all-eateries-in-lucknow-closed-till-march-31-599973|website=indiatvnews|author=}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, Delhi government announced that all malls in [[Delhi]] will close with only vegetable, grocery and medicine shops remaining open.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/north-and-central/all-delhi-malls-to-be-closed-grocery-and-pharmacy-stores-exempted-cm-arvind-kejriwal-815679.html|title=All Delhi malls to be closed, grocery and pharmacy stores exempted: CM Arvind Kejriwal|author=|first=|date=20 March 2020|website=Deccan herald|agency=PTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=All Delhi malls to be closed, grocery and pharmacy stores exempt: Arvind Kejriwal| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/all-delhi-malls-to-be-closed-grocery-and-pharmacy-stores-exempt-arvind-kejriwal/articleshow/74728178.cms|website=Economic times|author=}}</ref> Shops in [[Mumbai]], [[Pune]] and Nagpur will remain closed till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mumbai Lockdown: Many markets and shops in lockdown mode due to Coronavirus| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/mumbai/virus-effect-many-mumbai-markets-and-shops-in-lockdown-mode/amp_articleshow/74726223.cms|website=timesofindia|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus in Maharashtra: All non-essential shops, offices to shut in Mumbai, Nagpur, Pune| url=https://m.businesstoday.in/lite/story/coronavirus-in-maharashtra-govt-orders-lockdown-of-offices-shops-as-cases-rise-to-52/1/398774.html|website=Business standard|author=}}</ref> During this period, the essential services will continue. Medical services will be available.<ref>{{cite web |title=Maharashtra CM Announces Lockdown In Mumbai, Pune, Nagpur And Pimpri\n| url=https://curlytales.com/maharashtra-cm-announces-lockdown-in-mumbai-pune-nagpur-and-pimpri/|website=curlytales|author=}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] chief minister [[Amarinder Singh]] has said that in view of coronavirus, the state has ordered lockdown till 31 March. All essential government services will continue and shops for essential goods such as food, medicines etc. will remain open.<ref>{{cite web |title=Punjab to enforce lockdown till March 31| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/punjab-to-enforce-lockdown-till-march-31/articleshow/74756389.cms|website=Economic Times|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Punjab Becomes 5th State to Declare Partial COVID-19 Lockdown as India-Wide Cases Soar to 324| url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/punjab-5th-state-to-announce-coronavirus-lockdown-as-india-wide-cases-soar-to-324-2546229.html|website=news18|author=}}</ref> The chief minister of [[Rajasthan]] [[Ashok Gehlot]] said public vehicle will be banned till 31 March, along with all the malls and shops will remain closed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Ashok Gehlot orders lockdown in Rajasthan till March 31, exempts essential services| url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/west/coronavirus-ashok-gehlot-orders-lockdown-in-rajasthan-till-march-31-exempts-essential-services-816329.html|website=Deccan Herald|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Rajasthan announces complete lockdown till March 31| url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/coronavirus-rajasthan-announces-complete-lockdown-till-march-31/article31133432.ece|website=The hindu|author=}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nOn 16 March, the union government declared a countrywide lock-down of schools and colleges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/mumbai-s-siddhivinayak-temple-to-close-entry-for-devotees-from-today-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-2195660|title=Schools Closed, Travel To Be Avoided, Says Centre On Coronavirus: 10 Points|website=NDTV.com|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 18 March, [[Central Board of Secondary Education|CBSE]] released revised guidelines for examination centres.<ref>{{cite web |title=CBSE Board advises social distancing, face masks at exam centres to prevent coronavirus| url=https://m.hindustantimes.com/education/cbse-board-advises-social-distancing-face-masks-at-exam-centres-to-prevent-coronavirus/story-anUZT6gqcnyyd52l1QZjYL.html|website=Hindustan times|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19: CBSE sets new rules for exam centres as precautionary against coronavirus spread| url=https://www.shiksha.com/articles/covid-19-cbse-sets-new-rules-for-exam-centres-as-precautionary-against-coronavirus-spread-blogId-32531|website=shikha|author=}}</ref> This includes maintaining a distance of at least 1 meter between the students taking the exam with a class not having more than 24 students. If the rooms of the examination centres are small, divide the students and make them sit in different rooms. On 19 March, [[Central Board of Secondary Education|CBSE]] and [[Joint Entrance Examination|JEE]] main examinations were postponed till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=CBSE 10th and 12th Board exams postponed due to coronavirus epidemic| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/home/education/news/cbse-10th-and-12th-board-exams-rescheduled-due-to-coronavirus-epidemic/articleshow/74698356.cms|website=timesofindia|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=CBSE Class 10, 12 Board exams postponed due to coronavirus; to be rescheduled after March 31| url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/breaking-coronavirus-outbreak-cbse-class-10-12-board-exams-postponed-599404|website=indiatv|author=}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, [[Maharashtra]] government cancelled examinations for class 1 to 8 and promoted the students to the next classes, whereas examinations for class 9 and 11 were postponed till 15 April.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/covid-19-mumbai-maharashtra-class-1-to-8-exams-cancelled-students-promoted-next-classes-coronavirus-599929|title=COVID-19: Maharashtra govt cancels Classes 1 to 8 exam; Class 9th, 11th exams to be conducted post April 15|date=|work=India TV|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Madhya Pradesh Board of Secondary Education]] postponed board exams for class 10 and 12 and asked school principals to promote or detain students of class 5 to 8 based on their performance in previous terms.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/home/education/news/mp-board-10th-12th-exams-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-exams-of-classes-5-8-cancelled/articleshow/74715064.cms|title=MP Board 10th & 12th exams postponed due to Coronavirus|date=|work=Times of India|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Board exams of class 10 and 12 were postponed in [[Kerala]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/covid-19-kerala-postpones-class-10-class-12-board-exams-a-first-for-the-state-11584692189302.html|title=COVID-19: Kerala postpones Class 10, Class 12 board exams, a first for the state|date=|work=Livemint|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Assam]] government cancelled all exams till 31 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/education/article/assam-government-cancels-all-exams-till-march-31-due-to-covid19-new-dates-to-be-out-soon/567181|title=Assam Government cancels all exams till March 31 due to COVID19, new dates to be out soon|date=|work=Times Now News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Union Public Service Commission]] also postponed the interview for the [[Civil Services Examination]] 2019 to be held from 23 March to 3 April.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus outbreak: UPSC defers civil services interviews| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-outbreak-upsc-defers-civil-services-interviews/amp_articleshow/74732283.cms|website=Economic|author=}}</ref> The [[Secondary School Certificate|SSC]] exams in Tamil Nadu and Puducherry were postponed to 15 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/education/tn-ssc-10th-board-exams-postponed-in-tamil-nadu-puducherry-due-to-coronavirus/story-m5Q0J50KHnlM40bJ88eS4O.html|title=TN SSC 10th board exams postponed in Tamil Nadu, Puducherry due to coronavirus|date=21 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Economy===\n{{main|Economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n{{see also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nOn 2 March, the [[BSE SENSEX]] witnessed a [[flash crash]] on the back of Union Health Ministry's announcement of two new confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sensex witnesses flash crash on 2 new coronavirus cases in India; over 340 stocks hit 52-week low |url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/markets/sensex-witnesses-flash-crash-on-2-new-coronavirus-cases-in-india-over-340-stocks-hit-52-week-low-4993351.html |accessdate=3 March 2020 |work=Moneycontrol}}</ref> A UN report estimated a trade impact of US$348 million on India due to the outbreak, making India one of the 15 worst affected economies across the world.<ref>{{cite news |title=Trade impact of Coronavirus epidemic for India estimated at 348 million dollars: UN report |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/foreign-trade/trade-impact-of-coronavirus-epidemic-for-india-estimated-at-348-million-dollars-un-report/articleshow/74487020.cms |accessdate=5 March 2020 |work=Economic Times}}</ref> [[Asian Development Bank]] estimated that the outbreak could cause losses of up to US$29.9 billion to India's economy.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus outbreak may cost Indian economy $29.9 bn: ADB |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-outbreak-in-india-could-cost-the-economy-29-9-billion-adb-11583480504316.html |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Livemint}}</ref> On 9 March, The [[BSE SENSEX]] closed 1,942 points lower at 35,635 while the [[NIFTY 50|NSE Nifty 50]] was down by 538 points to 10,451.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Raj|first=Shubham|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/monday-mayhem-may-mark-worst-day-for-sensex-5-factors-causing-this-crash/articleshow/74547106.cms|title=Monday mayhem marks worst day for Sensex: 5 factors causing this crash|date=9 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, Indian stock markets suffered their worst crash since June 2017 after WHO's declaration of the outbreak as a pandemic. The BSE SENSEX dropped 8.18 per cent or 2,919 points which was its lowest in 23 months while the [[NIFTY 50|NIFTY]] dropped 9 per cent or 950 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/business/bse-sensex-today-live-market-news-sensex-ends-2919-points-lower-nifty-at-9590-amid-coronavirus-fear-2193751|title=Sensex Crashes 2,919 Points, Nifty Ends At 9,590 In Worst Day For Markets Ever|website=NDTV.com|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April, the coal mining operations of [[Singareni Collieries Company]] in Telangana wer halted due to the threat of the COVID pandemic.<ref>\nGali Nagaraja,\n[https://thewire.in/rights/covid-19-singareni-underground-opearations-halt COVID-19 Threat: Underground Operations at Singareni Coal Mines Come to a Halt], The Wire, 2 April 2020.\n</ref>\n\n=== Entertainment ===\n{{see also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema}}\nThe [[International Indian Film Academy Awards]], planned to take place on March 27, was canceled.<ref>{{cite web |title=IIFA 2020 cancelled due to coronavirus scare, fresh date to be announced soon| url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/iifa-2020-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus-scare-fresh-date-to-be-announced-soon/story-QtJSVSQyxqYIC1qIEVTvPN.html|website=Hindustan Times|author=| date= 6 March 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date= 6 March 2020}}</ref> Cinema halls were shut down by most state governments. Film bodies decided to stop the production of films, TV shows and web series till 31 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jha|first=Lata|url=https://www.livemint.com/industry/media/coronavirus-scare-in-india-all-film-tv-web-shoots-cancelled-11584279151544.html|title=Coronavirus scare in India: All film, TV, web shoots cancelled|date=15 March 2020|work=Livemint|access-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 25 March, all video streaming services, jointly decided to offer only SD quality content on cellular networks. They also decided to lower the bitrates to 480p to lower the stress on telecom networks throughout the 21-day lockdown during which there would be an unprecedented surge in mobile internet consumption since people were confined to their homes.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.economictimes.com/industry/media/entertainment/video-streaming-services-like-netflix-hotstar-suspend-hd-service-on-cellular-networks/articleshow/74807392.cms|title=Video streaming services like Netflix, Hotstar suspend HD streaming on cellular networks|date=|work=Economic Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The release of ''[[Sooryavanshi]],'' which was initially scheduled to release on 24 March, was postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/movies/bollywood/story/sooryavanshi-release-date-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-will-be-back-when-the-time-is-right-1654909-2020-03-12|title=Sooryavanshi release date postponed due to coronavirus: Will be back when the time is right|date=March 12, 2020|work=India Today|accessdate=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312173945/https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/movies/bollywood/story/sooryavanshi-release-date-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-will-be-back-when-the-time-is-right-1654909-2020-03-12|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  The [[Indian Broadcasting Foundation]] (IBF) said that four major broadcasting networks in the country have decided to waive all fees for four channels for two months. The IBF is an organisation promoting the Indian television industry.\nIn a statement, the foundation said that [[Sony Pal]], run by [[Sony]], [[Star Utsav]], run by Star India, Viacom18's [[Colors Rishtey]] run by colors and [[Zee Anmol]] run by [[Zee TV]] will be available for two months free to all viewers in the country. This offer is for all DTH and cable networks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Impact: IBF members waive all charges of four pay channels for two months| url=https://www.financialexpress.com/brandwagon/coronavirus-impact-ibf-members-waives-all-charges-of-four-pay-channels-for-two-months/1912071/|website=financial express|author=| date=29 March 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Events===\n{{see also|List of major events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nOn 6 March, the [[Border Security Force]] announced that the [[Wagah-Attari border ceremony]] would be conducted without any spectators as a precautionary measure, effective from 7 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-attari-border-ceremony-to-be-conducted-without-public-presence/amp-11583503640550.html|title=Coronavirus: Attari border ceremony to be conducted without public presence|work=Livemint|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref> The 21st [[IIFA Awards]] ceremony, which was scheduled to be held in [[Indore]] on 29 March, was postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/iifa-awards-2020-postponed-over-coronavirus-scare-new-dates-awaited-2190996?amp=1&akamai-rum=off|title=IIFA Awards 2020 Postponed Over Coronavirus Scare. New Dates Awaited|work=NDTV|accessdate=6 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306102131/https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/iifa-awards-2020-postponed-over-coronavirus-scare-new-dates-awaited-2190996?amp=1&akamai-rum=off|archive-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> The [[India Fashion Week]], scheduled to begin on 11 March in New Delhi, was put off.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indulgexpress.com/fashion/2020/mar/06/fdci-postpones-lotus-makeup-india-fashion-week-amidst-covid-19-fears-22914.html|title=FDCI postpones Lotus Makeup India Fashion Week amidst COVID-19 fears|work=Indulge Express|accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Orders, decorations, and medals of India|Padma Awards]] ceremony that was scheduled to be held on 3 April was postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/rashtrapati-bhavan-padma-awards-postponed-coronavirus-outbreak-1655564-2020-03-14|title=Upcoming Padma Awards ceremony postponed in wake of coronavirus outbreak|first=Jitendra Bahadur |last=Singh |date=14 March 2020|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Historical buildings===\nOn 17 March, All the historic buildings in the country will remain closed till 31 March. According to Union Tourism Minister [[Prahlad Patel]] the [[Taj Mahal]], [[Red Fort]] and [[Qutub Minar]] and all the National Monuments and Museums under the Archaeological Department of India will remain closed till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Outbreak: ASI shuts monuments; Taj Mahal, Hampi, Ajanta closed| url=https://www.financialexpress.com/lifestyle/travel-tourism/coronavirus-outbreak-asi-shuts-monuments-taj-mahal-hampi-ajanta-closed/1900158/lite/|website=financial express|author=| date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Statue of Unity]] will be closed to visitors till 25 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus scare in Gujarat: Sardar Patel's Statue Of Unity| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/vadodara/coronavirus-scare-in-gujarat-worlds-tallest-statue-closes/articleshow/74665311.cms|website=Times of India|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus impact: Statue of Unity closed for public; ASI shuts all monuments| url=https://m.businesstoday.in/story/coronavirus-impact-statue-of-unity-closed-for-public-asi-shuts-all-monuments/1/398477.html|website=Business standard|author=}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion}}\n\n[[File:20200402 - The Times of India - COVID-19 lockdown - Ram Temple in Bhubaneswar wears a deserted look on Ram Navami.webm|thumb|thumbtime=0:28|Temple [[Ram Mandir, Bhubaneswar|Ram Mandir]] in the heart of Bhubaneswar.]]\n\nOn 17 March, [[Mumbai]]'s [[Siddhivinayak Temple, Mumbai|Siddhivinayak Temple]] was closed till further notice.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Scare: Siddhivinayak Temple Closed For Devotees Till Further Notice| url=https://www.mumbailive.com/en/civic/siddhivinayak-temple-closed-due-to-corona-virus-46730|website=mumbailive|author=}}</ref> The next day, the [[Vaishno Devi|Mata Vaishno Devi]] pilgrimage in [[Jammu and Kashmir (union territory)|Jammu and Kashmir]] was called off.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19: Mata Vaishno Devi Shrine Board appeals pilgrims to postpone their visit to temple| url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/covid-19-mata-vaishno-devi-shrine-board-appeals-pilgrims-to-postpone-their-visit-to-temple20200317224905/|website=aninews|author=}}</ref> Apart from this, the operation of all interstate buses coming to from Jammu and Kashmir has also been stopped. Shri Mata Vaishno Devi Shrine Board (SMVDSB), issued a consultation for foreigners not to visit the temple until 28 days after their arrival in [[India]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Journey of Mata Vaishno Devi closed from today due to coronavirus| url=https://news.abplive.com/videos/news/india-journey-of-mata-vaishno-devi-closed-from-today-due-to-coronavirus-1177683|website=abplive|author=}}</ref> Entry restrictions are also in place for the aarti held at the Ganges Ghat in [[Varanasi]]; the organisers have been asked to complete the Ganga Aarti in a simple way.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Varanasi district administration bans Ganga Arti| url=https://news.abplive.com/videos/news/india-coronavirus-varanasi-district-administration-bans-ganga-arti-1177641|website=abplive|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ganga Aarti have been suspended in Varanasi in wake of Covid-19 scare| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/ganga-aarti-have-been-suspended-in-varanasi-in-wake-of-covid-19-scare/videoshow/74689654.cms|website=Economic times|author=}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, entry at [[Har Ki Pauri]], Ganga Ghat, in [[Haridwar]] was closed till 31 March. However, the aarti at Har Ki Pauri Ghat continued and shown to devotees through live streaming.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus scare: Ganga Aarti at Har ki Pauri - Haridwar administration restricts entry of visitors| url=https://www.timesnownews.com/india/article/coronavirus-scare-ganga-aarti-at-har-ki-pauri-haridwar-administration-restricts-entry-of-visitors/566472|website=timesofindia|author=}}</ref> [[Jagannath Temple, Puri]] was closed for visitors till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Covid-19 in Odisha: Puri Jagannath temple to shut from Friday |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bhubaneswar/covid-19-in-odisha-puri-jagannath-temple-to-shut-from-friday/articleshow/74708952.cms |website=Times of India |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, the [[Government of Andhra Pradesh]] closed visits to [[Venkateswara Temple, Tirumala]] until 31 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/covid-19-andhra-govt-closes-tirupati-tirumala-temple-visitors-till-march-31-120632|title=COVID-19: Andhra govt closes Tirupati Tirumala temple to visitors till March 31|website=www.thenewsminute.com|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> [[Sabarmati Ashram|Gandhi Ashram]] in [[Ahmedabad]] will also be closed to visitors from 19 to 29 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sabarmati Ashram closes doors to visitors till March 29 in light of coronavirus outbreak| url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/india/story/sabarmati-ashram-closes-doors-to-visitors-till-march-29-in-light-of-coronavirus-outbreak-1657186-2020-03-19|website=indiatoday|author=}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, [[Ramanathaswamy Temple|Rameswaram Ramanathan Swamy Temple]] in [[Tamil Nadu]] was closed till 31st. During this period, devotees were banned from entering the temple.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rameswaram Ramanathaswami Temple to remain closed till March 31| url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/rameswaram-ramanathaswami-temple-to-remain-closed-till-march-31-120032100630_1.html|website=Business standard|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Rameswaram Ramanathaswami Temple to remain closed till March 31| url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/rameswaram-ramanathaswami-temple-to-remain-closed-till-march-3120200321161022/|website=aninews|author=}}</ref> On 26 March, The [[Makkah Masjid, Hyderabad|Mecca Masjid]] of Hyderabad was closed to devotees.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19: Mecca Masjid management asks people not to come for prayers| url=https://telanganatoday.com/covid-19-mecca-masjid-management-asks-people-not-to-come-for-prayers|website=telanganatoday|author=| date=27 March 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany Christian churches have suspended in-person [[Mass (liturgy)|mass]] and have offered worship for their congregants through livestreaming, radio and television.<ref name=\"Sharad2020\">{{cite web |last1=Sharad |first1=Arpita |title=Followers catch up on church service streaming live on various platforms |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/aurangabad/followers-catch-up-on-church-service-streaming-live-on-various-platforms/articleshow/74764511.cms |publisher=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=English}}</ref> The [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Ranchi]] has appealed to the Christian faithful to aid refugees from the Indian state of [[Jharkhand]] who have been stranded since the lockdown.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gomes |first1=Robin |title=Coronavirus: Ranchi Archdiocese urges Indian Church not to abandon stranded migrants - Vatican News |url=https://www.vaticannews.va/en/church/news/2020-03/india-ranchi-archdiocese-appeal-stranded-migrants-coronavirus.html |publisher=[[Vatican News]] |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=English |date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\n{{see also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nThe 2020 [[ISSF World Cup]], which was to commence on 15 March in New Delhi, was postponed.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/virus-hits-indian-sports/articleshow/74519560.cms|title=Virus hits Indian sports|date=6 March 2020|work=Economic Times|accessdate=7 March 2020|url-status=live|agency=PTI}}</ref> The [[India Open|Indian Open]] badminton tournament which was scheduled to be held in New Delhi from 24 to 29 March was suspended until 12 April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/sports-news-coronavirus-india-open-badminton-tournament-cancelled/348760|title=Coronavirus: India Open Badminton Tournament Cancelled|last=|first=|date=14 March 2020|website=Outlook|agency=PTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIndia's [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|FIFA World Cup qualification]] match on 26 March against Qatar in [[Bhubaneswar]] was postponed.<ref>{{cite news |title=India's FIFA World Cup qualifier against Qatar postponed due to coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/football/story/india-vs-qatar-fifa-world-cup-2020-qualifiers-coronavirus-bhubaneswar-postponed-1653414-2020-03-07 |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=India Today |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308222645/https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/football/story/india-vs-qatar-fifa-world-cup-2020-qualifiers-coronavirus-bhubaneswar-postponed-1653414-2020-03-07 |archive-date=8 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[All India Football Federation]] suspended all matches of [[I-League]] and [[I-League 2nd Division]] from 15 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-in/news/coronavirus-i-league-matches-suspended-from-march-15/1ujkopnrik7ww11yarhfvjhxxj|title=Coronavirus: I-League matches suspended from March 15|last=Mukherjee|first=Soham|date=14 March 2020|website=Goal.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 14 March, the [[2020 Indian Super League Final]] was played [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiansuperleague.com/news/refund-process-for-hero-isl-2019-20-final-ticket-holders|title=Refund process for Hero ISL 2019-20 final ticket holders|website=Indian Super League|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/coronavirus-isl-final-to-be-held-behind-closed-doors/articleshow/74605305.cms|title=Coronavirus: ISL final to be held behind closed doors - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] announced that the opening of [[2020 Indian Premier League]] was postponed from 29 March to 15 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=It's official: IPL 2020 postponed to April 15 due to coronavirus |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/ipl/top-stories/its-official-ipl-2020-postponed-to-mid-april-due-to-coronavirus/articleshow/74609776.cms |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Times of India}}</ref> Later that day, it cancelled the [[South African cricket team in India in 2019\u201320|ODI matches between India and South Africa]] on 15 and 18 March, which were originally announced to be played without spectators.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rao|first=Rakesh|url=https://www.thehindu.com/sport/cricket/coronavirus-india-south-africa-series-called-off-due-to-covid-19-threat/article31061061.ece|title=India-South Africa series called off due to COVID-19 threat|date=13 March 2020|work=The Hindu|accessdate=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[World 10K Bangalore|TCS World 10 Bengaluru]], the [[IAAF Road Race Label Events|IAAF Gold Label Road Race]] scheduled to be held on 17 May was postponed to 13 September.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Biji Babu Cyriac |title=TCS World 10K Bengaluru postponed |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/more-sports/athletics/tcs-world-10k-bengaluru-postponed/articleshow/74831080.cms |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Times of India |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Transportation===\n'''Flights'''\n\n[[IndiGo]] cancelled its [[Delhi]]-[[Istanbul]] and [[Chennai]] - [[Kuala Lumpur]] flights starting 18 March to prevent international travel from [[Turkey]] and [[Malaysia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article-amp/pti-stories/indigo-cancels-flights-on-delhi-istanbul-chennai-kuala-lumpur-route-from-march18-31-120031701637_1.html|title=IndiGo cancels flights on Delhi-Istanbul, Chennai-Kuala Lumpur route from March18\u201331|author=|first=|date=17 March 2020|website=Business Standard|agency=PTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> This ban will continue till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/corona-impact-indigo-to-cancel-flights-to-turkey-malaysia/1771423|title=Corona Impact: IndiGo to cancel flights to Turkey, Malaysia|author=|first=|date=17 March 2020|website=Outlook India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> On 17 March 2020, [[GoAir|Go Air]] suspended its international flights till further notice.<ref>{{cite web |title=GoAir suspends international operations| url=https://www.livemint.com/companies/news/goair-suspends-international-operations-sends-staff-on-leave-without-pay-11584451946542.html|website=Mint|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 19 March, the [[Government of India]] announced that no [[international flight]]s will be allowed to land in India from 22 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=No international commercial flight will be allowed to land India from March 22| url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/no-international-commercial-flight-will-be-allowed-to-land-india-from-march-22-599644|website=indiatvnews|author=}}</ref> On 23 March, the [[Government of India|union government]] announced the suspension of all [[domestic flight]]s in the country starting 25 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-india-suspends-domestic-flights-from-25-march-11584962827845.html|title=Coronavirus: India suspends domestic flights from 25 March|date=|work=Livemint|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''Railways'''\n\nOn 14 March, [[Western Railway (India)|Western]] and [[Central Railways]] removed curtains and blankets from AC coaches.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Central, Western Railway withdraw curtains, blankets from AC coaches| url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/coronavirus-central-western-railway-withdraw-curtains-blankets-from-ac-coaches-120031401174_1.html|newspaper=Business Standard India| date=14 March 2020| last1=India| first1=Press Trust of}}</ref> On 17 March, [[Western Railway (India)|Western Railways]] hiked platform ticket charges from Rs. 10 to Rs. 50 across 250 stations.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.cnbctv18.com/healthcare/coronavirus-impact-railway-platform-ticket-price-hiked-to-rs-50-in-250-stations-5501061.htm|title=Coronavirus impact: Railway platform ticket price hiked to Rs 50 in 250 stations|date=|work=CNBC TV18|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Central Railway zone|Central Railways]] cancelled 23 trains.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://zeenews.india.com/india/live-updates/breaking-news-march-17-latest-updates-2269902|title=Live: Central Railways cancel 23 trains amid coronavirus scare|date=|work=Zee News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 19 March, [[Tejas Express]] running between [[Lucknow]] Junction to [[New Delhi]] and [[Varanasi]] to [[Indore]] will remain canceled till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tejas Express cancelled| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/lucknow/tejas-express-cancelled-due-to-low-occupancy-and-mass-cancellations/amp_articleshow/74696379.cms|website=timesofinfia|author=}}</ref> On 20 March, [[Delhi Metro]] was scheduled to remain closed on 22 March due to [[Janata Curfew]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Delhi Metro To Be Closed On Sunday As Part Of PM's \"Janata Curfew\" Move| url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/delhi-metro-to-remain-closed-on-sunday-as-part-of-pms-janta-curfew-move-to-fight-coronavirus-2197994|website=ndtv|author=}}</ref> On 22 March, metro services across India were suspended till 31 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Metro services shut across India till March 31 |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/metro-services-shut-across-india-till-march-31/articleshow/74760183.cms |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Economic Times |agency=PTI |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> On 21 March, in view of [[Janata curfew]], Indian Railways announced the cancellation of 3,700 trains across the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Janata curfew: 3,700 trains cancelled on Sunday| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/janata-curfew-3700-trains-cancelled-on-sunday/articleshow/74740006.cms|website=timesofindia|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Janta curfew: Railways cancels 3700 trains on Sunday| url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/covid-19-janta-curfew-railways-cancels-3700-trains-on-sunday-11584723537011.html|website=Livemint|author=}}</ref> On 22 March, the [[Government of India|union government]] cancelled all train services in the country baring goods trains, that is around 12,500 trains, and all non-essential passenger transport including interstate transport buses.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/after-trains-interstate-bus-services-suspended-till-31st-march/articleshow/74758323.cms|title=After trains, interstate bus services suspended till 31st March|date=|work=Economic Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Indian Railway Catering and Tourism Corporation|IRCTC]] suspended the bookings for 3 private trains till 30 April.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://sarkaripaper.co.in/irctc-suspends-bookings-for-its-3-private-trains-till-april-30-amid-nationwide-lockdown-due-to-coronavirus-covid-19/|title=IRCTC suspends bookings for its 3 private trains till April 30, amid nationwide lockdown due to coronavirus COVID-19|date=|work=sarkaripaper.co,in|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''Road'''\n\nOn 19 March, bus services between the cities of [[Maharashtra]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]] have been postponed from 21 to 31 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bus services between Indore and Maharashtra to be suspended| url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/bus-services-between-indore-and-maharashtra-to-be-suspended-1657078-2020-03-18|website=indiatoday|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Bus services between Indore and Maharashtra to be suspended| url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/bus-services-between-indore-and-maharashtra-to-be-suspended/1772086|website=outlookindia|author=}}</ref> [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] government imposed a ban on [[public transport]] including [[buses]], [[auto rickshaws]] and [[tempos]] from 21 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Punjab to ban public transport from March 21 |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/coronavirus/punjab-to-ban-public-transport-from-march-21/ |website=The Indian Express |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> Public transport including buses, mini buses, maxi cabs and auto services were banned in [[Srinagar]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Govt bans public transport in Srinagar to prevent spread of Coronavirus |url=https://www.greaterkashmir.com/news/srinagar/govt-bans-public-transport-in-srinagar-to-prevent-spread-of-coronavirus/ |website=Greater Kashmir |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Exodus of migrant workers===\nAn estimated 139 million migrant workers from the countryside work in India's cities and towns. With factories and workplaces shut down, they were left with  no livelihood. In the first few days of the lockdown, television screens captured long processions of migrant workers walking miles to go back to their native villages, often with families and young children on shoulders.<ref>Ismat Ara, [https://thewire.in/labour/watch-no-work-no-money-thousands-stranded-on-anand-vihar-bus-stand Watch | 'No Work, No Money': Thousands Stranded on Anand Vihar Bus Stand], The Wire, 29 March 2020.</ref> Two days later, the Uttar Pradesh government decided to arrange buses at Delhi's [[Anand Vihar ISBT|Anand Vihar bus station]] to take the migrants back to their villages. Large crowds gathered at the bus station awaiting buses. The central government issued a press statement stating that it had asked state governments to set up immediate relief camps for the migrant workers returning to their native states.<ref>[https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/fighting-covid-19-after-the-long-walk-jobless-migrants-head-home-by-bus-120032900041_1.html Fighting Covid-19: After the long walk, jobless migrants head home by bus], Business Standard, 29 March 2020.</ref> On 29 March, the government issued sweeping orders directing that the landlords should not demand rent during the period of the lockdown and that employers should pay wages without deduction. The people that violated the lockdown were to be sent to government-run quarantine facilities for 14 days.<ref>[https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/coronavirus-centre-warns-lockdown-violators-of-14-day-quarantine/article31198038.ece Coronavirus | Migrant workers to be stopped, quarantined at borders, says Centre], The Hindu, 29 March 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/coronavirus-crisis-landlords-can-not-ask-rent-from-students-workers-for-1-month/story/399551.html Coronavirus crisis: Landlords can't ask rent from students, workers for 1 month], Business Today, 29 March 2020.</ref> The [[Supreme Court of India]] agreed to hear a petition on behalf of the migrant workers on 30 March.<ref>[https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/petition-seeking-food-shelter-for-migrants-amid-coronavirus-lockdown-to-be-heard-in-supreme-court-to-2202655?pfrom=home-topstories Supreme Court To Hear Petition On Migrants Amid Lockdown Tomorrow], NDTV, 29 March 2020.</ref>\n[[File:Migrant workers stand in a queue for food at Delhi Govt school during COVID-19 Lockdown at Delhi IMG 20200331 132400.jpg|thumb|Migrant workers stand in a queue for food at Delhi Govt school during COVID-19 Lockdown at Delhi]]\n\n===Unemployment===\nThe coronavirus lockdown in India has left tens of millions of [[migrant worker]]s unemployed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: India's pandemic lockdown turns into a human tragedy |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52086274 |publisher=BBC News |date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Hungry, desperate: India virus controls trap its migrant workers |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/ajimpact/hungry-desperate-india-virus-controls-trap-migrant-workers-200402031123631.html |work=Al Jazeera |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Help==\n===Immediate relief===\nOn 19 March, [[Kerala]] [[Chief minister (India)|chief minister]] (CM) [[Pinarayi Vijayan]] announced a stimulus package of {{INRConvert|20000|c|lk=|year=2020}} to help the state overcome both the Covid-19 epidemic and economic hardship caused by it.<ref>{{cite news|last = | title = Kerala government announces Rs 20,000 crore package to tackle coronavirus outbreak| newspaper = Hindustan Times | location = | pages = | language = English | date = 20 March 2020 | url = https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/kerala-government-announces-rs-20-000-crore-package-to-tackle-coronavirus-outbreak/story-KzGvehTH4HXjhnkTBLU49M.html | access-date = 25 March 2020}}</ref> On 21 March, [[Uttar Pradesh]] CM [[Yogi Adityanath]] announced {{INRConvert|1000||lk=|year=2020}} to all daily wage labourers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Yogi Adityanath announces relief measures for UP's daily wage earners| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/yogi-adityanath-announces-relief-measures-for-ups-daily-wage-earners/articleshow/74744711.cms|website=Economic times|author=}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] CM [[Amarinder Singh]] announced {{INRConvert|3000||lk=|year=2020}} to all registered construction workers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Rs 3,000 relief for construction workers, says Punjab CM Amarinder Singh |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/coronavirus-rs-3000-relief-for-construction-workers-says-punjab-cm-amarinder-singh/articleshow/74754595.cms |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Times of India |agency=TNN |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> [[Telangana]] CM [[K. Chandrashekar Rao]] announced that white [[Ration card (India)|ration card]] holders will be provided {{INRConvert|1500||lk=|year=2020}} per family through [[ration shop]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://telanganatoday.com/telangana-lockdown-12-kg-free-rice-per-person-rs-1500-per-family-to-be-supplied-for-each-white-ration-card|title=Telangana Lockdown: 12 kg free rice per person {{INRConvert|1500||lk=|year=2020}} per family to be supplied for each white ration card|date=|work=Telangana Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 March, Union Finance Minister [[Nirmala Sitharaman]] announced an economic relief package of {{INRConvert|1.7|lc|lk=|year=2020}}, which would be a mix of food security and direct cash transfer, primarily for [[Migrant worker|migrant labourers]] and daily wage labourers.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/finance-minister-nirmala-sitharaman-live-updates-economic-relief-package-india-coronavirus-1659912-2020-03-26 | title = Coronavirus: FM Sitharaman announces package worth Rs 1,70,000 crore for poor, daily wagers | date = March 26, 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200326224738/https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/finance-minister-nirmala-sitharaman-live-updates-economic-relief-package-india-coronavirus-1659912-2020-03-26 | archive-date = 26 March 2020 | url-status = live | access-date = 26 March 2020 }}</ref> [[Prime Minister's National Relief Fund]] received several donations - {{INRConvert|3381|c|lk=|year=2020}} from the [[Central Reserve Police Force]],<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/covid19-crpf-contributes-rs-3381-cr-fund-from-jawans-oneday-salary/1781014|title=COVID-19: CRPF contributes Rs 33.81 cr fund from jawan''s one-day salary|date=|work=Outlook|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |title=Sachin Tendulkar donates Rs 50 lakh for COVID 19 relief fund |url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/sachin-tendulkar-donates-rs-50-lakh-for-covid-19-relief-funds/articleshow/74839144.cms |accessdate=27 March 2020 |publisher=Mumbai Mirror |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> and a month's salary from [[Vice President of India|Vice President]] [[Venkaiah Naidu]], [[Law Minister]] [[Ravi Shankar Prasad]] and [[Nationalist Congress Party|NCP]]'s [[Member of parliament (India)|MP]]<nowiki/>s.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/venkaiah-naidu-ravi-shankar-prasad-donate-their-one-month-s-salary-in-fight-against-covid-19-818322.html|title=Venkaiah Naidu, Ravi Shankar Prasad donate their one month's salary in fight against COVID-19|date=|work=Deccan Herald|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/ncp-legislators-to-donate-salary-for-coronavirus-relief/1781131|title=NCP legislators to donate salary for coronavirus relief|date=|work=Outlook|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Nationalist Congress Party|NCP]] President [[Sharad Pawar]] announced that his party's [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLAs]] would donate their one month's salary to Maharashtra CM's Reief Fund.<ref name=\"auto\"/> [[Reserve Bank of India|RBI]] Governor [[Shaktikanta Das]] permitted all banks to provide a [[Moratorium (law)|moratorium]] on all [[loans]] for three months without having to worry about [[Non-performing asset|NPAs]] and keeping their books healthy. He also laid down various measures for injecting {{INRConvert|3.74|lc|lk=|year=2020}} [[liquidity]] into the system.<ref>{{cite news |title=RBI Governor Shaktikanta Das: Interest rates cut by 75 bps, EMIs put on hold |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/rbi-governor-shaktikanta-das-live-rate-cut-expected-11585280776382.html |accessdate=27 March 2020 |publisher=Livemint |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> Saibaba Sansthan Trust, [[Shirdi]] donated {{INRConvert|51|c|lk=|year=2020}} to [[Maharashtra]] [[Chief minister (India)|CM]]'s relief fund.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shri Saibaba Sansthan Trust donates Rs 51 cr to combat COVID-19| url=https://www.bignewsnetwork.com/news/264441730/shri-saibaba-sansthan-trust-donates-rs-51-cr-to-combat-covid-19|website=bignewsnetwork|author=| date=27 March 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The Union Government released {{INRConvert|4431|c|lk=|year=2020}} pay off the pending wages of daily wage labourers who come under MGNREGA scheme.<ref>{{cite web |title=Centre releases Rs 4431 crore to clear pending wages under MGNREGA, to pay all dues by April 10| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/economy/finance/centre-releases-rs-4431-crore-to-clear-pending-wages-under-mgnrega-to-pay-all-dues-by-april-10/articleshow/74849430.cms|website=Economic Times|author=| date=27 March 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Centre releases 4,431 crore to clear pending wages under MGNREGA| url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/coronavirus-centre-releases-4431-crore-to-clear-pending-wages-under-mgnrega/article31185034.ece/amp/|website=The Hindu|author=| date=27 March 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> In Delhi, [[Arvind Kejriwal]] announced that if a doctor, nurse or hygiene worker dies during treatment, their family will be provided Rs 1 crore.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rs 1 Crore For Families Of COVID-19 Warriors If They Die: Arvind Kejriwal| url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/arvind-kejriwal-announces-rs-1-crore-for-families-of-health-personnel-if-they-lose-their-lives-while-2204204|website=ndtv|author=| date= 1 April 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n===PM CARES Fund===\n\nOn 28 March, the [[PM CARES Fund|Prime Minister's Citizen Assistance and Relief in Emergency Situations Fund]] (PM CARES Fund) was set up to provide relief to the affected people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsonair.com/Main-News-Details.aspx?id=384047|title=People urged to donate generously in PM CARES fund; PM Modi says every contribution matters|website=newsonair.com|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Several large business groups contributed to the relief fund, including [[Tata Sons]] and [[Sir Ratan Tata Trust|Tata Trusts]] ({{INR}}1,500 crore),<ref>{{cite news |title=Tata Sons' Rs 1,000 cr top-up takes group coronavirus fund to Rs 1,500 cr - India's biggest |url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/corporate/tata-sons-announces-additional-rs-1000-crore-support-towards-coronavirus-fund/story/399506.html |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=Business Today}}</ref> [[Wipro]] and [[Azim Premji]] Foundation ({{INR}}1,125 crore),<ref>{{cite news |title=Azim Premji\u2019s foundation, Wipro commit Rs 1,125 crore as India battles with coronavirus |url=https://www.financialexpress.com/industry/azim-premjis-foundation-wipro-commit-rs-1125-crore-as-india-battles-with-coronavirus/1916114/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=Financial Express}}</ref> [[Reliance Industries]] ({{INR}}500 crore)<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Reliance Industries announces Rs 500 crore contribution to PM-CARES fund, |url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/coronavirus-outbreak-reliance-industries-announces-rs-500-crore-contribution-to-pm-cares-fund-8207531.html |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=Firstpost}}</ref> and [[Aditya Birla Group]] ({{INR}}500 crore).<ref>{{cite news |title=Covid-19: Aditya Birla Group donates Rs 500 crores in PM-CARES fund |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/covid-19-aditya-birla-group-donates-rs-500-crores-in-pm-cares-fund-1663117-2020-04-04 |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=India Today}}</ref> In addition, power and renewable energy [[Public sector undertakings in India|PSUs]] contributed a total of {{INR}}925 crore,<ref>{{cite news |title=Power, renewable energy PSUs to contribute Rs 925 cr to PM CARES fund |url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/power-renewable-energy-psus-to-contribute-rs-925-cr-to-pm-cares-fund-820963.html |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=Deccan Herald}}</ref> whereas oil and gas PSUs contributed more than {{INR}}1,031 crore.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus {{!}} ONGC, IOC and other oil cos contribute over \u20b91,031 cr to PM CARES Fund |url=https://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/coronavirus-ongc-ioc-and-other-oil-cos-contribute-over-1031-cr-to-pm-cares-fund/article31219474.ece |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\n===Gas cylinders===\nOn 26 March, finance minister [[Nirmala Sitharaman]] announced free gas cylinders for three months to beneficiaries of [[Pradhan Mantri Ujjwala Yojana]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus relief package: Free gas cylinders to Ujjwala beneficiaries for next 3 months| url=https://m.businesstoday.in/story/coronavirus-relief-package-free-gas-cylinders-to-ujjwala-beneficiaries-for-next-3-months/1/399313.html|website=Business Standard|author=}}</ref>\n\n===Rations===\nOn 21 March, [[Delhi]] [[Chief minister (India)|CM]] [[Arvind Kejriwal]] increased free ration from 5 kilograms to 7.5 kilograms for the 7.2 million people who are dependent on the [[Rationing|ration scheme]].<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 causing financial stress to poor, ration per person increased: Arvind Kejriwal| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pension-for-elderly-widows-specially-abled-being-doubled-in-view-of-covid-19-announces-arvind-kejriwal/articleshow/74747399.cms|website=economic Times|author=}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Karnataka]] CM [[BS Yediyurappa]] announced two months of free ration for all the people.<ref>{{cite web |title=Karnataka Seals its Borders, Announces Free Ration for All for 2 Months as Covid-19 Cases Reach 20| url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/karnataka-seals-its-borders-announces-free-ration-for-all-for-2-months-as-covid-19-cases-reach-20-2546273.html|website=News18|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> [[Andhra Pradesh]] CM [[Y. S. Jaganmohan Reddy]] announced free ration for the poor.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/ap-announces-lockdown-till-march-31/1776396|title=AP announces lockdown till March 31|date=|work=Outlook India|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Telangana]] CM announced that white [[Ration card (India)|ration card]] holders will be provided with 12 kilograms of free rice per person (against a monthly supply of 6 kilograms per card person) through [[ration shop]]s. On 23 March, [[Bihar]] [[Chief minister (India)|CM]] [[Nitish Kumar]] announced one month of free ration for all ration card holders.\n\nOn 25 March, Union Minister [[Prakash Javadekar]] announced that 80[[Crore|{{Nbsp}}crore]] (800[[Crore|{{Nbsp}}]]<nowiki/>million) people would be given wheat at the rate of Rs 2 per kg, and rice at Rs 3 per kg. He also said that three months ration advance would be given.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cabinet Meet Live Updates: Centre To Provide 7 Kg Ration To 80 Crore| url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/economy-finance/cabinet-meet-live-updates-government-to-announce-decisions-taken-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-nirmala-sitharaman-narendra-modi-labour-minister-workforce-financial-plan-measures-direct-benefit-transfer-gdp-economy|website=bloombergquint|author=}}</ref>\n\n===Masks and supplies===\nOn 25 March, [[Vivo (technology company)|Vivo]] said that they would be donating 1 lakh [[Medical mask|surgical]] and 5,000 [[NIOSH air filtration rating|N95 masks]] to [[Maharashtra]] government.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/industry/technology/coronavirus-outbreak-vivo-to-donate-1-lakh-protective-masks-to-maharashtra-govt-xiaomi-suspends-local-manufacturing/1909019/|title=Coronavirus outbreak: Vivo to donate 1 lakh protective masks to Maharashtra Govt, Xiaomi suspends local manufacturing|date=|work=Financial Express|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 March, former Indian [[cricketers]], [[Irfan Pathan]] and [[Yusuf Pathan]], made a donation of 4,000 masks.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/coronavirus-outbreak-former-india-cricketers-irfan-pathan-yusuf-pathan-donate-4000-masks-amidst-rising-covid-19-cases-8180911.html|title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Former India cricketers Irfan Pathan, Yusuf Pathan donate 4,000 masks amidst rising COVID-19 cases|date=|work=Firstpost|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, [[Hyundai Motor India Limited|Hyundai India]] announced placing an order for 25,000 COVID-19 Advanced Diagnostic Testing Kits from [[South Korea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://auto.ndtv.com/news/coronavirus-lockdown-hyundai-orders-advanced-covid-19-testing-kits-for-india-2202063|title=Coronavirus Lockdown: Hyundai India Orders Advanced COVID-19 Testing Kits From Korea|last=|first=|date=|website=CarandBike|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIndia hasn't experienced [[Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 related shortages]] so far.\n\n{{As of|2020|April|3}}, [[Indian Railways]] had produced total of 2[[Lakh|{{Nbsp}}lakh]] (200,000) masks and 25,000 sanitisers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Railway workers produce sanitisers & masks| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/hyderabad/rly-workers-produce-sanitisers-masks/articleshow/74957651.cms|website=timesofindia|author=| date= 3 April 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date= 3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Situation==\n===Panic buying===\n{{See also|Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nHyderabad witnessed panic buying throughout 20 and 21 March.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nanisetti |first1=Serish |title=Panicky shoppers clear out grocery shops |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/panicked-shoppers-clear-out-grocery-shops/article31131827.ece |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Panic buying of milk and other dairy products was also reported.<ref>{{cite news |title=No need for panic buying of milk |url=https://ahmedabadmirror.indiatimes.com/ahmedabad/others/no-need-for-panic-buying-of-milk/articleshow/74754049.cms |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Ahmedabad Mirror |date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=No need for panic buying of milk, other dairy products, says Amul MD |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/no-need-for-panic-buying-of-milk-other-dairy-products-says-amul-md/articleshow/74750809.cms |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Economic Times |agency=PTI |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> Online grocery delivery service [[Grofers]] also witnessed panic buying across states.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haq |first1=Haq |last2=Chitlangia |first2=Risha |title=Coronavirus: Govt monitors supplies to ease panic buying crunch |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/coronavirus-govt-monitors-supplies-to-ease-panic-buying-crunch/story-GKXs9RkVgkkyfcRv1ZNFuN.html |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nRetailers and consumer goods firms saw their average daily sales more than double on 19 March as consumers rushed to buy essentials ahead of [[Prime minister|PM]] [[Narendra Modi|Modi]]\u2019s address to the nation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/panic-buying-goes-a-notch-up-ahead-of-pm-modis-address/articleshow/74721852.cms|title=Panic buying goes a notch up ahead of PM Modi's address|date=|work=Economic Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> In response to this, Modi assured the citizens that there was enough food and ration supplies and advised them against panic buying.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/coronavirus-outbreak-pm-modis-9-key-messages-for-indians/articleshow/74716261.cms|title=Janata curfew, avoid panic buying, stay at home: PM Modi's 9 key messages for Indians|date=|work=Times of India|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Escaping of suspected people ===\nSeveral cases are reported across the country, where people who are suspected to have come in contact with the virus, escaped from the quarantines and hospitals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/11-coronavirus-suspects-in-navi-mumbai-traced-readmitted20200316214213/|title=11 coronavirus suspects in Navi Mumbai traced, readmitted|website=ANI News|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/5-coronavirus-suspects-escape-from-isolation-ward-of-nagpur-hospital-all-traced/story-WqxUDicK8Ejeczq1yatULM.html|title=5 coronavirus suspects escape from isolation ward of Nagpur hospital, all traced|date=14 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Chhattisgarh]], a 35 yr-old man from Tagapani, Dhamtari, who was put under isolation home by the health dept after his return from [[Tamil Nadu]], committed suicide.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chhattisgarh: Covid-19 suspect under home quarantine commits suicide in Dhamtari| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/raipur/chhattisgarh-covid-19-suspect-under-home-quarantine-commits-suicide-in-dhamtari/articleshow/74899263.cms|website=timesofindia|author=| date=31 March 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Gujarat]], 93 people have broken self-isolation rules in 10 days. FIRs have been filed against 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/in-gujarat-93-flouted-self-isolation-rules-in-10-days-firs-against-10-6327258/|title=In Gujarat, 93 flouted self-isolation rules in 10 days, FIRs against 10|last=Ghosh|first=Sohini|last2=Jha|first2=Vaibhav|date=23 March 2020|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nTwo expats in Kasaragod district, [[Kerala]], who violated quarantine measures were subjected to punitive measures, including cancellation of their Indian passports.<ref>{{cite news |title=Passports of two NRIs to be cancelled for violating quarantine orders in Kasaragod |url=https://english.mathrubhumi.com/news/kerala/passports-of-two-nris-to-be-cancelled-for-violating-quarantine-orders-in-kasaragod-1.4640844 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Mathrubhumi |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, A case of 26-year-old woman suspected of being infected with the corona virus has been reported to have fled the hospital in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]. The woman, who hails from Mohali, recently returned from the US and was brought to a government hospital in [[Chandigarh]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus in India: Mohali woman who travelled to UK tests positive| url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-in-india-mohali-woman-who-travelled-to-uk-tests-positive-1657743-2020-03-20|website=indiatoday|author=}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March in [[Telangana]], one woman returned from [[Singapore]] has been missing, while a man who came from [[Doha]] went somewhere without telling hospital staff.<ref>{{cite web |title=Covidiots everywhere; cases of foreign returnees flouting home quarantine in rise| url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/230320/covidiots-everywhere-cases-of-foreign-returnees-flouting-home-quarant.html|website=Deccan chronicle|author=}}</ref>\n\n===Misinformation and discrimination===\n{{see also|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nDespite evidence to the contrary, a viral rumour spread online alleging that only people who eat meat were affected by coronavirus, causing \"#NoMeat_NoCoronaVirus\" to trend on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=3 March 2020|title='No Meat, No Coronavirus' Makes No Sense|url=https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|website=The Wire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303034133/https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|archive-date=3 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> To curb these rumours and combat declining sales, some poultry industry associations held a \"Chicken and Egg Mela\" in Hyderabad. Several Telangana state ministers were in attendance and ate some of the free eggs and fried chicken being distributed at the event to show their support for the industry.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=3 March 2020|title=Amid COVID-19 fears, KTR relishes chicken and eggs to dispel rumours|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/hyderabad/2020/feb/29/amid-covid-19-fears-ktr-relishes-chicken-and-eggs-to-dispel-rumours-2110056.html|website=The New Indian Express|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303034135/https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/hyderabad/2020/feb/29/amid-covid-19-fears-ktr-relishes-chicken-and-eggs-to-dispel-rumours-2110056.html|archive-date=3 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMuslim cleric Ilyas Sharafuddin has stated that [[Allah]] has punished the Chinese by unleashing Corona virus on them for their brutal crackdown on [[Uyghurs|Uighur]] Muslims. His claim was largely criticised and was condemned for passing such communal and insensitive comments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/india/article/allah-unleashed-coronavirus-on-chinese-for-persecuting-uighur-muslims-islamic-cleric-ilyas-sharafuddin/546408|title=Allah unleashed Coronavirus on Chinese for persecuting Uighur Muslims: Islamic cleric Ilyas Sharafuddin|website=www.timesnownews.com}}</ref>\n\nSome politicians like [[Swami Chakrapani]] and [[Suman Haripriya]] claimed that drinking cow urine and applying cow dung on the body can cure coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|title=Coronavirus: Can cow dung and urine help cure the novel coronavirus?|website=Times of India|accessdate=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206035509/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|archive-date=6 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|title=Novel coronavirus can be cured with gaumutra, gobar claims Assam BJP MLA Suman Haripriya|website=Firstpost|accessdate=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304051130/https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> WHO's chief scientist [[Soumya Swaminathan (scientist)|Soumya Swaminathan]] rubbished such claims and criticised these politicians for spreading misinformation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://swachhindia.ndtv.com/novel-coronavirus-outbreak-indias-response-and-surveillance-has-been-quite-robust-says-whos-chief-scientist-42015|title=Novel Coronavirus Outbreak: \"India's Response And Surveillance Has Been Quite Robust,\" Says WHO's Chief Scientist|website=NDTV|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51910099|title=India's coronavirus health myths fact-checked|first=Reality Check|last=team|date=19 March 2020|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\nReports of harassment of people from [[Northeast India]], which shares a border with [[Tibet Autonomous Region|Tibet]] and [[Myanmar]], in Chennai, Pune and Hyderabad have been reported following the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |title=Northeast community fends off racist attacks with coronavirus |url=https://punemirror.indiatimes.com/pune/cover-story/northeast-community-fends-off-racist-attacks-with-coronavirus-label/articleshow/74542293.cms |website=pune mirror |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=We are the Coronavirus for few Indians': says people from North-east in Hyderabad |url=https://newsmeter.in/we-are-the-coronavirus-for-few-indians-says-people-from-north-east/ |website=newsmeter |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Covid-19: Northeast India Welfare Association complains of racism |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-northeast-india-welfare-association-complains-of-racial-discrimination-in-chennai/articleshow/74733326.cms |website=timesofindia |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> Students from [[Kirori Mal College]] in Delhi, [[Tata Institute of Social Sciences]] in Mumbai and other institutes in Kolkata have also faced harassment and filed complaints with authorities.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus outbreak: NE students at TISS report incidents of 'racism, harassment' |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/coronavirus-outbreak-northeastern-students-at-tiss-report-incidents-of-racism-harassment-6272973/ |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=The Indian Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218172700/https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/coronavirus-outbreak-northeastern-students-at-tiss-report-incidents-of-racism-harassment-6272973/ |archive-date=18 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2 Students Allegedly Faced Racial Taunts Linked To Coronavirus In Kolkata |url=https://www.ndtv.com/kolkata-news/coronavirus-outbreak-2-students-allegedly-faced-racial-taunts-linked-to-coronavirus-in-kolkata-2196428 |website=ndtv |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus outbreak: NE students at TISS report incidents of 'racism, harassment' |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/coronavirus-outbreak-northeastern-students-at-tiss-report-incidents-of-racism-harassment-6272973/ |website=Indianexpress |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMisinformation that the government is spreading \"anti-corona\" drug in the country during Janata curfew went viral on social media.<ref>{{cite news |title=Is government spraying coronavirus vaccine using airplanes? No, it\u2019s fake news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/is-government-spraying-coronavirus-vaccine-using-airplanes-no-it-s-fake-news/story-QmSDrfLW8SkSghT2TUf5cK.html |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |date=20 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Film actor [[Mohanlal]] and many others shared the fake news that, the vibration generated by clapping together during Janata curfew will kill the virus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/mohanlal-many-others-share-fake-info-clapping-may-kill-virus-pib-debunks-120844 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |title=Mohanlal, many others share fake info that \u2018clapping may kill virus\u2019, PIB debunks |work=[[The News Minute]]}}</ref> One viral message says that the lifetime of coronavirus is only 12 hours and staying home for 14 hours during Janata curfew break the chain of transmission.<ref name=indiatoday1>{{cite news |last1=DelhiMarch 21 |first1=Ratna New |last2=March 21 |first2=Ratna New |last3=Ist |first3=Ratna New |title=Fact Check: Social media users give misleading twist to PM Modi's concept of 'Janta curfew' |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/fact-check/story/social-media-users-give-misleading-twist-pm-modi-janta-curfew-1658195-2020-03-21 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref> Another message claimed that observing Janata curfew will result in the reduction of coronavirus cases by 40%.<ref name=indiatoday1/> Tweet by [[Rajinikanth]] claiming that a 14-hour stay home can stop the coronavirus disease going from \"stage 2\" to \"stage 3\" was classified as misinformation and was taken down by Twitter for violating community guidelines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=ChennaiMarch 21 |first1=India Today Web Desk |last2=March 21 |first2=India Today Web Desk |last3=Ist |first3=India Today Web Desk |title=Twitter takes down Rajinikanth's Janata Curfew video for spreading misinformation |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/regional-cinema/story/twitter-takes-down-rajinikanth-s-janata-curfew-video-for-spreading-misinformation-1658282-2020-03-21 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref> [[Amitabh Bachchan]] was heavily criticised for one of his tweets, which claimed vibrations from clapping, blowing conch shells as part of Sunday's Janata Curfew would have reduced or destroyed coronavirus potency as it was \u2018[[amavasya]]\u2019, the darkest day of the month.<ref>{{cite news |title=Amitabh Bachchan deletes post on \u2018clapping vibrations destroy virus potency\u2019 after being called out |url=https://trib.al/Bcqp2dp |work=The Hindu |date=23 March 2020 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\nResidents of a village named ''Korauna'' in [[Sitapur district]] in [[Uttar Pradesh]] faced discrimination due to similarity in name of the village with the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/people-confuse-ups-korauna-for-corona-outsiders-even-wont-take-a-phone-call-from-village20200329195919|title=People confuse UP's Korauna for Corona; outsiders even won't take a phone call from village|work=ANI|date=29 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome doctors and medical workers were evicted from their homes over fears they may be carrying coronavirus. In cases reported across the country, healthcare professionals described the growing stigma they are facing from their neighbours and landlords, resulting in many being refused taxis, barricaded from their own homes, or made homeless.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/30/indian-doctors-being-evicted-from-homes-over-coronavirus-fears |title=Indian doctors being evicted from homes over coronavirus fears |work=The Guardian |date=30 March 2020 |authors=Hannah Ellis Petersen |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/bengal-kolkata-landlords-evict-medical-professionals-coronavirus-1659333-2020-03-25 |title=Kolkata landlords evict medical professionals, Resident Doctor's Association steps in |work=India Today |date=25 March 2020 |authors=Romita Datta |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, foreigners from countries such as UK, US and Israel were facing hostility, including evictions from rented homes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/foreign-tourists-face-hostility-india-coronavirus-panic-200324083648362.html|title=Foreign tourists face hostility in India amid coronavirus panic|work=[[Al Jazeera]]|date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome patients, in different quarantine facilities of [[Uttar Pradesh]], refused to eat food because the cooks in these facilities were [[Dalit]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/coronavirus-outbreak-untouchability-even-in-quarantine/cid/1764186 |title=Untouchability, even in quarantine |work=The Telegraph |date=12 April 2020 |author=Piyush Srivastava |access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://thestateindia.com/2020/04/12/patient-admitted-to-quarantine-center-in-kushinagar-refuses-to-eat-food-cooked-by-dalit |title=Patient admitted to quarantine center in Kushinagar refuses to eat food cooked by Dalit |work=The State |date=12 April 2020 |access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nMuslim gatherings organised by the [[Tablighi Jamaat]] has resulted in a large increase in COVID-19 cases, which has triggered [[Islamophobia|Islamophobic]] reactions and increased [[Communalism (South Asia)|communal tension]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-india-islam-insigh/the-religious-retreat-that-sparked-indias-major-coronavirus-manhunt-idUSKBN21K3KF |title=The religious retreat that sparked India's major coronavirus manhunt |author1=Devjyot Ghoshal |author2=Aftab Ahmed |author3=Alasdair Pal |work=Reuters |access-date=3 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403134104/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-india-islam-insigh/the-religious-retreat-that-sparked-indias-major-coronavirus-manhunt-idUSKBN21K3KF |archive-date=3 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-52147260 |title=Coronavirus: Islamophobia concerns after India mosque outbreak |date= 3 April 2020 |work=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/33017d73-d526-42ea-a2ee-b09078684534 |title=Muslims fear backlash of India's coronavirus fury |work=Financial Times |date=3 March 2020 |author1=Amy Kazmin |author2=Edward White |author3=Stefania Palma |access-date=3 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403112048/https://www.ft.com/content/33017d73-d526-42ea-a2ee-b09078684534 |archive-date=3 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Islamophobic hashtags began circulating shortly after the news broke in late March.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://time.com/5815264/coronavirus-india-islamophobia-coronajihad/ |title=It Was Already Dangerous to Be Muslim in India. Then Came the Coronavirus |work=Time Magazine |date=3 April 2020 |author=Billy Perrigo |url-status=live }}</ref> Videos falsely claiming to show members of Tablighi Jamaat spitting on police and other such allegations quickly went viral on social media.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.altnews.in/coronavirus-video-of-an-undertrial-in-mumbai-falsely-viral-as-nizamuddin-markaz-attendee-spitting-at-cop/ |title=Coronavirus: Video of an undertrial in Mumbai falsely viral as Nizamuddin markaz attendee spitting at cop |publisher=[[Altnews.in]] |date=2 April 2020 |first=Pooja| last=Chaudhuri |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.altnews.in/old-video-from-philippines-where-dilivery-boy-was-caught-taking-pieces-of-bread-from-packets-viral-with-communal-angle/ |title=Old video from Philippines shared with false claim of Muslim man spitting on bread |publisher=[[AltNews.in]] |date=9 April 2020 |first=Archit| last=Mehta |url-status=live }}</ref> A tribal boy in [[Jharkhand]] was killed over a clash over such rumours.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://scroll.in/latest/958611/jharkhand-one-dead-after-clashes-over-rumours-of-muslim-men-spitting-to-spread-coronavirus |title=Jharkhand: One dead after clashes over rumours of Muslim men spitting to spread coronavirus |work=Scroll |date=8 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In [[North West Delhi]], a mob attacked a Muslim man and told him to renounce [[Islam]] as they believed that he was part of a so-called Islamic conspiracy to spread [[SARS-CoV-2|coronavirus]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/13/coronavirus-conspiracy-theories-targeting-muslims-spread-in-india |title=Coronavirus conspiracy theories targeting Muslims spread in India |work=The Guardian |date=13 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n\nThe numbers are from data published by [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare]] on their website.{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India medical cases}} {{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India medical cases summary}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Confirmed Indian cases abroad===\nThe Ministry of External Affairs has confirmed that there are 276 confirmed Indians cases abroad as of 18 March. Most of them were in Iran (255), with others in United Arab Emirates, Italy, Kuwait, Sri Lanka, Rwanda and Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/indians-including-iran-test-positive-for-coronavirus-abroad-confirms-mea-1656927-2020-03-18|title=276 Indians including 255 in Iran test positive for coronavirus abroad, confirms MEA|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> One Indian died in Iran on 20 March 2020.<ref name=\"Iran\">{{Cite news|last=Chaudhury|first=Dipanjan Roy|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-one-indian-in-iran-dead-government-gives-local-help-to-254-others/articleshow/74722021.cms|title=Covid-19: One Indian in Iran dead, Government gives local help to 254 others|date=20 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> A 3-year-old Indian girl tested positive in Singapore on 26 March, taking total to 277.<ref name=singapore>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/india/article/3-yr-old-indian-girl-among-73-new-coronavirus-cases-in-singapore-tally-of-infected-people-crosses/569723|title=3-yr-old Indian girl among 73 new coronavirus cases in Singapore, tally of infected people crosses 600|website=www.timesnownews.com|agency=PTI|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> In Kuwait, a 46-year-old Indian died on 4 April.<ref name=\"Kuwait\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=2884135&language=en|title=Kuwait reports 1st coronavirus death, 62 new cases|website=Kuwait News Agency|date=4 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:90%;\"\n|+\nConfirmed cases of Indian nationals abroad\n!Country/Region\n!Active cases\n!Death\n!Total\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Hong Kong}}\n|1\n| style=\"color:gray;\" |0\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Iran}}\n|254\n|1<ref name=\"Iran\"/>\n|255\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Italy}}\n|5\n| style=\"color:gray;\" |0\n|5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Kuwait}}\n| style=\"color:gray;\" |0\n|1<ref name=\"Kuwait\"/>\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Rwanda}}\n|1\n| style=\"color:gray;\" |0\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|United Arab Emirates}}\n|12\n| style=\"color:gray;\" |0\n|12\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Sri Lanka}}\n|1\n| style=\"color:gray;\" |0\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Singapore}}\n|189 <\n|1  <ref>{{cite web|author=Jean Iau |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/record-142-new-covid-19-cases-in-spore-indian-national-later-confirmed-to-have |title=Record 142 new coronavirus cases in S'pore; Indian national later confirmed to have Covid-19 died while awaiting test result, Health News & Top Stories |publisher=The Straits Times |date=1970-01-01 |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n|190<ref name=singapore/>\n|-\n!Total\n!463\n!3\n!466\n|}\n\n=== States and Union Territories without confirmed cases ===\n\nNo confirmed cases have been reported in the following states and union territories\n* [[Meghalaya]]\n* [[Sikkim]]\n* [[Dadra and Nagar Haveli and Daman and Diu]]\n* [[Lakshadweep]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Asia]]\n* [[SAARC COVID-19 Emergency Fund]]\n* [[2020 stock market crash]]\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|India|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.mygov.in/covid-19 COVID-19] on [[MyGov.in]] \u2013 Government's portal for COVID-19\n* [https://fieldmaps.in/covid19/ District level map of COVID-19 cases], fieldmaps.in\n* {{YouTube|playlist=PL1a9DHjZmejE-Ep2PAu2OR8HBfLP0BLIk|title=}} \u2013 COVID-19 Management videos by the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare]]\n* {{Cite book|last=Prasad|first=R.|url=https://creatives.thehindu.com/covid_19_ebook.pdf|title=The Pandemic Notebook|last2=Perappadan|first2=Bindu Shajan|last3=Shelar|first3=Jyoti|publisher=The Hindu|year=2020|isbn=|editor-last=George|editor-first=P.J.|location=|pages=|quote=A handy guide from The Hindu on understanding the coronavirus pandemic and staying protected against COVID-19}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India| ]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|India]]\n[[Category:2020 in India|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|epidemiology of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] in India|the current quarantine|2020 coronavirus lockdown in India}}\n{{Merge from|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Uttar Pradesh|date=March 2020|discuss=Talk:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n{{pp-30-500|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}{{Current event|2=current disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in India\n| website         = {{url|https://www.mohfw.gov.in/}}\n| width           = \n| map1            = File:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in India.svg\n| legend1         = Map of the pandemic in India (as of 13 April)\n{{legend|#d40000|1000+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ff2a2a|500\u2013999 confirmed cases}}{{legend|#ff5555|100\u2013499 confirmed cases}}{{legend|#ff8080|50\u201399 confirmed cases}}{{legend|#ffaaaa|10\u201349 confirmed cases}}{{legend|#ffd5d5|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n| map2            = COVID-19 Death Cases in India.png\n| legend2         = Map of deaths due to the pandemic in India (as of 13 April)\n{{legend|#ff5555|100+ death cases}}{{legend|#ff8080|50\u201399 death  cases}}{{legend|#ffaaaa|10\u201349 death cases}}{{legend|#ffd5d5|1\u20139 death cases}}\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51466362 |title=Coronavirus disease named Covid-19 |date=11 February 2020 |work=[[BBC News Online]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215204154/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51466362 |archive-date=15 February 2020 |url-status=live |access-date=15 February 2020 }}</ref>\n| location        = India\n| first_case      = [[Thrissur]], [[Kerala]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/kerala-reports-first-confirmed-novel-coronavirus-case-in-india-1641593-2020-01-30|title=Kerala confirmed first novel coronavirus case in India|publisher=India Today|date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n| arrival_date    = 30 January 2020<br /> {{small|({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=30|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})}}<ref>{{cite news |title=India confirms its first coronavirus case |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/30/india-confirms-first-case-of-the-coronavirus.html |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=CNBC |date=30 January 2020 |author=David Reid |language=en}}</ref>\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sheikh |first1=Knvul |last2=Rabin |first2=Roni Caryn |title=The Coronavirus: What Scientists Have Learned So Far |url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/what-is-coronavirus.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=10 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 10,363<ref name=\"mohfw\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mohfw.gov.in/|title=Home {{!}} Ministry of Health and Family Welfare {{!}} GOI|website=www.mohfw.gov.in|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><br /> {{small|(including 76 foreign nationals)}}\n| active_cases    = 8,988<ref name=\"mohfw\"/>\n| recovery_cases  = 1,036<ref name=\"mohfw\"/><br /> {{small|(including 1 migrated case)}}\n| deaths          = 339<ref name=mohfw/><br /> {{small|(including 2 foreign nationals)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/number-of-covid-19-cases-in-india-climb-to-467-death-toll-rises-to-8-11584977451791.html|title=Number of Covid-19 cases in India climbs to 467, death toll rises to nine|date=23 March 2020|website=livemint|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/a-yemen-national-is-2nd-coronavirus-casualty-in-delhi/story-qzIqICzaQnI7JkKDPEQm4N.html|title=60-year-old Yemeni national dies due to coronavirus in Delhi|date=27 March 2020|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n| territories     = [[States and union territories of India|26 states and 6 union territories]]<ref name=\"mohfw\"/>\n}}\nThe first case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] in India was reported on 30 January 2020, [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Mainland China|originating from China]]. As of {{TODAY}}, the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare]] have confirmed a total of 10,363 cases, 1,036 recoveries (including 1 migration) and 339 deaths in the country.<ref name=mohfw/> Experts suggest the number of infections could be much higher as India's testing rates are among the lowest in the world.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: India defiant as millions struggle under lockdown |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52077395 |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=BBC |date=28 March 2020}}</ref> The infection rate of [[COVID-19]] in India is reported to be 1.7, significantly lower than in the worst affected countries.<ref>[https://indianexpress.com/article/coronavirus/coronavirus-india-infection-rate-china-6321154/ One COVID-19 positive infects 1.7 in India, lower than in hot zones], The Indian Express, 19 March 2020. \"One reason for the relatively slow increase in the number of novel coronavirus patients in India, as of now, could be the fact that every infected person has been passing on the virus only to another 1.7 people on an average. This is remarkably lower than what has been observed in the worst-affected countries, a study by scientists at the Institute of Mathematical Sciences in Chennai shows.\"</ref>\n\nThe outbreak has been declared an [[epidemic]] in more than a dozen states and union territories, where provisions of the [[Epidemic Diseases Act, 1897]] have been invoked, and educational institutions and many commercial establishments have been shut down. India has suspended all tourist visas, as a majority of the confirmed cases were linked to other countries.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nOn 22 March 2020, India observed a 14-hour voluntary public curfew at the instance of the prime minister [[Narendra Modi]]. The government followed it up with lockdowns in 75 districts where COVID cases had occurred as well as all major cities.<ref name=\"CNN lockdown\">\nHelen Regan, Esha Mitra Swati Gupta, [https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/23/asia/coronavirus-covid-19-update-india-intl-hnk/index.html Millions in India under coronavirus lockdown as major cities restrict daily life], CNN, 23 March 2020\n</ref><ref name=\"Al Jazeera lockdown\">\n[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/scores-indian-districts-lockdown-coronavirus-200323041150247.html India locks down over 100 million people amid coronavirus fears], Al Jazeera, 23 March 2020.\n</ref> Further, on 24 March, the prime minister ordered a nationwide [[2020 India coronavirus lockdown|lockdown]] for 21 days, affecting the entire 1.3 billion population of India.<ref>\n[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/india-coronavirus-lockdown-modi-speech-cases-update-news-a9421491.html India coronavirus: Modi announces 21-day nationwide lockdown, limiting movement of 1.4bn people], The Independent, 24 March 2020.\n</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/indias-coronavirus-lockdown-clear-roads-clean-air-80s-tv-2209373 |title=India's Coronavirus Lockdown: What It Looks Like When India's 1.3 Billion People Stay Home |publisher=Ndtv.com |date=2019-02-22 |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\nOn 14 April, the prime minister extended nationwide lockdown till 3 May.<ref name=\"lockdownext\"/>\n\n[[Michael J. Ryan (doctor)|Michael Ryan]], chief executive director of the [[World Health Organization|World Health Organisation]]'s health emergencies programme, said that India had \"tremendous capacity\" to deal with the coronavirus outbreak and, as the second most populous country, will have enormous impact on the world's ability to deal with it.<ref>\n[https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-has-tremendous-capacity-in-eradicating-coronavirus-pandemic-who/articleshow/74788341.cms India has tremendous capacity in eradicating coronavirus pandemic: WHO], The Economic Times, 24 March 2020.\n</ref>\nOther commentators worried about the economic devastation caused by the lockdown, which has huge effects on informal workers, micro and small enterprises, farmers and the self-employed, who are left with no livelihood in the absence of transportation and access to markets.<ref name=\"HT Jayati Ghosh\">\n[https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/unprecedented-crisis-do-whatever-it-takes-jayati-ghosh-on-covid-19/story-i9tPVvFhAs1d1Ud6uEYN4L.html \u2018Unprecedented crisis; do whatever it takes\u2019: Jayati Ghosh on Covid-19], Hindustan Times, 28 March 2020.\n</ref><ref name=CEPR>\nDebraj Ray, S. Subramanian, Lore Vandewalle, [https://www.theindiaforum.in/article/indias-lockdown India's Lockdown], The India Forum, 11 April 2020. \"But in societies like India, a lockdown can kill: via job loss, increased vulnerability to economic shocks, and via social stigma and misinformation. Then the objective of saving lives as a whole may or may not be achieved by a draconian lockdown.\"\n</ref>\nThe lockdown was justified by the government and other agencies for being preemptive to prevent India from entering a higher stage which could make handling very difficult and cause even more losses thereafter.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Sanchita Sharma|title=\u2018Lockdown in India was early, far-sighted and courageous\u2019: WHO envoy|url=https://m.hindustantimes.com/india-news/lockdown-in-india-was-early-this-was-far-sighted-courageous-move-who-special-envoy-on-covid-19/story-wNdCkNVOqV5gCN8Du9jJ3N.html|publisher=Hindustan Times|date=2020-04-03|accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=India's response to COVID outbreak|url=https://pib.gov.in/PressReleseDetail.aspx?PRID=1608727|publisher=Press Information Bureau|date=2020-03-28|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>{{POV statement|date=April 2020}}\n\nAccording to a study at [[Shiv Nadar University]], India could have witnessed a surge of 31,000 cases of disease between March 24 and April 14 without lockdown.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Sagar Kulkarni|title=India would have seen 31,000 coronavirus cases without lockdown: Researches|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/india-would-have-seen-31000-coronavirus-cases-without-lockdown-researches-821010.html|publisher=Deccan Herald|date=2020-04-03|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] of 2003,<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{main|Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India medical cases chart}}\n[[File:COVID-19 India Total Cases Animated Map.gif|thumb|Timeline of the pandemic spread across India (since 30 January 2020)|alt=|300px]]\nOn 30 January, India reported its first case of COVID-19 in Kerala, which rose to three cases by 3 February; all were students who had returned from Wuhan, China.<ref>{{cite news|title=India confirms its first coronavirus case|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/30/india-confirms-first-case-of-the-coronavirus.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://weather.com/en-IN/india/news/news/2020-02-14-kerala-defeats-coronavirus-indias-three-covid-19-patients-successfully|title=Kerala Defeats Coronavirus; India's Three COVID-19 Patients Successfully Recover|website=The Weather Channel|access-date=21 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218172552/https://weather.com/en-IN/india/news/news/2020-02-14-kerala-defeats-coronavirus-indias-three-covid-19-patients-successfully|archive-date=18 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> No significant rise in cases was seen in the rest of February. On 4 March, 22 new cases came to light, including those of an Italian tourist group with 14 infected members.<ref>[https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/covid-19-6-members-of-delhi-patients-family-test-positive-for-coronavirus/article30980724.ece COVID-19 | 6 members of Delhi patient\u2019s family test positive for coronavirus], The Hindu, 4 March 2020.</ref>\n\nThe transmission escalated during March, after several cases were reported all over the country, most of which were linked to people with a travel history to affected countries. On 12 March, a 76-year-old man who had returned from Saudi Arabia became the first victim of the virus in the country.<ref name=\"death1\">{{cite web |title=India's first coronavirus death is confirmed in Karnataka |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/india-s-first-coronavirus-death-in-karnataka-confirmed/story-2ZJ6IuxJ38EiGndBq5pfHO.html |website=Hindustan Times |language=en |date=12 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nConfirmed cases crossed 100 on 15 March,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/coronavirus-five-more-test-positive-near-pune-maharashtra-count-rises-to-31/article31070898.ece|title=Coronavirus - Number of confirmed cases in India crosses 100|last=Shelar|first=Jyoti|newspaper=The Hindu|date=15 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> 1,000 on 28 March<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/india-has-909-active-corona-cases-total-tally-crosses-1000/1783310|title=India has 909 active corona cases, total tally crosses 1,000|date=|work=Outlook|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> and 5,000 on 7 April.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/coronavirus-cases-in-india-cross-5000-1-year-old-among-165-dead/articleshow/75037913.cms|title=Coronavirus cases cross 5,000; 1-year-old among 165 dead|date=|work=Times of India|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The death toll crossed 50 on 1 April<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/news/nation/2020/04/01/coronavirus-covid-india-death-number-of-cases-live-updates.html|title=COVID-19 fight in top gear as cases inch to 2,000 mark, death toll breaches 50|date=|work=Malayala Manorama|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> and 100 on 5 April.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/toll-crosses-100-tablighi-jamaat-members-account-for-30-of-all-cases/articleshow/75000552.cms|title=Toll crosses 100; Tablighi Jamaat members account for 30% of all coronavirus cases|date=|work=Times of India|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<!-- This is timeline. DO NOT add political material, recriminations or argumentations here. -->\nA Sikh preacher that returned from travel to Italy and Germany, carrying the virus, turned into \"super spreader\" by attending a [[Hola Mohalla|Sikh festival]] in Anandpur Sahib during 10\u201312 March.<ref>{{cite news|title=40,000 Indians quarantined after 'super spreader' ignores government advice |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/28/40000-quarantined-punjab-super-spreader-ignores-government-advice/ |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=super>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus: India 'super spreader' quarantines 40,000 people|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52061915 |newspaper=BBC News |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> Twenty-seven COVID-19 cases were traced back to him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Septuagenarian Sikh priest infected 27 of total 38 coronavirus cases in Punjab |newspaper=India Today |date=28 March 2020 |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/septuagenarian-sikh-priest-infected-27-of-38-coronavirus-cases-punjab-1660789-2020-03-28}}</ref> Over 40,000 people in 20 villages in Punjab were quarantined on 27 March to contain the spread.<ref name=super/><ref>{{cite news |title=At least 40,000 quarantined in India after single priest spread coronavirus |newspaper=NBC News |date=30 March 2020 |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/at-least-40000-quarantined-in-india-after-single-priest-spread-coronavirus/ar-BB11Sezp}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, a [[Tablighi Jamaat]] religious congregation event that took place in Delhi in early March emerged as a new virus hotspot after numerous cases across the country were traced back to the event.<ref>\n{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52104753 |title=India event sparks massive search for Covid-19 cases |date=31 March 2020 |work=BBC News}}\n</ref>  Over 9,000 missionaries may have attended the congregation, with the majority being from various states of India,<ref name=\"TOI 2 April\">\n{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: About 9,000 Tablighi Jamaat members, primary contacts quarantined in country, MHA says |newspaper=The Times of India |agency=PTI |date=2 April 2020 |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/coronavirus-about-9000-tablighi-jamaat-members-primary-contacts-quarantined-in-country-mha-says/articleshow/74948832.cms}}\n</ref><ref name=\"HT 2 April\">\n{{cite news |title=How Nizamuddin markaz became Covid-19 hotspot; more than 8,000 attendees identified |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=2 April 2020 |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/how-nizamuddin-markaz-became-a-hotspot-for-covid-19-8-000-people-identified/story-zedKlaDNTPpbDLdMsgExAM.html}}\n</ref> and 960 attendees from 40 foreign countries.<ref>\n{{cite news |title=379 Indonesians among foreigners from 40 countries attended Tablighi Jamaat gathering: Sources |url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/379-indonesians-among-foreigners-from-40-countries-attended-tablighi-jamaat-gathering-sources20200403152720/ |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=ANI}}\n</ref> As of 6 April, 1,445 out of 4,067 confirmed cases were linked to this event in 17 Indian states and union territories.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/1-445-out-of-4-067-covid-19-cases-linked-to-tablighi-jamaat-health-ministry/story-eK8oimpTN6qCZcnUAYlrDN.html |title=1445 out of 4067 Covid-19 cases linked to Tablighi Jamaat: Health Ministry |work=Hindustan Times }}</ref><ref name=\"3K\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-india-68-coronavirus-deaths-in-india-2-902-cases-so-far-with-601-reported-in-last-24-hou-2205948|title=Coronavirus Cases Cross 3,000 In India, 75 Deaths: 10 Points|date=4 April 2020|work=NDTV|access-date=4 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April 2020, in Mumbai's [[Wockhardt Hospitals|Wockhardt Hospital]], 26 nurses and 3 doctors were found to have been infected with the virus. The hospital was temporarily shut down and declared a containment zone. Negligence of the hospital administration has been blamed for the infections.<ref>[https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/mumbai-s-wockhardt-hospital-declared-containment-zone-after-nurses-doctors-test-positive-for-covid-19/story-a3JpRK4WiMyf8TMeymNlCK.html Mumbai\u2019s Workhardt hospital shut after 26 nurses test Covid-19 positive], Hindustan Times, 6 April 2020.</ref>\n\n==Government responses==\n===January\u2013February===\nProtective measures were first applied in January. India began thermal screening of passengers arriving from China on 21 January.<ref>\n[https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/china-coronavirus-thermal-screening-of-passengers-flying-in-from-china-at-7-airports/articleshow/73493350.cms?from=mdr Coronavirus: Thermal screening of passengers flying in from China at 7 airports], The Economic Times, 21 January 2020.\n</ref> Initially carried out at 7 airports, it was expanded to 20 airports towards the end of January.<ref>\n[https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/editorial/alarming-spread/article30677660.ece Alarming spread: on novel coronavirus outbreak], The Hindu (Editorial), 29 January 2020.\n</ref>\nDuring February, the screening was extended to passengers from Thailand, Singapore, Hong Kong, Japan and South Korea.<ref>\n[https://www.livemint.com/news/india/passengers-arriving-from-japan-and-south-korea-will-also-be-screened-for-covid-19-all-3-patients-in-india-recovered-11581762093232.html Passengers arriving from Japan and South Korea will also be screened for COVID-19, all 3 patients in India recovered], livemint, 15 February 2020.\n</ref>\nNepal, Vietnam, Indonesia and Malyais were added to the list towards the end of February.<ref>\n[https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/india-news-coronavirus-convid-19-india-airports-to-screen-passengers-from-4-countries-nepal-indonesia-vietnam-and-malaysia/347751 Coronavirus: Indian Airports To Now Screen Passengers From Four More Countries Including Nepal, Malaysia], Outlook, 23 February 2020.\n</ref>\nVery few new cases were discovered during February, but [[Shashi Tharoor]] pointed out that asymptomatic, infectious persons could still slip through the sreening. He worried that no comprehensive nationwide surveillance system was in place, testing infrastructure was inadequate, and the public awareness was minimal.<ref>\nShashi Tharoor, [https://www.theweek.in/columns/shashi-tharoor/2020/02/28/india-not-prepared-for-coronavirus.html India not prepared for coronavirus], The Week, 29 February 2020.\n</ref>\n\n=== March ===\n[[File:Coronavirus Do's & Don'ts by Indian MoHFW.pdf|thumb|Awareness poster released by the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare|alt=|293x293px]]\n\nBy early to mid March the government had drawn up plans to deal with a worsening of the pandemic in the country which includes seven ministries working together to set up additional quarantine and treatment facilities across the country. States and twenty ministries including [[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|home]], [[Ministry of Defence (India)|defence]], [[Ministry of Railways (India)|railways]], [[Ministry of Labour and Employment (India)|labour]], [[Ministry of Minority Affairs|minority affairs]], [[Ministry of Civil Aviation (India)|aviation]] and [[Ministry of Tourism (India)|tourism]] have been informed of the containment plan.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mishra|first=Mihir|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-seven-ministries-to-set-up-quarantine-facilities/articleshow/74586054.cms|title=Covid-19: Seven ministries to set up quarantine facilities|date=12 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> Plans to avoid a panic like situation have also been made. The [[Ministry of Textiles]] has been assigned the task of making sure the availability of protective and medical materials. The [[Ministry of Chemicals and Fertilizers|Department of Pharmaceuticals]] is tasked with making sure of the availability of essential medicines. [[Ministry of Consumer Affairs, Food and Public Distribution]] has been asked to ensure availability of essentials.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-outbreak-govt-working-on-a-containment-plan/articleshow/74504048.cms?from=mdr|title=Coronavirus outbreak: Govt working on a 'containment plan'|date=6 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Indian Space Research Organisation]] (ISRO) has adopted precautions against the pandemic in its three facilities in [[Thiruvananthapuram district|Thiruvananthapuram]], Kerala. The facilities have suspended bio-metric fingerprint scanning, disabled entrance [[turnstile]]s and limited internal meetings and travel to a minimum while stepping up medical surveillance. However, mission schedules were not affected.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/despite-tight-schedule-isro-eases-work/article31072973.ece|title=ISRO eases work schedule|date=15 March 2020|work=The Hindu|access-date=15 March 2020|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, The [[Government of India]] issued an advisory urging to all Indian states to take [[social distancing]] measures as a preventive strategy for implementation till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Govt calls for social distancing| url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/govt-calls-for-social-distancing-as-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-124-11584384445401.html|website=livemint|author=| date=17 March 2020}}</ref> A government directive was issued asking all [[Central Armed Police Force]]s to get into battle mode; all non-essential leave has been cancelled.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/covid-19-government-asks-capfs-to-axe-non-essential-leaves-of-troops-get-into-battle-mode/articleshow/74689685.cms|title=COVID-19: Government asks CAPFs to axe non-essential leaves of troops, get into 'battle mode'|date=18 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live|agency=PTI}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/enter-battle-mode-paramilitary-forces-told-after-virus-infects-soldier-2196796|title='Enter Battle Mode,' Paramilitary Forces Told After Virus Infects Soldier|last=Sharma|first=Neeta|date=18 March 2020|editor-last=Srinivasan|editor-first=Chandrashekar|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> A [[COVID-19 Economic Response Task Force]] has also been formed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ddnews.gov.in/national/covid-19-task-force-deal-economic-challenges|title=COVID-19: Task Force to deal with economic challenges {{!}} DD News|website=ddnews.gov.in|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-narendra-modi-forms-economic-response-task-force-calls-for-janata-curfew/articleshow/74715013.cms?from=mdr|title=PM Narendra Modi forms economic response task force, calls for 'Janata Curfew'|date=20 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, The [[Tamil Nadu]] government has issued appointment orders to 1508 lab technicians, 500 doctors and 1000 nurses with immediate effect in view of the current status of corona virus. With this, orders have also been given to increase 200 new ambulances in the state.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tamil Nadu recruits 530 doctors, 1508 lab technicians, 1000 nurses to contain coronavirus COVID-19 outbreak: CM K Palaniswami| url=https://zeenews.india.com/india/tamil-nadu-recruits-530-doctors-1508-lab-technicians-1000-nurses-to-contain-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak-cm-k-palaniswami-2272083.html|website=zeenews|author=| date=27 March 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe government of [[Assam]] started making isolation facilities in [[Indira Gandhi Athletic Stadium|Sarusajai stadium]] and [[Nehru Stadium, Guwahati|Nehru Stadium]] in [[Guwahati]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/assam-govt-transforms-sarusajai-stadium-into-coronavirus-isolation-facility20200326151534/|title=Assam govt transforms Sarusajai Stadium into coronavirus isolation facility|website=ANI News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sentinelassam.com/top-headlines/sarusajai-stadium-and-nehru-stadium-in-guwahati-to-be-converted-into-quarantine-centres/|title=Sarusajai Stadium and Nehru Stadium in Guwahati to be converted into quarantine centres|date=2020-03-26|website=The Sentinel|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n[[Government of India|Union]] and [[State governments of India|state governments]] have setup national and state helpline numbers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Helpline Numbers |url=https://www.mohfw.gov.in/pdf/coronvavirushelplinenumber.pdf |website=Ministry of Health and Family Welfare |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Travel and entry restrictions===\nOn 3 March 2020, the Indian government stopped issuing of new visas. Previously issued visas for the nationals of Italy, Iran, South Korea, and Japan were suspended.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boi.gov.in/content/advisory-travel-and-visa-restrictions-related-covid-19 |title=Advisory: Travel and Visa restrictions related to COVID-19 |website=Bureau of Immigration}}</ref>\n\nAll visas were suspended 13 March 2020, except for diplomatic and other official visas, as well as the visa-free travel for [[Overseas Citizen of India|Overseas Citizens of India]]. Indians returning from COVID-affected countries were asked to be quarantined for 14 days.<ref name=\":2\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-impact-visas-to-india-suspended-till-april-15-2193382 |title=India Suspends All Tourist Visas Till April 15 Over Coronavirus: 10 Facts |website=NDTV.com |access-date=12 March 2020}}\n</ref><ref>\n[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/india-suspends-visas-attempt-coronavirus-spread-200312035057594.html India suspends visas in attempt to contain coronavirus spread], Al Jazeera, 12 March 2020.\n</ref> These measures were expanded to Europe, Gulf countries and Asian countries including Malaysia on 17\u201318 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Travel from EU, U.K. banned as India tightens preventive steps |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/coronavirus-government-prohibits-entry-of-passengers-from-eu-turkey-uk-from-march-18/article31083949.ece |newspaper=the hindu |date=16 March 2020 |access-date=17 March 2020 |last1=Perappadan |first1=Bindu Shajan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Pandemic: India bans entry of passengers from these countries with immediate effect |url=https://www.financialexpress.com/lifestyle/travel-tourism/coronavirus-pandemic-india-bans-entry-of-passengers-from-these-countries-with-immediate-effect/1900372/ |website=Financial express |author= |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe land border with [[Myanmar]] began to be restricted on 9 March with the initiative of the state governments of [[Mizoram]] and [[Manipur]].<ref>\n{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/coronavirus-mizorams-international-borders-to-be-sealed/article31025105.ece |title=Coronavirus: Mizoram's international borders to be sealed |date=9 March 2020 |work=The Hindu |access-date=10 March 2020 |agency=PTI |language=en-IN |issn=0971-751X}}\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/videos/news/covid-19-india-closes-border-with-myanmar-in-manipur/videoshow/74560495.cms |title=Covid-19: India closes border with Myanmar in Manipur |website=The Times of India \u2013 Videos |language=en |access-date=10 March 2020}}\n</ref>\nOn 13 March, the Government of India closed passenger traffic from all neighbouring countries other than Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mohfw.gov.in/GuidelinesDT13032020.pdf |title=GuidelinesDT13032020.pdf |last= |first= |date= |website= |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323075951/https://www.mohfw.gov.in/GuidelinesDT13032020.pdf |archive-date=23 March 2020 |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\nThe traffic from Pakistan itself was closed on 16 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mohfw.gov.in/NewinstructionsDt14032020Restirctiononinternationalpassengertraffic.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319061749/https://www.mohfw.gov.in/NewinstructionsDt14032020Restirctiononinternationalpassengertraffic.pdf |archivedate= 19 March 2020 |title=Restriction on international passenger traffic through Land Check Posts in view of the spread of COVID-19 |last= |first= |date= |website=mohfw.gov.in |url-status=dead |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\nTravel and registration for [[Kartarpur Corridor|Sri Kartarpur Sahib]] was also suspended on this date.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2020/03/15/coronavirus-pilgrimage-to-kartarpur-sahib-suspended.html |title=Coronavirus: Pilgrimage to Kartarpur Sahib suspended |website=The Week |language=en |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Sikkim]] restricted entry of domestic tourists in the state from 17 March and asked those who are already in the state to leave.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/sikkim-quarantines-itself-seals-borders-bans-entry-of-outsiders-as-coronavirus-fear-spikes/story-ClukHlUjLbfov83kTlWD3I.html |title=Sikkim quarantines itself, seals borders, bans entry of outsiders as coronavirus fear spikes |website=Hindustan Times |date=16 March 2020 |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> [[Himachal Pradesh]] banned entry of foreign and domestic tourists on 19 March until further notice.<ref>{{cite news |last1= |first= |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/himachal-bans-entry-of-domestic-foreign-tourists-amid-coronavirus-threat-58038 |title=Himachal bans entry of domestic, foreign tourists amid coronavirus threat |date= |work=The Tribune |accessdate=19 March 2020 |url-status=live |agency=Tribune News Service |issue=19 March 2020}}</ref> Other states followed such as Uttarakhand, which has also banned tourists till further orders.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/coronavirus-uttarakhand-bans-entry-of-domestic-and-foreign-tourists/article31119270.ece |title=Coronavirus {{!}} Uttarakhand bans entry of domestic and foreign tourists |date=20 March 2020 |work=The Hindu |access-date=21 March 2020 |agency=PTI |language=en-IN |issn=0971-751X}}</ref> [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] banned the use of public transport as of 21 March.<ref>{{cite news |last1=staff |title=Coronavirus: Punjab to ban public transport from March 21 |url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/coronavirus-punjab-to-ban-public-transport-from-march-21-599607 |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=India TV |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Screening ===\nOn 4 March 2020, the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare|Minister of Health and Family Welfare]], [[Harsh Vardhan (Delhi politician)|Dr. Harsh Vardhan]], announced compulsory screening of all international passengers arriving in India. He also said that so far, 589,000 people have been screened at airports, over one million screened at borders with Nepal and around 27,000 were currently under community surveillance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/union-health-minister-harsh-vardhan-all-international-flights-to-be-screened-for-coronavirus-2189659 |title=Passengers Of All International Flights To Be Screened For Virus: Centre |website=NDTV.com |access-date=4 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304094159/https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/union-health-minister-harsh-vardhan-all-international-flights-to-be-screened-for-coronavirus-2189659 |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/all-international-arrivals-to-give-travel-history-at-airports/articleshow/74467810.cms?from=mdr |title=Coronavirus: All international arrivals to India to share travel history at airports |date=4 March 2020 |newspaper=The Economic Times}}</ref>\nThe government shall also now start universal screening for all passengers flying into India from abroad. Earlier, only passengers coming in from China, Hong Kong, Japan, South Korea, Thailand, Singapore, Nepal, Indonesia, Vietnam, and Malaysia were checked.\n\n=== Closedown and curfews ===\n* '''On 5 March''', amidst a surge in fresh cases being confirmed in [[National Capital Region (India)|Delhi NCR]], the [[Government of Delhi]] announced that all primary schools across Delhi would be shut until 31 March as a precaution.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus threat: Delhi govt orders closure of all primary schools till March 31 |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/education/coronavirus-threat-delhi-govt-orders-closure-of-all-primary-schools-till-march-31/story-ExewEmJeLCZ6egWDW6Ss2N.html |accessdate=5 March 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306042604/https://www.hindustantimes.com/education/coronavirus-threat-delhi-govt-orders-closure-of-all-primary-schools-till-march-31/story-ExewEmJeLCZ6egWDW6Ss2N.html |archive-date=6 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* '''On 7 March''', primary schools in [[Jammu district]] and [[Samba district]] were closed down until 31 March after two suspected cases with \"high viral load\" were reported in [[Jammu]].<ref>{{cite news |title=J-K govt braces for coronavirus, shuts down schools in Jammu and Samba till March 31 |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/jk-govt-braces-for-coronavirus-shuts-down-schools-in-jammu-and-samba-till-march-31/story-WyYt7c9S0RzX2PvnxXqDvN.html |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307064903/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/jk-govt-braces-for-coronavirus-shuts-down-schools-in-jammu-and-samba-till-march-31/story-WyYt7c9S0RzX2PvnxXqDvN.html |archive-date=7 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* '''On 9 March''', [[District magistrate|collector and district magistrate]] of [[Pathanamthitta district]] of Kerala declared three days long holidays for all educational institutions in the district.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.mathrubhumi.com/news/kerala/coronavirus-20-people-in-isolation-in-pathanamthitta-kollam-1.4598606|title=Coronavirus: 20 people in isolation in Pathanamthitta, Kollam|website=Mathrubhumi|language=en|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> Karnataka declared indefinite holiday for all kindergarten and pre-primary schools in Bangalore.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/city/top-bengaluru-stories/coronavirus-holiday-for-all-lkg-ukg-pre-primary-schools-in-bengaluru-due-to-covid-19-811899.html|title=Coronavirus: Holiday for all LKG, UKG, pre-primary schools in Bengaluru due to COVID-19|website=Deccan Herald|date=8 March 2020|language=en|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> The holiday was extended to all primary schools up to fifth grade after a confirmed case was reported in the city.<ref>{{cite news |title=Karnataka confirms first case of COVID-19, declares holiday for all primary schools in Bengaluru |url=https://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/news/state/karnataka-confirms-first-case-of-covid-19-declares-holiday-for-all-primary-schools/articleshow/74555439.cms |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Bangalore Mirror}}</ref>\n* '''On 10 March''', Kerala announced closure of all schools and colleges across the state until 31 March, with effect from 11 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: All schools, colleges in Kerala to shut down in March; 6 more test positive |url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/news/kerala/2020/03/10/coronavirus-holiday-for-upto-class-7-kerala.html |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=Manorama Online}}</ref>\n* '''On 12 March''', the [[Chief Minister of Delhi]] [[Arvind Kejriwal]] announced that all schools, colleges and cinema halls in New Delhi would be closed till the end of March and all public places disinfected as a precautionary measure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/schools-colleges-movie-theatres-to-be-shut-in-delhi-till-march-31-due-to-coronavirus-2193840|title=Delhi Schools, Colleges, Cinemas Shut Till March 31 Due To Coronavirus|date=12 March 2020|editor-last=Sanyal|editor-first=Anindita|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''On 12 March''', the [[Chief Minister of Karnataka]] [[B. S. Yediyurappa]] announced that all educational institutions, malls, cinema halls and pubs would be shut for a week across the state. He also issued prohibitory orders on public events such as parties and weddings.<ref>{{cite news |title=Malls, pubs, theatres shut, parties banned for a week across Karnataka over COVID-19 |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/malls-pubs-theatres-shut-week-parties-banned-across-karnataka-over-covid-19-120138 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The News Minute}}</ref> The Government of Odisha, declaring the outbreak a \"disaster\", announced the closure of educational institutions and cinema halls until the end of the month, as well as prohibition on non-essential official gatherings.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: After Delhi, Odisha closes schools, colleges and cinema halls till month end |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-after-delhi-odisha-closes-schools-colleges-and-cinema-halls-till-month-end-11584087439578.html |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Livemint}}</ref> The Government of Maharashtra declared the outbreak to be an epidemic in the cities of Mumbai, Navi Mumbai, Nagpur, Pune and Pimpri Chinchwad. It announced that all malls, cinema halls, swimming pools and gyms in these cities will be closed until 31 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Maharashtra orders closure of malls, cinema halls in five cities until 31 March |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-maharashtra-orders-closure-of-malls-cinema-halls-in-five-cities-until-31-march-11584102050561.html |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Livemint}}</ref>\n* '''On 13 March''', the [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] and [[Chhattisgarh]] governments declared holidays in all schools and colleges till 31 March.<ref>[https://m.tribuneindia.com/news/punjab-schools-shut-till-march-31-to-prevent-coronavirus-spread-54917 Punjab Schools, colleges and universities shut till 31 March to prevent coronavirus spread] ''The Tribune''. Retrieved 14 March 2020.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livehindustan.com/career/story-coronavirus-school-college-in-chhattisgarh-closed-till-31-march-3082405.html|title=\u0915\u094b\u0930\u094b\u0928\u093e\u0935\u093e\u092f\u0930\u0938 : \u091b\u0924\u094d\u0924\u0940\u0938\u0917\u0922\u093c \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u0938\u094d\u0915\u0942\u0932 \u0915\u0949\u0932\u0947\u091c 31 \u092e\u093e\u0930\u094d\u091a \u0924\u0915 \u092c\u0902\u0926|website=www.livehindustan.com|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> [[Manipur]] government announced that all schools in the state, where examination are not being held would remain closed till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/manipur-shutdown-schools-till-march-31-coronavirus-outbreak-1654982-2020-03-13|title=Manipur govt orders shutdown of schools till March 31 due to coronavirus outbreak|last=Guwahati|first=Hemanta Kumar Nath|date=13 March 2020|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''On 14 March''', the [[Himachal Pradesh]] chief minister [[Jai Ram Thakur]] declared that all educational institutions and theatres would remain closed until 31 March as a precautionary measure in view of the threat of the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |title=Himachal Pradesh closes all schools, colleges, Anganwadi centers till March 31 due to coronavirus threat| url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/himachal-pradesh-closes-all-schools-colleges-anganwadi-centers-till-march-31-due-to-coronavirus-threat-598055|website=indiatvnews|author=| date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Also, in the [[West Bengal]] government announced that all educational institutions will be closed till 31 March, however the board examinations will be conducted.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: All Educational Institutes In West Bengal Shut Till March 31| url=https://www.ndtv.com/education/coronavirus-all-educational-institutes-in-west-bengal-shut-till-march-31-2194885?amp=1&akamai-rum=off|website=ndtv|author=}}</ref> [[Maharashtra]] government closed shopping malls, swimming pools, movie theatres, gyms and asked all schools and colleges in the state's urban areas to remain close till 31 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-cases-in-maharashtra-surge-states-shut-down-public-places-developments-1655635-2020-03-15|title=Coronavirus: Cases in Maharashtra surge, states shut down public places {{!}} Developments|date=15 March 2020|work=India Today|access-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/coronavirus-outbreak-live-updates-covid-19-who-pandemic-quarantine-india-noida-bangalore-cases-alert-novel-latest-news-today-ipl-school-college-8138611.html|title=Coronavirus Outbreak LIVE Updates: Maharashtra closes malls till 31 March, postpones exams up to Class 9 as number of reported cases rises to 26|website=Firstpost|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> [[Government of Rajasthan]] announced to close all educational institutions, gyms, and cinema halls till 30 March, however ongoing school and college exams will continue.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Iqbal|first=Mohammed|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/coronavirus-rajasthan-closes-schools-cinema-halls-till-march-30/article31067344.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Rajasthan closes schools, cinema halls till 30 March|date=14 March 2020|work=The Hindu|access-date=15 March 2020|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n* '''On 15 March''', [[IIT, Bombay]] suspended all academic activities till 29 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=IIT Bombay suspends academic activities till March 29| url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article-amp/news-ani/iit-bombay-suspends-academic-activities-till-march-29-120031401159_1.html|website=Business standard|author=}}</ref> In [[Goa]] chief minister [[Pramod Sawant]] declared that all educational institutions would remain closed until 31 March. While the examinations of the 10th and 12th Goa Board of Secondary and Higher Secondary Education will be held as per schedule.<ref>{{cite web |title=Maharashtra Schools closed till March 31, all exams cancelled except for 10th, 12th Boards| url=https://www.timesnownews.com/education/article/school-holiday-updates-due-to-coronavirus-in-kerala-karnataka-jammu-kashmir-bangalore-delhi-mumbai-india/563653|website=timesnownews|author=}}</ref> [[Brihanmumbai Municipal Corporation]] shut down [[Jijamata Udyaan]] till further orders.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/coronavirus-updates-live-total-number-of-coronavirus-cases-in-india-maharashtra-telangana-haryana/liveblog/74632927.cms|title=Coronavirus outbreak live updates: Mumbai cops invoke section 144 to ban group tours till March 31|date=15 March 2020|work=Times of India|access-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Gujarat]] government announced that all schools, colleges, cinema halls will be closed till 31 March, however the board examinations will be conducted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/breaking-coronavirus-gujarat-shuts-schools-colleges-covid19-598370|title=Coronavirus: Gujarat shuts all schools, colleges, cinema halls from tomorrow|last=Hardaha|first=Rashi|date=15 March 2020|website=www.indiatvnews.com|language=en|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> [[Bihar Public Service Commission]] (BPSC) has postponed all the recruitment exams till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=BPSC assistant engineer main exam 2019 postponed amid coronavirus outbreak| url=https://m.hindustantimes.com/education/bpsc-assistant-engineer-main-exam-2019-postponed-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/story-rQzUCoRWC4NHWa7Gq0SQTN.html|website=Hindustan times|author=| date=14 March 2020}}</ref> [[Vaishno Devi]] Shrine Board issued an advisory asking non-resident Indians and foreigners not to visit the temple for 28 days after landing in India.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-cases-in-india-live-news-latest-updates-march15/liveblog/74633220.cms|title=Coronavirus News Live Updates: Third case reported in Telangana|date=15 March 2020|work=Economic Times|access-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Tamil Nadu]] and [[Telangana]] governments declared closure of schools, malls and theatres till 31 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Narasimhan|first=T. E.|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-closes-schools-malls-and-theatres-till-march-31-120031500446_1.html|title=Coronavirus: Tamil Nadu closes schools, malls and theatres till March 31|date=15 March 2020|work=Business Standard India|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-schools-colleges-malls-movie-theatres-to-be-closed-in-telangana-until-31-march-11584186142495.html|title=Coronavirus: Schools, movie theatres to be closed in Telangana until 31 March|date=14 March 2020|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> [[Ministry of Culture (India)|Ministry of Culture]] shut down all monuments and museums under [[Archaeological Survey of India]] till 31 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/all-asiprotected-monuments-central-museums-across-india-to-be-shut-till-march-31-govt/1763377|title=All ASI-protected monuments, central museums across India to be shut till March 31: Govt|date=|work=Outlook|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* '''On 17 March''', schools, colleges and multiplexes in [[Uttar Pradesh]] were shut down till 2 April and on-going examinations were postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=All schools, colleges, cinema halls in UP closed till April 2 amid coronavirus pandemic| url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/schools-colleges-cinema-halls-in-uttar-pradesh-closed-till-april-2-amid-coronavirus-pandemic-598922|website=indianews|author=| date=17 March 2020}}</ref> [[Brihanmumbai Municipal Corporation|BMC]] ordered private firms in [[Mumbai]] to function \"only at 50% of their staff capacity or face action under section 188 of the [[Indian Penal Code|IPC]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/bmc-orders-private-firms-to-work-only-at-50-of-their-capacity/articleshow/74661516.cms|title=BMC orders private companies to work only at 50% of capacity as coronavirus count rises|date=|work=Economic Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Rajasthan]] government banned the gathering of more than 50 people in public places till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus outbreak: Rajasthan bans all 50-plus gathering in public places till March 31, says official| url=https://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/coronavirus-outbreak-rajasthan-bans-all-50-plus-gathering-in-public-places-till-march-31-says-official/1900701/|website=financial express|author=| date=17 March 2020}}</ref> Important tourist destinations in [[Tamil Nadu]] were locked down. Authorities in [[Nilgiris]] district ordered the closure of tourist sites including [[Ooty]] and the tourists staying in hotels and resorts were given 24 hours to leave the city.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Tourist centres in TN under lockdown; Visitors in| url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/coronavirus-tourist-centres-in-tn-under-lockdown-visitors-in/1768933|website=outlookindia|author=}}</ref> In [[Maharashtra]], government offices were closed down for seven days.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Maharashtra to shut government offices for next 7 days| url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/coronavirus-uddhav-thackeray-maharashtra-government-offices-shut-7-days-598998|website=indiatv|author=| date=17 March 2020}}</ref> [[Chandigarh]] administration ordered the closure of shopping malls, cinema halls, gyms, nightclubs, swimming pools, coaching centres, spas, creches and video game parlours till 31 March. It also banned gatherings of more than a 100 people and census work was postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Covid-19: Malls, cinema halls, gyms closed in Chandigarh| url=https://m.hindustantimes.com/cities/malls-clubs-discotheques-and-gyms-closed-in-chandigarh-till-march-31-to-check-coronavirus-spread/story-SlWceuV22oQXG5RKxODz4M.html|website=Hindustan times|author=| date=16 March 2020}}</ref> At the same time, [[Dera]] chiefs were asked to postpone all religious events till 31 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Punjab malls, gyms, restaurants deserted after advisory on coronavirus| url=https://wap.business-standard.com/multimedia/video-gallery/general/punjab-malls-gyms-restaurants-deserted-after-advisory-on-coronavirus-101227.htm|newspaper=Business Standard India|author=}}</ref> The GoM has also directed that no more than 50 people are allowed to gather at any place other than [[weddings]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Punjab: Malls, shopping complexes shut till March 31; curbs on gatherings at marriage palaces| url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/north-and-central/punjab-malls-shopping-complexes-shut-till-march-31-curbs-on-gatherings-at-marriage-palaces-814691.html|website=Deccan herald|author=| date=17 March 2020}}</ref> [[Pondicherry]] shut down schools, colleges, cinemas and gyms till 31 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/coronavirus-live-updates-number-of-coronavirus-cases-in-india-mumbai-hyderabad-kerala-pune-delhi/liveblog/74664459.cms|title=Coronavirus outbreak live updates: Railways cancels 76 trains as coronavirus precautionary measure, non-occupancy|date=|work=Times of India|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mumbai Police]] ordered the closure of pubs, bars and discotheques till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/coronavirus-in-mumbai-eatery-industry-seeks-financial-relief-from-government/articleshow/74682915.cms |website=Times of India |accessdate=18 March 2020|date=18 March 2020|title=Coronavirus in Mumbai: Pubs, bars closed |first1=Reeba |last1=Zachariah |first2=S Ahmed |last2=Ali}}</ref>\n* '''On 18 March''', [[District magistrate|district magistrate and deputy commissioner]] of [[Srinagar district]] in [[Jammu and Kashmir (union territory)|Jammu and Kashmir]] said that the entry of all foreign tourists has been banned in the entire union territory.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Foreign tourists' entry banned in Kashmir| url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/coronavirus-foreign-tourists-entry-banned-in-kashmir20200318043955/|website=ANI|author=}}</ref> On the other hand, the Directorate of Floriculture, Parks and Horticulture of the state has also extended the [[Bahu Fort|Bagh-e-Bahu Garden]] to the general public from 18 to 31 March to keep the situation under control in the Union Territory.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Entry of foreign tourists banned in Kashmir| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/coronavirus-entry-of-foreign-tourists-banned-in-kashmir/amp_articleshow/74680062.cms|website=timesofindia|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Foreign tourists' entry banned in Kashmir| url=https://in.news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-foreign-tourists-entry-banned-kashmir-230952993.html?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAAsTPJ7Iu8cHV2-xuPg420W0USOlXiZxrTxRaDzUOSe5JdhiIz3IZSoNue88uIJ6prDuoXqZJARg2C8LnSYSxIymW9gjjnnnAAptcCa3E3BOPUOfZxHBFR2hFOPpN5U7HP3MFvt6wIV-_j4WcRlVUxq_FjHwkZKTOgU_NrfcszhK|website=Yahoo india|author=}}</ref> [[Government of Andhra Pradesh]] announced closure of all educational institutions till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/education/news/andhra-pradesh-educational-institutions-remain-closed-till-march-31-due-to-coronavirus/articleshow/74694735.cms|title=AP educational institutions to remain closed till March 31 due to Coronavirus outbreak|website=The Times of India|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''On 23 March''', [[Chief Minister of Maharashtra]] announced that borders of all the districts will be closed, and a strict curfew will be implemented statewide.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/uddhav-thackeray-imposes-curfew-in-entire-maharashtra/articleshow/74775886.cms?from=mdr|title=Uddhav Thackeray imposes curfew in entire Maharashtra|date=23 March 2020|newspaper=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n\n===Lockdown===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus lockdown in India}}\nOn 22 March, the [[Government of India]] decided to completely lockdown 82 districts in 22 states and Union Territories of country where confirmed cases have been reported till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/82-districts-under-lockdown-over-covid-19-what-s-open-and-what-is-shut/story-c1AEMZXuuXN6FvmrAdRvsJ.html|title=82 districts under lockdown over Covid-19: What is shut and where|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> At 6 am on 23 March Delhi was put under lockdown till at least 31 March. Essential services and commodities were to continue.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jagannath |first1=J. |title=Delhi lockdown to start at 6 am Monday, until 31 March: Kejriwal |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/delhi-lockdown-to-start-at-6-am-monday-until-31-march-kejriwal-11584881955813.html |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Livemint |date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/lockdown-in-west-bengal-from-5pm-today-government-to-shut-down-non-essentials/articleshow/74766599.cms|title=Lockdown in West Bengal: From 5pm today, government to shut down non-essentials|date=23 March 2020|work=The Times of India|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> 80 cities including major cities such as Bengaluru, Chennai, Mumbai,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marpakwar |first1=Prafulla |title=Poor public response pushed govt to declare lockdown in Mumbai |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/poor-public-response-pushed-govt-to-declare-lockdown-in-mumbai/articleshow/74766049.cms |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Times of India |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Chandigarh<ref>{{cite news |title=Chandigarh orders lock down till March 31 |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/chandigarh-orders-lock-down-till-march-31/article31135191.ece |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> and Kolkata were also put under lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gunasekar |first1=Arvind |last2=Bhattacharji |first2=Chetan |title=Coronavirus: 80 Cities Across India Go Into Lockdown Till March 31. What It Means |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-covid-19-80-cities-across-india-go-into-lockdown-till-march-31-what-it-means-2198894 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=NDTV |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Inter-state movements are allowed during the lockdown period. However some states have closed their borders.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-outbreak-lockdown-in-delhi-uttar-pradesh-rajasthan-telangana-andhra-nagaland-full-details-1658523-2020-03-22|title=Coronavirus outbreak: States impose lockdown in battle against Covid-19 {{!}} All you need to know|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, [[Government of India|union]] and [[State government in india|state governments]] announced the lockdown of 75 districts where cases were reported.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus update: 75 cities across India under lockdown. Full list across states| url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-update-75-cities-across-india-under-lockdown-full-list-across-states-11584931492672.html|website=Livemint|author=| date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, [[Prime Minister of India|PM]] [[Narendra Modi]] announced a complete nationwide lockdown, starting from midnight for 21 days.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/narendra-modi-on-coronavirus-speech-live-updates-streaming-watch-india-pm-address-to-nation-on-covid-19-today-latest-news-lockdown-janata-curfew-8182241.html|title=Narendra Modi on Coronavirus Outbreak LIVE Updates: India under complete shutdown for 21 days starting 12 pm tonight, says PM|date=|work=Firstpost|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, in Telangana, the chief minister suggested that the lockdown should be extended by two weeks after April 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/india/news/lockdown-in-telangana-extended-till-june-3/articleshow/75014509.cms|title=Telangana CM suggests lockdown extension by two weeks|date=|website=Business Insder|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date= 6 April 2020}}</ref> On 8 April, the [[Government of Uttar Pradesh|Yogi government]] has ordered the hot spot areas of 15 districts of [[Uttar Pradesh]] to be sealed till 15 April.<ref>[https://www.timesnownews.com/india/article/up-15-district-name-uttar-pradesh-lockdown-latest-news-15-districts-sealed-list-and-what-it-means/575560t]{{dead link |date=April 2020}}</ref> [[Government of Odisha|Odisha]], [[Government of Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[Government of Maharashtra|Maharashtra]], and [[Government of West Bengal|West Bengal]] governments have extended the lockdown in their states till 30 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/odisha-becomes-first-state-to-extend-covid-19-lockdown-sets-april-30-as-new-date/story-MLEr0Zie3fXZWufT1lC2QM.html|title=Odisha becomes first state to extend Covid-19 lockdown; sets 30 April as new date|date=2020-04-09|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/punjab-extends-lockdown-till-april-30/articleshow/75082850.cms|title=Covid-19: Punjab extends lockdown till April 30|date=10 April 2020|work=Economictimes|access-date=10 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web |title=Maharashtra, West Bengal Extend Coronavirus Lockdown Till April 30 After Video-Meet With PM Narendra Modi| url=https://www.latestly.com/india/news/maharashtra-west-bengal-extend-coronavirus-lockdown-till-april-30-after-video-meet-with-pm-narendra-modi-1675139.html|website=Latestly|date= 11 April 2020|language=en|url-status=live|access-date= 11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April, [[Prime Minister of India|PM]] [[Narendra Modi]] extended nationwide lockdown till 3 May, and he also announced that after 20 April a conditional relaxation in lockdown will be given in some areas of the country where spread have been prevented or contained. <ref name=\"lockdownext\">{{cite web |title=PM Modi announces extension of lockdown till 3 May| url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/pm-modi-announces-extension-of-lockdown-till-3-may-11586839412073.html|website=Livemint|author=| date= April 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date= 14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Communication===\n{{Quote box\n| width = 24%\n| align = right\n| quote = 'Prepare, but don't panic' has been India's guiding mantra in dealing with the virus outbreak. Our region has reported less than 150 coronavirus cases, but we need to remain vigilant. Step-by-step approach helped avoid panic, made special efforts to reach out to vulnerable groups.\n| source = \u2014 Prime Minister Narendra Modi during the video conference with SAARC nations, 15 March 2020.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |title=India offers $10 mn for coronavirus emergency fund: PM Modi to SAARC leaders| url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/saarc-video-conference-live-we-evacuated-1-400-indians-from-different-countries-says-modi-11584273185030.html|website=Livemint|author=| date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n[[File:PM Modi\u2019s address to the nation on Corona Virus.webm|right|thumb|Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi's televised address about Coronavirus on 19 March 2020]]\n[[File:PM Modi's address to the nation on vital aspects relating to COVID-19 menace.webm|right|thumb|Modi's address about COVID-19 on 24 March 2020]]\nOn 19 March, during a 30-minute live telecast, [[Prime Minister of India|Indian Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] asked all citizens to observe '[[Janata Curfew]]' (people's curfew) on 7 am to 9 pm on 22 March. During this curfew he asked everyone, except those involved in essential services, to stay at home. He also asked people to avoid routine checkups and [[Elective surgery|elective surgeries]] to reduce the burden on the health system. He announced the formation of a [[COVID-19 Economic Response Task Force]]. To acknowledge the work being done by various sectors during the outbreak, he urged people to gather in front of their own doors, windows or balconies at 5 pm and applaud them for five minutes. State and local authorities were told to blow the siren to remind people about the same.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/-janata-curfew-and-other-highlights-from-pm-modi-s-address-to-the-nation-11584632651166.html|title='Janata Curfew' and other highlights from PM Modi's address to the nation|date=|work=Livemint|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 24 March, Modi announced a nationwide lockdown from midnight of that day, for a period of 21 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/india/covid-19-indian-pm-modi-announces-complete-lock-down-starting-march-25-1.1585060911566|title=COVID-19: Indian PM Modi announces complete lock down starting March 25|author=|website=gulfnews}}</ref> He also announced a {{INRConvert|15000|c}} aid for the healthcare sector. This money would be used for developing testing facilities, [[Personal protective equipment|PPEs]], [[Intensive care unit|ICUs]], [[Ventilators]] and for training medical workers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/rs-15000-crore-alloted-for-healthcare-to-fight-coronavirus-says-pm-modi/story/399119.html|title=Rs 15,000 crore allotted for healthcare to fight coronavirus, says PM Modi|website=www.businesstoday.in}}</ref> On 3 April, PM Modi addressed the nation to turn off the lights for nine minutes and lighting the [[candle]]s on 5 April.<ref>{{cite web |title=PM Modi urges countrymen to dispel the darkness spread by coronavirus by lighting a candles on April 5| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-modi-urges-countrymen-to-dispel-the-darkness-spread-by-coronavirus-by-lighting-a-candle-on-april-5/articleshow/74959545.cms|website=Economic Times|author=| date= 3 April 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date= 3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Legal announcements ====\n{{see also|Essential Services Maintenance Act|Essential Commodities Act}}\nOn 11 March 2020, the [[Cabinet Secretary of India]], [[Rajiv Gauba]], announced that all states and UTs should invoke provisions of Section 2 of the [[Epidemic Diseases Act, 1897]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/the-123-year-old-law-that-india-may-invoke-as-more-and-more-coronavirus-cases-emerge/articleshow/74593639.cms|title=The 123-year-old law that India may invoke to counter coronavirus|date=12 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/to-combat-coronavirus-india-invokes-provisions-of-colonial-era-epidemic-act-all-you-need-to-know-8142601.html|title=To combat coronavirus, India invokes provisions of colonial-era Epidemic Diseases Act: A look at what this means|last=|first=|date=12 March 2020|website=Firstpost|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, the union government declared the pandemic as a \"notified disaster\" under the [[Disaster Management Act, 2005]], enabling states to spend a larger part of funds from the State Disaster Response Fund to fight the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/india-declares-coronavirus-a-notified-disaster-lists-compensation-2194915|title=India Declares Coronavirus A Notified Disaster|last=|first=|date=14 March 2020|editor-last=Srinivasan|editor-first=Chandrashekar|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/india-declares-coronavirus-outbreak-as-a-notified-disaster-11584184739353.html|title=India declares coronavirus outbreak as a notified disaster|date=14 March 2020|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Evacuations===\n[[File:Minister visiting the Coronavirus Quarantine Centre 2.jpg|thumb|The Minister of State for Home Affairs, [[Nityanand Rai]] visiting evacuees at the Coronavirus Quarantine Centre, after completion of their requisite quarantine period, at the ITBP Chhawla Centre, in New Delhi on 13 March 2020.]]\nThe [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]] under [[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Minister]] [[Subrahmanyam Jaishankar]], [[Air India]] and the [[Indian Air Force]] have been successful in evacuating many Indian nationals and certain foreign nationals from the virus effected areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-special-flights-land-in-delhi-after-evacuation-from-japan-china-11582773171379.html|title=Coronavirus: Special flights land in Delhi after evacuation from Japan, China|first=Elizabeth|last=Roche|date=27 February 2020|website=Livemint|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228151542/https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-special-flights-land-in-delhi-after-evacuation-from-japan-china-11582773171379.html|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/india-extended-offer-of-evacuating-people-from-wuhan-to-all-its-neighbours-jaishankar-in-rajya-sabha/story-eoa4XVzKN3WGQFAsAEJP2H.html|title=India offered to evacuate students of all neighbours, says Jaishankar on Pak students in Wuhan|date=7 February 2020|website=Hindustan Times|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223060302/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/india-extended-offer-of-evacuating-people-from-wuhan-to-all-its-neighbours-jaishankar-in-rajya-sabha/story-eoa4XVzKN3WGQFAsAEJP2H.html|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/iaf-air-india-flights-evacuate-indians-foreigners-wuhan-japan-ship-1650379-2020-02-27|title=IAF evacuates 112 from coronavirus-hit Wuhan; Air India repatriates Indian crew from cruise ship|first1=|date=27 February 2020|website=India Today|access-date=2 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228162735/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/iaf-air-india-flights-evacuate-indians-foreigners-wuhan-japan-ship-1650379-2020-02-27|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* On 1 February, India evacuated 324 people which included three minors, 211 students and 110 working professionals from Wuhan region on its first [[Air India]] flight [[Emergency evacuation|evacuation]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://scroll.in/video/951794/its-empty-air-india-crews-first-reaction-to-landing-in-wuhan-airport-in-china-for-evacuation |title='It's empty': Air India crew's first reaction to landing in Wuhan airport in China for evacuation |date=1 February 2020 |access-date=4 February 2020 |work=scroll |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202175816/https://scroll.in/video/951794/its-empty-air-india-crews-first-reaction-to-landing-in-wuhan-airport-in-china-for-evacuation |archive-date=2 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/324-indians-leave-coronvirus-hit-wuhan-in-air-india-flight/article30707329.ece |title=Coronovirus outbreak: People flown in from China quarantined |date=1 February 2020 |access-date=4 February 2020 |work=The Hindu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204043752/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/324-indians-leave-coronvirus-hit-wuhan-in-air-india-flight/article30707329.ece |archive-date=4 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* On 2 February, India evacuated a second Air India flight carrying 323 Indians and seven [[Maldivians]] from Wuhan region.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/second-air-india-plane-evacuates-323-indians-from-coronavirus-hit-wuhan-in-china-2173454 |title=India Evacuates Second Batch Of 323 People From Coronavirus Epicentre |date=1 February 2020 |access-date=4 February 2020 |work=ndtv |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204103827/https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/second-air-india-plane-evacuates-323-indians-from-coronavirus-hit-wuhan-in-china-2173454 |archive-date=4 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/air-indias-2nd-flight-lands-in-delhi-with-323-indians-7-maldivians-from-coronavirus-hit-wuhan/article30718676.ece |title=Air India's 2nd flight lands in Delhi with 323 Indians, 7 Maldivians from coronavirus-hit Wuhan |date=1 February 2020 |access-date=4 February 2020 |work=The Hindu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203152544/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/air-indias-2nd-flight-lands-in-delhi-with-323-indians-7-maldivians-from-coronavirus-hit-wuhan/article30718676.ece |archive-date=3 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* On 7 February, [[Brazil]] evacuated 34 Brazilians, four Poles, a Chinese and an Indian national from Wuhan by Air Force planes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/2020/02/07/avioes-decolam-de-wuhan-na-china-com-40-passageiros-repatriados-ao-brasil-e-a-polonia.ghtml|title=Avi\u00f5es decolam de Wuhan, na China, com 40 passageiros repatriados ao Brasil e \u00e0 Pol\u00f4nia|website=G1|access-date=7 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208144310/https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/2020/02/07/avioes-decolam-de-wuhan-na-china-com-40-passageiros-repatriados-ao-brasil-e-a-polonia.ghtml|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* On 27 February, [[Indian Air Force]] evacuated 112 people from Wuhan, which included 76 Indian nationals and 36 foreign nationals (23 nationals from Bangladesh, 6 from China, 2 each from Myanmar and Maldives and one each from South Africa, USA and [[Madagascar]]). This was the third evacuation flight sent by India to Wuhan. India also provided 15 tonnes of medical assistance comprising masks, gloves and other emergency medical equipment to China through the same IAF flight.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Chaudhury|first=Dipanjan Roy|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-india-brings-back-36-foreigners-and-76-nationals-from-wuhan/articleshow/74328899.cms|title=Coronavirus: India brings back 36 foreigners and 76 nationals from Wuhan|date=27 February 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/iaf-air-india-flights-evacuate-indians-foreigners-wuhan-japan-ship-1650379-2020-02-27|title=IAF evacuates 112 from coronavirus-hit Wuhan; Air India repatriates Indian crew from cruise ship|last=DelhiFebruary 27|first=India Today Web Desk New|last2=February 27|first2=2020UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=28 February 2020|last3=Ist|first3=2020 09:34|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228162735/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/iaf-air-india-flights-evacuate-indians-foreigners-wuhan-japan-ship-1650379-2020-02-27|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day, 124 people \u2013 119 Indians and five nationals from Sri Lanka, Nepal, [[South Africa]] and [[Peru]] were evacuated from Japan by an Air India flight.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://pib.gov.in/PressReleseDetail.aspx?PRID=1606408|title=Press Information Bureau|website=pib.gov.in|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 10 March, Indian Air Force's [[Boeing C-17 Globemaster III|C-17 Globemaster]] transport aircraft evacuated 58 Indian pilgrims from Iran, the flight took off from [[Hindan Air Force Station|Hindon Air Base]], [[Ghaziabad, India|Ghaziabad]] on the evening of 9 March. It also brought back another 44 passengers on 11 March from Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/indian-air-force-to-fly-c-17-globemaster-to-evacuate-indians-from-coronavirus-affected-iran-1654005-2020-03-09|title=Coronavirus: IAF's C-17 Globemaster takes flight from Hindon airport to evacuate Indians from Iran|last=|first=|last2=|first2=|date=9 March 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 March 2020|last3=|first3=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-58-indians-evacuated-from-virus-hit-iran-more-to-come-foreign-minister-2192585|title=58 Indians Evacuated From Virus-Hit Iran, More To Come: Foreign Minister|website=NDTV.com|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n* On 11 March, 83 people were evacuated from Italy by [[Air India]]. The evacuees were 74 Indian citizens and 9 US citizens of Indian origin. All evacuees were placed under quarantine for 14 days in an army facility.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-83-evacuated-from-italy-put-in-army-s-manesar-quarantine-facility-1654529-2020-03-11|title=Coronavirus: 83 evacuated from Italy, put in Army's Manesar quarantine facility|first=Manjeet |last=Negi |date=11 March 2020|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 15 March, 218 Indians from Italy were evacuated by a special Air India flight. The evacuees brought to New Delhi will be shifted to Indo-Tibetan Border Police's camp in [[Chhawla]] area where they will be quarantined for 14 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/218-indians-from-coronavirus-hit-italy-land-in-delhi-will-be-quarantined-for-14-days/story-vYY3hbhcVC6F8wCW8kScGN.html|title= 218 Indians from coronavirus-hit Italy land in Delhi, will be quarantined for 14 days|date=15 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Later, 234 Indian nationals including 131 students and 103 pilgrims were evacuated from [[Iran]] who were quarantined for 14 days in Indian Army's wellness centre facility in [[Jaisalmer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/covid-19-234-indians-stranded-in-coronavirus-hit-iran-arrive-in-india/story-HePm2t2E3DYh2fZe1DfgIM.html|title=Covid-19: 234 Indians from coronavirus-hit Iran reach India|date=15 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/indians-brought-back-from-iran-reach-jaisalmer-coronavirus-quarantine-camp/story-TQ3PGtg97fgWQ9W9c1RXoJ.html|title=Indians brought back from Iran reach Jaisalmer coronavirus quarantine camp|date=15 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 16 March, 53 Indians which includes 52 students and 1 teacher were evacuated from [[Tehran]] and [[Shiraz]] cities of Iran and were then quarantined at Army wellness centre, Jaisalmer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-another-batch-of-53-indians-from-iran-arrives-to-be-moved-to-army-facility-in-jaisalmer-1655870-2020-03-16|title=Coronavirus: Another batch of 53 stranded in Iran return home, moved to Army facility in Jaisalmer|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 22 March, 263 Indians were evacuated by [[Air India]] from [[Rome]], [[Italy]] and then were quarantined at Indo-Tibetan Border Police's camp near [[Delhi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-263-indians-evacuated-from-italy-sent-to-itbp-quarantine/articleshow/74756441.cms|title=Coronavirus: 263 Indians evacuated from Italy sent to ITBP quarantine|date=22 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 29 March, 275 Indians who were evacuated from Iran landed in [[Jodhpur]], and after preliminary screening they were quarantined at Army Wellness Centre Jodhpur.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/another-batch-of-275-indians-evacuated-from-iran-reach-jodhpur-1660895-2020-03-29|title=Another batch of 275 Indians evacuated from Iran reach Jodhpur|work=India Today|agency=PTI|date=29 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Legal action ===\nOn 9 March, an [[First information report|FIR]] was lodged against a man in [[Arunachal Pradesh]] for allegedly posting misleading information on social media regarding the outbreak.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.hindustantimes.com/india-news/man-booked-for-sharing-misleading-info-on-coronavirus/story-5F2mcz6opjqWFVya6J9eUK.html|title=Man booked for sharing misleading info on coronavirus|date=|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 16 March, the father of a woman, whose husband had tested positive for coronavirus in [[Bangalore|Bengaluru]], was booked by [[Agra]] police for allegedly misleading authorities about the whereabouts of his daughter, who was a suspected patient.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2020/03/16/india-first-coronavirus-fir-father-of-techie-wife-who-fled-agra-booked.html|title=India's first coronavirus FIR: Father of infected techie's wife booked for 'misleading authorities'|date=|work=The Week|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 18 March, a case was registered against the owner of a furniture shop at [[Bhiwandi]] in [[Thane district]], [[Maharashtra]] for issuing a misleading advertisement which claimed that mattresses sold at his shop cured the disease.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/mar/18/fir-in-maharashtras-thane-over-advertisement-of-coronavirus-curing-mattress-2118380.html|title=FIR in Maharashtra's Thane over advertisement of 'coronavirus-curing' mattress|date=|work=The New Indian Express|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Lucknow]] police lodged an [[First information report|FIR]] against [[Bollywood]] singer, [[Kanika Kapoor]] for alleged negligence in compliance of necessary directives post her return from [[London]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.hindustantimes.com/lucknow/kanika-kapoor-booked-for-negligence-after-leaving-a-trail-of-quarantined-vips/story-QfNRessOzhF4Ieqks9Zz5N.html|title=Kanika Kapoor booked for negligence after leaving a trail of quarantined VIPs|date=|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 21 March, a chemist was booked for allegedly selling [[N95 mask]]s at over four times higher than the fixed price in [[Himachal Pradesh]]'s [[Kangra district]].<ref>{{cite news |title=FIR against Chemist for Selling N95 Masks at Four Times of Fixed Price in HP's Kangra |url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/fir-against-chemist-for-selling-n95-masks-at-four-times-of-fixed-price-in-hps-kangra-2545919.html |accessdate=28 March 2020 |publisher=News18 India |date=28 March 2020}}</ref> On 24 March, a 54-year-old man from [[Ernakulam]], who landed from [[Chennai]] at the [[Cochin International Airport]] on 23 March, was arrested for refusing to follow instructions given by doctors.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/coronavirus-india-latest-updates-almost-all-of-india-is-in-lockdown/articleshow/74785133.cms|title=Domestic air passenger arrested in Kochi for refusing to follow norms to check coronavirus spread|date=|work=Times of India|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> A case was registered against a [[Coca-Cola]] plant in [[Himachal Pradesh]] for operating in violation of lockdown order.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/fir-against-coca-cola-factory-in-hp-for-violation-of-coronavirus-lockdown-11585029163888.html|title=FIR against Coca Cola factory in HP for violation of coronavirus lockdown|date=|work=Livemint|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> 255 people in [[West Bengal]] were arrested for violating restriction order and were prosecuted under [[Indian Penal Code|IPC]] section 188.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.huffingtonpost.in/entry/coronavirus-west-bengal-2-new-cases_in_5e799776c5b62f90bc506514|title=2 New Coronavirus Cases In West Bengal, 255 Arrested For Violating Restriction Orders While s|date=|work=Huffington Post|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> A man was arrested for hosting a party during the lockdown in [[Andhra Pradesh]]'s [[West Godavari district]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsmeter.in/man-arrested-for-hosting-party-during-lockdown-in-aps-west-godavari-district/|title=Man arrested for hosting party during lockdown in AP's West Godavari district|last=Network|first=Newsmeter|date=24 March 2020|website=NewsMeter|language=en-US|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> Hyderabad traffic police seized 2,480 vehicles for violating the lockdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsmeter.in/hyderabad-traffic-police-seize-2480-vehicles-for-violating-lockdown/|title=Hyderabad traffic police seize 2,480 vehicles for violating lockdown|last=Network|first=Newsmeter|date=24 March 2020|website=NewsMeter|language=en-US|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> On 25 March, two people were booked under sections 353, 188 and other relevant provisions of the [[Indian Penal Code|IPC]] and [[Disaster Management Act, 2005]] for allegedly abusing and manhandling policemen during the lockdown at [[Kalyan]] in [[Maharashtra]]'s [[Thane district]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/maha-two-booked-for-manhandling-cops-during-covid19-lockdown/1779337|title=Maha: Two booked for manhandling cops during COVID-19 lockdown|date=|work=Outlook India|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 March, [[Delhi]] police arrested a 40-year-old man and seized his [[scooty]] for allegedly calling a [[Northeast India|northeastern]] woman \"coronavirus\" and spitting [[paan]] at her.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.ndtv.com/delhi-news/man-arrested-for-calling-northeast-woman-corona-spitting-on-her-delhi-police-2200793|title=Man Arrested For Calling Northeast Woman \"Corona\", Spitting On Her: Delhi Police|date=|work=NDTV|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 27 March, an [[Infosys]] employee from [[Bengaluru]] was arrested for his social media post that encouraged people to venture out and spread the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Infosys Employee Arrested Over \"Spread-The-Virus\" Post, Company Sacks Him |url=https://www.ndtv.com/karnataka-news/coronavirus-lockdown-india-infosys-employee-arrested-over-spread-the-virus-post-company-sacks-him-2201926 |accessdate=28 March 2020 |publisher=NDTV |date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Three people were arrested for circulating a fake audio clip which suggested that 59 fresh cases were reported in [[Nagpur]], [[Maharashtra]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Three arrested for making fake audio clip of Nagpur reeling with '59 positive' cases |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/three-arrested-for-making-fake-audio-clip-of-nagpur-reeling-with-59-positive-cases/articleshow/74841275.cms |accessdate=27 March 2020 |publisher=Times of India |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> A 29-year-old woman was arrested in [[Kolkata]] for allegedly spreading rumours related to the outbreak by posting fake news on social media.<ref>{{cite news |title=In Kolkata, woman arrested for spreading coronavirus rumours on social media |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/woman-arrested-in-kolkata-for-spreading-rumours-on-coronavirus-on-social-media/story-Oo9qJYBQhOwcAfN9HwUjTN.html |accessdate=28 March 2020 |publisher=Hindustan Times |date=28 March 2020}}</ref> [[Patna]] police arrested three policemen for allegedly shooting at a driver of a vehicle carrying potatoes and asking for a bribe of {{INRConvert|5000||lk=|year=2020}}.<ref>{{cite news |title=Covid-19 lockdown: Three Bihar policemen arrested for shooting at van driver, demanding bribe |url=https://scroll.in/latest/957396/covid-19-lockdown-three-bihar-policemen-shoot-at-van-driver-demand-bribe-arrested |accessdate=28 March 2020 |publisher=Scroll |date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== State government response ===\n{{Main|Indian local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic}}\nState governments took various measures to contain the spread of the virus.\n\n===International relations===\nOn 26 February, India sent 15 tons of [[Surgical mask|masks]], gloves and other emergency medical equipment by an Indian Air Force jet to [[China]]. The medical supplies sent to China include one hundred thousand masks, five hundred thousand pairs of gloves, 75 infusion pumps, and 30 internal feeding pumps.<ref>{{cite web |title=India provided 15 tonnes of medical supplies worth Rs 2.11 crore to coronavirus-hit China: Government| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-provided-15-tonnes-of-medical-supplies-worth-rs-2-11-crore-to-coronavirus-hit-china-government/amp_articleshow/74693578.cms|website=Economic times|author=|date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, Modi proposed that [[SAARC]] nations jointly fight the pandemic, an idea that was welcomed by the leaders of [[Nepal]], [[Maldives]], [[Sri Lanka]] [[Bhutan]], [[Bangladesh]], and [[Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/pm-modi-bats-for-joint-saarc-strategy-to-fight-coronavirus-gets-prompt-support-from-neighbours/articleshow/74616095.cms|title=PM Modi bats for joint Saarc strategy to fight coronavirus, gets prompt support from neighbours |last=13 Mar|agency=PTI |last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=14 March 2020|last3=Ist|first3=20:51}}</ref> On 15 March, after a video conference of [[SAARC]] leaders,<ref name=\":5\"/> he allocated {{INRConvert|74|c|lk=on|year=2020}} of funds classified as COVID-19 Emergency Fund for the SAARC countries.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOn 4 April, the Government of India banned the export of [[hydroxychloroquine]] \"without any exception\", in order to stockpile supplies for domestic use.<ref name=\"Caravan HCQ\">\nVidya Krishnan, [https://caravanmagazine.in/healt/covid-19-hydroxychloroquine-hcq-export-ban-lifted-donald-trump Stuck in a policy haze, government takes back export ban on COVID-19 related drug HCQ], The Caravan, 7 April 2020.\n</ref>\nThe United States, which imports half its supply of the drug from India and expects to use it for treating COVID patients, grew concerned. The US President [[Donald Trump]] called Prime Minister Modi the next day, and hinted at possible retaliation in a press conference. India agreed to allow its export on \"humanitarian grounds\".<ref name=\"LA Times HCQ\">\nShashank Bengali, Vidya Krishnan, [https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-04-07/india-ship-hydroxychloroquine-u-s India says it will ship hydroxychloroquine to U.S. after Trump threatens retaliation], Los Angeles Times, 7 April 2020.\n</ref>{{refn|group=note|Apart from the US, India had outstanding orders for Hydroxychloroquine from some 30 countries, including Brazil, Spain, France, UK, Germany, Australia, the Gulf countries and the SAARC neighbours. The decision to partially lift the ban preceded President Trump's comment on possible retaliation.<ref>Nayanima Basu, [https://theprint.in/diplomacy/india-partially-lifts-ban-on-export-of-hydroxychloroquine-hours-after-trumps-threat/396792/ India partially lifts ban on export of hydroxychloroquine to help US, others fight Covid-19], The Print, 7 April 2020.</ref>}}\n\nOn 11 April, India sent a team of 15 doctors and health care professionals to [[Kuwait]] to assist in its fight against coronavirus, following a telephone conversion between prime minister Modi and the Kuwaiti prime minister [[Sabah Al-Khalid Al-Sabah]]. Kuwait was facing 1,154 COVID-19 cases at this time.<ref>[https://www.livemint.com/news/india/covid-19-india-sends-a-team-of-doctors-medical-staff-to-kuwait-11586618621306.html Covid-19: India sends a team of doctors, medical staff to Kuwait], livemint, 11 April 2020.</ref><ref> [https://gulfnews.com/world/gulf/kuwait/rapid-response-team-from-india-reaches-kuwait-to-combat-covid-19-1.1586619932751 Rapid response team from India reaches Kuwait to combat COVID-19], Gulf News, 11 April 2020.</ref>\n\n===Aarogya Setu===\nThe Indian Government launched a smart phone application called '''Aarogya Setu''' to help in \"contact tracing and containing the spread\" of COVID-19 pandemic in the nation. The [[World Bank]] lauded the early deployment of such technology to combat the pandemic. Global technology giants Apple and Google announced on 11 April, that they will taken up the building of software for smartphones which would help in contact tracing, just as the Aarogya Setu application does.<ref> https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/with-aarogya-setu-app-india-has-shown-the-way-says-world-bank/articleshow/75113753.cms </ref><ref> https://m.economictimes.com/tech/software/how-to-use-aarogya-setu-app-and-find-out-if-you-have-covid-19-symptoms/articleshow/75023152.cms </ref>\n\n== Testing and countermeasures ==\n=== Testing ===\n[[File:Covid-testing kiosk.jpg|thumb|A sample collection kiosk for COVID-19 testing in Kerala]]\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float:right; clear:right;\"\n|+Summary of test results\n!Samples tested\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |217,554\n|-\n!Tests per 1 million people\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |{{formatnum:{{#expr:217554/1352642280*1000000 round 0}}}}\n|-\n!Tested individuals\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |202,551\n|-\n!Tested positive\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |9,341\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:right;\" |{{As of|2020|April|12}}<ref name=\"ICMRtests\"/>\n|}\nThe Union Health Ministry's war room and policy making team in New Delhi consists of the ministry's Emergency Medical Response Unit, the [[Integrated Disease Surveillance Programme|Central Surveillance Unit (IDSP)]], the [[National Centre for Disease Control|National Centre for Disease Control (NCDC)]] and experts from three government hospitals.<ref name=\":0a\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/coronavirus-war-room-india-in-mission-mode/story-NHYzzcrmFUDg19lPUSbjVM.html|title=How conference hall at health ministry emerged as coronavirus-control war-room|last=Sharma|first=Sanchita|date=5 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307150726/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/coronavirus-war-room-india-in-mission-mode/story-NHYzzcrmFUDg19lPUSbjVM.html|archive-date=7 March 2020|accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref> They are part of policy decisions to decide how coronavirus should be tackled in the country.<ref name=\":0a\" /> A cluster-containment strategy is mainly being adopted, similar to how India contained previous epidemics, as well as \"breaking the chain of transmission\".<ref name=\":0a\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2020/03/13/delhi-declares-coronavirus-as-epidemic-as-india-reports-first-death-from-infection.html|title=Delhi declares coronavirus as epidemic as India reports first death from infection|website=The Week|language=en|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/04/812013578/covid-19-we-can-push-this-virus-back-who-leader-says-of-coronavirus|title=COVID-19: 'We Can Push This Virus Back,' WHO Leader Says Of Coronavirus|website=NPR.org|language=en|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> 15 labs across India led by the [[National Institute of Virology|National Institute of Virology (NIV), Pune]], are testing for the virus, with more labs being trained.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Biswas|first=Soutik|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51747932|title=Is India prepared for a coronavirus outbreak?|date=7 March 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=7 March 2020|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307055219/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51747932|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 14 March [[Viral Research and Diagnostic Laboratories#Labs|65 labs]] were named capable for testing for the virus (though as of 17 March not all are fully functional).<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=We need to ramp up testing facilities|date=17 March 2020|work=The Times of India (print edition)|access-date=|url-status=live|page=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/pulse/956110/is-india-testing-enough-for-coronavirus-cases|title=Is India testing enough for coronavirus cases?|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus test in India: Complete list of testing sites for coronavirus in India|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/52-testing-sites-for-coronavirus-in-india/articleshow/74547684.cms |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, scientists at the National Institute of Virology isolated a strain of the novel coronavirus. By doing so, India became the fifth country to successfully obtain a pure sample of the virus after China, Japan, Thailand and the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/fewer-cases-but-india-becomes-5th-country-to-isolate-coronavirus/articleshow/74620323.cms|title=Coronavirus cases in India: Fewer cases, but India becomes 5th country to isolate coronavirus {{!}} India News - Times of India|first=N|last=Durgesh|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Indian Council of Medical Research]] (ICMR) said that isolation of the virus will help towards expediting the development of drugs, vaccines and rapid diagnostic kits in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/covid-19-india-becomes-5th-country-globally-to-isolate-virus-strain-11584102221498.html|title=India becomes fifth country to isolate Covid-19 virus strain|last=Sharma|first=Neetu Chandra|date=13 March 2020|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> NIV has shared two SARS-CoV-2 genome sequences with [[GISAID]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Prasad|first=R.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/science/coronavirus-india-shares-two-sars-cov-2-genome-sequences/article31007227.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} India shares two SARS-CoV-2 genome sequences|date=7 March 2020|work=The Hindu|access-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307064132/https://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/science/coronavirus-india-shares-two-sars-cov-2-genome-sequences/article31007227.ece|archive-date=7 March 2020|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nInitially, the labs tested samples only from those with a travel history to 12 countries designated as high-risk, or those who have come in contact with anyone testing positive for the coronavirus, or showing symptoms as per the government guidelines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/testing-must-be-done-on-war-footing/story-4gI2HWQ2WLhVLFOm5rsioM.html|title=India needs a more aggressive testing regimen for coronavirus: Experts|date=15 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://caravanmagazine.in/health/public-health-experts-raise-concerns-about-india-restricted-testing-covid-19|title=Public-health experts raise concerns about India's restricted testing for COVID-19|last=Krishnan|first=Vidya|website=The Caravan|language=en|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> On 20 March, the government decided to also include all pneumonia cases, regardless of travel or contact history after the country saw a sharp increase in the number of cases.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/coronavirus/covid-19-india-test-coronavirus-pneumonia-6324733/|title=Covid-19 testing in India extended to all pneumonia cases: Govt|date=21 March 2020|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> The first and second confirmatory tests for the virus has been made free by the government.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/first-and-second-confirmatory-tests-for-covid-19-are-free-sanjeeva-kumar20200315173303/|title=First and second confirmatory tests for COVID-19 are free: Sanjeeva Kumar|website=ANI News|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 9 April, ICMR further revised the testing strategy and allowed testing of the people showing symptoms for a week in the hotspot areas of the country, regardless of travel history or local contact to a patient.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-testing-strategy-revised-in-india-ambit-widened-2209126|title=Coronavirus Testing Strategy Revised In India, Ambit Widened|website= NDTV.com|date=2020-04-09|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> As of 14 March, the [[National Institute of Virology]] (NIV) has tested around 5,900 samples from individuals across the country. The number of tests per million in the country was 5 as of 14 March. In comparison, it is 26 in US, 76 in Japan, 1,005 in Italy and 4,099 in South Korea.<ref name=\":3\" /> There are concerns that testing for the virus in India is being inadequately conducted and the need for ramping up the scale of testing is a necessity to understand the real scope of the number of people affected.<ref name=\":9\">{{cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/latest/trends/india-grossly-under-tested-on-coronavirus-urgent-steps-needed-to-ramp-up-testing/story/398488.html|title=India grossly under-tested on coronavirus; urgent steps needed to ramp up testing|last=Sharma|first=Kumar|date=17 March 2020|website=[[Business Today (India)|Business Today]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Ministry of Health said that only 10 per cent of test capacity has been utilised per day as of 15 March,<ref name=\":6\" /> claiming that the amount of tests were enough. However experts thought they were not, saying that [[Transmission (medicine)|community transmission]] may go undetected without adequate testing.<ref name=\":3\" /> They also wanted to add more testing centres by inclusion of private laboratories.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> In mid-March the government authorised accredited private labs to test for the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/accredited-private-labs-to-be-allowed-to-test-for-covid-19/articleshow/74664414.cms|title=Coronavirus testing lab: Accredited private labs to be allowed to test for Covid-19|last=Jha|first=Durgesh Nandan|date=17 March 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nTesting for community transmission began on 15 March. 65 laboratories of the Department of Health Research and the [[Indian Council of Medical Research]] (DHR-ICMR) have started testing random samples of people who exhibit flu-like symptoms and samples from patients without any travel history or contact with infected persons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/icmr-to-test-for-community-transmission-of-covid-19-6313521/|title=ICMR to test for community transmission of Covid-19|date=14 March 2020|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Thacker|first=Teena|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/will-know-if-indias-going-through-community-transmission-icmr/articleshow/74663239.cms|title=Will know if India is going through community transmission of Covid-19: ICMR|date=17 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> As of 18 March, no evidence of community transmission was found after results of 500 random samples tested negative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-still-in-phase-2-of-coronavirus-outbreak-confirms-icmr/articleshow/74673951.cms|title=Covid-19 outbreak: No evidence of community transmission, says ICMR|date=18 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> Between February 15 and April 2, 5,911 SARI (Severe Acute Respiratory Illnesses) patients were tested throughout the country of which, 104 tested positive (1.8%) in 20 states and union territories. About 40% of the identified patients did not have travel history or any history of contact with a positive patient.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-india-second-icmr-report-random-sampling-test-results-shows-possible-community-transmission-1665290-2020-04-10|title=Coronavirus: Second ICMR report on random sampling test results shows possible community transmission|last=Sharma|first=Milan|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The ICMR advised to prioritise containment in the 36 districts of 15 states which had reported positive cases among SARI patients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/icmr-suggests-containment-36-districts-after-many-with-respiratory-infection-test-covid19-positive-1665278-2020-04-10|title=ICMR suggests containment in 36 districts after many with respiratory infection test Covid-19 positive|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, The [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare|Union Ministry of Health]] has decided to allow private pathology labs to test for COVID-19. The ministry official said that only the government lab is allowed to test the coronavirus. By allowing private labs, the work of testing can be doubled. The ministry said that about 60 private labs may soon be allowed for this.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web |title=Metropolis among private labs short-listed for coronavirus testing| url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/metropolis-among-private-labs-short-listed-for-coronavirus-testing/article31090208.ece|website=thehindu|author=}}</ref> Once set up, a person can get COVID-19 test done at a private lab after a qualified physician in a government facility recommends it.<ref>{{cite web |title=Health Ministry to allow accredited private labs to conduct tests for coronavirus|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/health-ministry-to-allow-accredited-private-labs-to-conduct-tests-for-coronavirus-814595.html|website=Deccan herald|author=|date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The ICMR has appealed to the private labs to offer the tests for free as the government labs do.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nOn 18 March, A top health ministry official said that a Swiss private company named [[Roche Diagnostics]] has been given the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) emergency approval to conduct tests for coronavirus. The Indian regulator has given them a licence to conduct diagnostic tests of the virus on 17 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Roche Diagnostics India first private firm to get COVID-19 test approval| url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/india/story/roche-diagnostics-india-first-private-firm-to-get-covid-19-test-approval-1656965-2020-03-18|website=indiatoday|author=}}</ref> The [[Drug Controller General of India]] (DCGI) was assessing giving another firm license while two Indian diagnostic companies have also sought approval for the coronavirus testing kits developed by them.<ref>{{cite web |title=Roche Diagnostics India First Private Firm to Get COVID-19 Test Approval| url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/roche-diagnostics-india-first-private-firm-to-get-covid-19-test-approval-2541493.html|website=news18|author=}}</ref> The government has also issued guidelines to cap the cost of sample testing by private labs at {{Indian Rupee|4500}}.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-test-should-not-cost-more-than-rs-4500-government-to-private-labs/articleshow/74753826.cms|title=Coronavirus test should not cost more than Rs 4,500: Government to private labs|date=22 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, Ramanan Laxminarayan, director of the [[Center for Disease Dynamics, Economics & Policy]] stated that India could be facing a \"tsunami of cases within a few weeks\" as testing increases and the reason for the low number of confirmed cases currently is due to under-testing. He also said that according to mathematical models applied in the US or UK at least 20%-60% of the population will be affected. Applying the same models in India means that at the lower end of the estimate there could be 300 million cases of which 4-8 million could be severe.<ref>{{cite web |title=India must prepare for a tsunami of cases| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-asia-india-51962813/india-must-prepare-for-a-tsunami-of-coronavirus-cases|website=www.bbc.com|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n111 additional labs for testing became functional on 21 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/111-labs-for-testing-coronavirus-will-be-functional-across-india-from-today-health-ministry-1658235-2020-03-21|title=111 labs for testing coronavirus will be functional across India from today: Health Ministry|date=|work=India Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, [[Pune]]-based [[Molecular diagnostics|molecular diagnostic]] company [[Mylab Discovery Solutions]] became the first Indian company to have received validation for its [[Reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction|RT-PCR]] tests from [[National Institute of Virology]] and the [[Indian Council of Medical Research]] (ICMR). The test takes 2.5 hours and the company is looking to price it at around {{INRConvert|1200||lk=|year=2020}}, or Rs 80,000 for a 100 test kit.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pune based Mylab becomes first Indian company to get Covid-19 test kits validated | url=https://m.economictimes.com/industry/healthcare/biotech/healthcare/pune-based-mylab-becomes-first-indian-co-to-get-its-covid-19-test-kits-validated/articleshow/74785575.cms|website=Economic times|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=India can double coronavirus test kits to 200,000 in a week, thanks to Pune-based Mylabs| url=https://www.businessinsider.in/india/news/india-can-double-coronavirus-test-kits-to-200000-in-a-week-thanks-to-pune-based-mylabs/articleshow/74787231.cms|website=Business Standard|author=}}</ref>\n\nTill April, [[Institute of Genomics and Integrative Biology]] of Delhi had developed low cost paper-strip test that could detect COVID within an hour. Each test would cost {{INRConvert|500||lk=|year=2020}} and method could fulfill India's rapid need of testing.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Srishti Choudhury|title=India's first paper-strip test for Covid-19, CSIR lab makes a breakthrough|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/india-s-first-paper-strip-test-for-covid-19-csir-lab-makes-a-breakthrough-11585832200999.html|publisher=LiveMint|date=2020-04-02|accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ICMR, 217,554 samples from 202,551 individuals have been tested as of 13 April and 9,341 individuals have been confirmed positive.<ref name=\"ICMRtests\">{{cite web|url=https://icmr.nic.in/sites/default/files/whats_new/ICMR_testing_update_13April_9PM_IST.pdf|title=SARS-CoV-2 (COVID-19) Testing: Status Update 13 April 2020 9:00 PM IST|last=|first=|date=13 April 2020|website=[[Indian Council of Medical Research]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India testing data}}\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Treatment ===\nIn Rajasthan, a combination of anti-malaria, anti-Swine flu and anti-HIV drugs resulted into recovery of three patients in March.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Combination of two anti-HIV drugs proved crucial in Coronavirus treatment, Rajasthan official|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/combination-of-two-anti-hiv-drugs-proved-crucial-in-coronavirus-treatment-rajasthan-official/articleshow/74653762.cms|newspaper=The Economic Times|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> In same month, [[Indian Institute of Chemical Technology]], [[Council of Scientific and Industrial Research]] and [[Cipla]] corporation, launched a joint venture to develop anti-COVID-19 drugs.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Health: CSIR-IICT ties up with Cipla to develop anti-COVID-19 drug|url=https://health.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/pharma/csir-iict-ties-up-with-cipla-to-develop-anti-covid-19-drug/74693465|newspaper=The Economic Times|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Another Indian firm Stempeutics plans to introduce a stem-based agent for treating COVID patients in critical situation.<ref>{{Cite news|author=K Giriprakash|title=Stempeutics ties up with a consortium of stem cell firms for end-stage Covid-19 treatment|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/stempeutics-ties-up-with-a-consortium-of-stem-cell-firms-for-end-stage-covid-19-treatment/article31290232.ece|publisher=Business Line|date=2020-04-09|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March, Pune based SciTech Park'startup incubatee introduced ''Airon'', a negative ion generator capable of reducing a room's viral load by 99.7%.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Indian Ministry of Science and Technology|title=Technology by Pune based Startup incubatee of Scitech Park to disinfect Maharashtra hospitals in Covid 19 fight|url=https://pib.gov.in/PressReleseDetail.aspx?PRID=1609269|publisher=Press Information bureau|date=2020-03-30|accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref> Following early April, funds for a  number of preventive agents were released to initiate research.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Indian Ministry of Science and Technology|title=DST approves funding for developing a gel for nasal passage as prevention for COVID 19|url=https://pib.gov.in/PressReleseDetail.aspx?PRID=1612161|publisher=Press Information bureau|date=2020-04-08|accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=Indian Ministry of Science and Technology|title=SCTIMST scientists design super absorbent material for safe management of infected respiratory secretions|url=https://pib.gov.in/PressReleseDetail.aspx?PRID=1612412|publisher=Press Information bureau|date=2020-04-09|accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, the National Task Force for COVID19 constituted by [[Indian Council of Medical Research]] recommended the use of [[hydroxychloroquine]] for treatment of COVID19 for high-risk cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abplive.com/news/india/coronavirus-india-live-updates-covid-19-confirmed-cases-nears-400-mark-narendra-modi-1180287|title=Coronavirus Live Updates: Total Count Of Positive Covid-19 Cases Jump To 562; Ten Deaths Reported So Far|last=Bureau|first=ABP News|date=22 March 2020|website=news.abplive.com|language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nVarious Indian [[Public Sector Undertaking|PSUs]], firms and start ups including [[DRDO]] and [[ISRO]], have repurposed their production lines to manufacture general PPEs, full body suits and ventilators and designing low cost or mobile medical equipment.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Nikita Prasad|title=Kudos! Indian Railways manufactures low-cost ventilator prototype for COVID-19 patients in a week\u2019s time|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/infrastructure/railways/kudos-indian-railways-manufactures-low-cost-ventilator-prototype-for-covid-19-patients-in-a-weeks-time/1919953/|publisher=Financial Express|date=2020-04-06|accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=Sharmishte Datti|title=ISRO Puts Rockets, Satellites On Hold To Develop Ventilators For Coronavirus|url=https://www.gizbot.com/news/coronavirus-effect-isro-shifts-focus-to-ventilators-066694.html|publisher=GizBot|date=2020-03-31|accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=Manu Pubby|title=Low cost, high volume products being developed; DRDO chief says scientists rising to the occasion|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/defence/local-defence-technology-helps-fight-covid-19/articleshow/74958610.cms|publisher=The Economic Times|date=2020-04-04|accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=Archana Shukla|title=Bengaluru-based Skanray aims to make 1 lakh ventilators, opens up design IP|url=https://www.cnbctv18.com/healthcare/bengaluru-based-skanray-aims-to-make-1-lakh-ventilators-opens-up-design-ip-5540741.htm|publisher=CNBC TV18|date=2020-03-23|accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref> The focus remains to attain innovation and increased production of low cost, compact and portable and multi patient ventilators. Milestones included realisation of world's smallest and cheapest ventilators.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Kundan Jha|title=\u2018India using innovation as arsenal to fight coronavirus\u2019|url=https://www.sundayguardianlive.com/business/india-using-innovation-arsenal-fight-coronavirus|publisher=The Sunday Guardian|date=2020-04-11|accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n[[Centre for Cellular and Molecular Biology]] has been working on [[genome sequencing]] of COVID 19.<ref>{{Cite news|author=M Ramesh|title=CSIR lab working on genome sequencing of Covid-19|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/science/csir-lab-working-on-genome-sequencing-of-covid-19/article31175131.ece|publisher=Business Line|date=2020-03-26|accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nPune-based [[Serum Institute of India]] is expected to apply for clinical trials of certain strains from [[Drug Controller General of India]]. As per company president [[Adar Poonawalla]], a vaccine for COVID-19 will be delivered within an year, however, it may not be effective on 20 to 30% people.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Coronavirus vaccine within a year but it won't be 100% effective|url=https://m.economictimes.com/industry/healthcare/biotech/healthcare/coronavirus-vaccine-within-a-year-but-it-wont-be-100-effective/articleshow/74704452.cms|newspaper=The Economic Times|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Of other two companies trying to develop COVID 19 vaccine in India, one being [[Zydus Cadila]], replicating [[viral vector]] and developing [[DNA vaccination|DNA plasmid vaccine]]<ref>{{Cite news|author=PB Jayakumar|title=Zydus Cadila, Serum Institute too in the hunt for coronavirus vaccine|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/mail-today/story/zydus-cadila-serum-institute-too-in-the-hunt-for-coronavirus-vaccine-1663434-2020-04-05|publisher=India Today|date=2020-04-05|accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> and other being Hyderabad based Bharat Biotech in collaboration with US based FluGen, expecting first clinical trials of a nasal vaccine by late 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Hyderabad-based biotech firm working on nasal vaccine for Covid-19|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/india/story/hyderabad-based-working-on-nasal-vaccine-for-covid-19-1662976-2020-04-03|publisher=India Today|date=2020-04-03|accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Till early second half of February, [[Serum Institute of India]] had begun animal trials of it COVID vaccine candidates<ref>{{Cite news|author=Pankaj P. Khelkar|title=Indian company first to test coronavirus vaccine on animals, human trials expected in 6 months|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/indian-company-serum-institute-india-pune-1st-develop-novel-coronavirus-vaccine-1648128-2020-02-19|publisher=India Today|date=2020-02-19|accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref> followed by [[Zydus Cadila]] in March.<ref>{{Cite news|title=The experiment of coronavirus vaccine on animals started in India, hopefully desired results will come in 4-6 months|url=https://www.inventiva.co.in/stories/inventiva/the-experiment-of-coronavirus-vaccine-on-animals-started-in-india-hopefully-desired-results-will-come-in-4-6-months/|publisher=Inventia|date=2020-04-08|accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\n===Commercial establishments===\nOn 19 March, [[Delhi]] chief minister [[Arvind Kejriwal]] announced the closure of all restaurants in the capital by 31 March in view of the ever increasing case of coronavirus. He said that there will be a ban on eating in restaurants but food delivery will continue. He also said that 20 or more people will not be allowed to unite anywhere in the state.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kejriwal govt orders Delhi restaurants to shut shop with immediate effect until 31 March| url=https://theprint.in/india/kejriwal-govt-orders-delhi-restaurants-to-shut-shop-with-immediate-effect-until-31-march/384034/|website=theprint|author=}}</ref> On 20 March, in [[Lucknow]] all restaurants, hotels, sweet shops have been closed till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: All eateries in Lucknow to be closed till March 31| url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/coronavirus-all-eateries-in-lucknow-closed-till-march-31-599973|website=indiatvnews|author=}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, Delhi government announced that all malls in [[Delhi]] will close with only vegetable, grocery and medicine shops remaining open.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/north-and-central/all-delhi-malls-to-be-closed-grocery-and-pharmacy-stores-exempted-cm-arvind-kejriwal-815679.html|title=All Delhi malls to be closed, grocery and pharmacy stores exempted: CM Arvind Kejriwal|author=|first=|date=20 March 2020|website=Deccan herald|agency=PTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=All Delhi malls to be closed, grocery and pharmacy stores exempt: Arvind Kejriwal| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/all-delhi-malls-to-be-closed-grocery-and-pharmacy-stores-exempt-arvind-kejriwal/articleshow/74728178.cms|website=Economic times|author=}}</ref> Shops in [[Mumbai]], [[Pune]] and Nagpur will remain closed till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mumbai Lockdown: Many markets and shops in lockdown mode due to Coronavirus| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/mumbai/virus-effect-many-mumbai-markets-and-shops-in-lockdown-mode/amp_articleshow/74726223.cms|website=timesofindia|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus in Maharashtra: All non-essential shops, offices to shut in Mumbai, Nagpur, Pune| url=https://m.businesstoday.in/lite/story/coronavirus-in-maharashtra-govt-orders-lockdown-of-offices-shops-as-cases-rise-to-52/1/398774.html|website=Business standard|author=}}</ref> During this period, the essential services will continue. Medical services will be available.<ref>{{cite web |title=Maharashtra CM Announces Lockdown In Mumbai, Pune, Nagpur And Pimpri\n| url=https://curlytales.com/maharashtra-cm-announces-lockdown-in-mumbai-pune-nagpur-and-pimpri/|website=curlytales|author=}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] chief minister [[Amarinder Singh]] has said that in view of coronavirus, the state has ordered lockdown till 31 March. All essential government services will continue and shops for essential goods such as food, medicines etc. will remain open.<ref>{{cite web |title=Punjab to enforce lockdown till March 31| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/punjab-to-enforce-lockdown-till-march-31/articleshow/74756389.cms|website=Economic Times|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Punjab Becomes 5th State to Declare Partial COVID-19 Lockdown as India-Wide Cases Soar to 324| url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/punjab-5th-state-to-announce-coronavirus-lockdown-as-india-wide-cases-soar-to-324-2546229.html|website=news18|author=}}</ref> The chief minister of [[Rajasthan]] [[Ashok Gehlot]] said public vehicle will be banned till 31 March, along with all the malls and shops will remain closed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Ashok Gehlot orders lockdown in Rajasthan till March 31, exempts essential services| url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/west/coronavirus-ashok-gehlot-orders-lockdown-in-rajasthan-till-march-31-exempts-essential-services-816329.html|website=Deccan Herald|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Rajasthan announces complete lockdown till March 31| url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/coronavirus-rajasthan-announces-complete-lockdown-till-march-31/article31133432.ece|website=The hindu|author=}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nOn 16 March, the union government declared a countrywide lock-down of schools and colleges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/mumbai-s-siddhivinayak-temple-to-close-entry-for-devotees-from-today-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-2195660|title=Schools Closed, Travel To Be Avoided, Says Centre On Coronavirus: 10 Points|website=NDTV.com|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 18 March, [[Central Board of Secondary Education|CBSE]] released revised guidelines for examination centres.<ref>{{cite web |title=CBSE Board advises social distancing, face masks at exam centres to prevent coronavirus| url=https://m.hindustantimes.com/education/cbse-board-advises-social-distancing-face-masks-at-exam-centres-to-prevent-coronavirus/story-anUZT6gqcnyyd52l1QZjYL.html|website=Hindustan times|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19: CBSE sets new rules for exam centres as precautionary against coronavirus spread| url=https://www.shiksha.com/articles/covid-19-cbse-sets-new-rules-for-exam-centres-as-precautionary-against-coronavirus-spread-blogId-32531|website=shikha|author=}}</ref> This includes maintaining a distance of at least 1 meter between the students taking the exam with a class not having more than 24 students. If the rooms of the examination centres are small, divide the students and make them sit in different rooms. On 19 March, [[Central Board of Secondary Education|CBSE]] and [[Joint Entrance Examination|JEE]] main examinations were postponed till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=CBSE 10th and 12th Board exams postponed due to coronavirus epidemic| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/home/education/news/cbse-10th-and-12th-board-exams-rescheduled-due-to-coronavirus-epidemic/articleshow/74698356.cms|website=timesofindia|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=CBSE Class 10, 12 Board exams postponed due to coronavirus; to be rescheduled after March 31| url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/breaking-coronavirus-outbreak-cbse-class-10-12-board-exams-postponed-599404|website=indiatv|author=}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, [[Maharashtra]] government cancelled examinations for class 1 to 8 and promoted the students to the next classes, whereas examinations for class 9 and 11 were postponed till 15 April.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/covid-19-mumbai-maharashtra-class-1-to-8-exams-cancelled-students-promoted-next-classes-coronavirus-599929|title=COVID-19: Maharashtra govt cancels Classes 1 to 8 exam; Class 9th, 11th exams to be conducted post April 15|date=|work=India TV|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Madhya Pradesh Board of Secondary Education]] postponed board exams for class 10 and 12 and asked school principals to promote or detain students of class 5 to 8 based on their performance in previous terms.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/home/education/news/mp-board-10th-12th-exams-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-exams-of-classes-5-8-cancelled/articleshow/74715064.cms|title=MP Board 10th & 12th exams postponed due to Coronavirus|date=|work=Times of India|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Board exams of class 10 and 12 were postponed in [[Kerala]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/covid-19-kerala-postpones-class-10-class-12-board-exams-a-first-for-the-state-11584692189302.html|title=COVID-19: Kerala postpones Class 10, Class 12 board exams, a first for the state|date=|work=Livemint|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Assam]] government cancelled all exams till 31 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/education/article/assam-government-cancels-all-exams-till-march-31-due-to-covid19-new-dates-to-be-out-soon/567181|title=Assam Government cancels all exams till March 31 due to COVID19, new dates to be out soon|date=|work=Times Now News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Union Public Service Commission]] also postponed the interview for the [[Civil Services Examination]] 2019 to be held from 23 March to 3 April.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus outbreak: UPSC defers civil services interviews| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-outbreak-upsc-defers-civil-services-interviews/amp_articleshow/74732283.cms|website=Economic|author=}}</ref> The [[Secondary School Certificate|SSC]] exams in Tamil Nadu and Puducherry were postponed to 15 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/education/tn-ssc-10th-board-exams-postponed-in-tamil-nadu-puducherry-due-to-coronavirus/story-m5Q0J50KHnlM40bJ88eS4O.html|title=TN SSC 10th board exams postponed in Tamil Nadu, Puducherry due to coronavirus|date=21 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Economy===\n{{main|Economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n{{see also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nOn 2 March, the [[BSE SENSEX]] witnessed a [[flash crash]] on the back of Union Health Ministry's announcement of two new confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sensex witnesses flash crash on 2 new coronavirus cases in India; over 340 stocks hit 52-week low |url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/markets/sensex-witnesses-flash-crash-on-2-new-coronavirus-cases-in-india-over-340-stocks-hit-52-week-low-4993351.html |accessdate=3 March 2020 |work=Moneycontrol}}</ref> A UN report estimated a trade impact of US$348 million on India due to the outbreak, making India one of the 15 worst affected economies across the world.<ref>{{cite news |title=Trade impact of Coronavirus epidemic for India estimated at 348 million dollars: UN report |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/foreign-trade/trade-impact-of-coronavirus-epidemic-for-india-estimated-at-348-million-dollars-un-report/articleshow/74487020.cms |accessdate=5 March 2020 |work=Economic Times}}</ref> [[Asian Development Bank]] estimated that the outbreak could cause losses of up to US$29.9 billion to India's economy.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus outbreak may cost Indian economy $29.9 bn: ADB |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-outbreak-in-india-could-cost-the-economy-29-9-billion-adb-11583480504316.html |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Livemint}}</ref> On 9 March, The [[BSE SENSEX]] closed 1,942 points lower at 35,635 while the [[NIFTY 50|NSE Nifty 50]] was down by 538 points to 10,451.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Raj|first=Shubham|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/monday-mayhem-may-mark-worst-day-for-sensex-5-factors-causing-this-crash/articleshow/74547106.cms|title=Monday mayhem marks worst day for Sensex: 5 factors causing this crash|date=9 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, Indian stock markets suffered their worst crash since June 2017 after WHO's declaration of the outbreak as a pandemic. The BSE SENSEX dropped 8.18 per cent or 2,919 points which was its lowest in 23 months while the [[NIFTY 50|NIFTY]] dropped 9 per cent or 950 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/business/bse-sensex-today-live-market-news-sensex-ends-2919-points-lower-nifty-at-9590-amid-coronavirus-fear-2193751|title=Sensex Crashes 2,919 Points, Nifty Ends At 9,590 In Worst Day For Markets Ever|website=NDTV.com|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April, the coal mining operations of [[Singareni Collieries Company]] in Telangana wer halted due to the threat of the COVID pandemic.<ref>\nGali Nagaraja,\n[https://thewire.in/rights/covid-19-singareni-underground-opearations-halt COVID-19 Threat: Underground Operations at Singareni Coal Mines Come to a Halt], The Wire, 2 April 2020.\n</ref>\n\n=== Entertainment ===\n{{see also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema}}\nThe [[International Indian Film Academy Awards]], planned to take place on March 27, was canceled.<ref>{{cite web |title=IIFA 2020 cancelled due to coronavirus scare, fresh date to be announced soon| url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/iifa-2020-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus-scare-fresh-date-to-be-announced-soon/story-QtJSVSQyxqYIC1qIEVTvPN.html|website=Hindustan Times|author=| date= 6 March 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date= 6 March 2020}}</ref> Cinema halls were shut down by most state governments. Film bodies decided to stop the production of films, TV shows and web series till 31 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jha|first=Lata|url=https://www.livemint.com/industry/media/coronavirus-scare-in-india-all-film-tv-web-shoots-cancelled-11584279151544.html|title=Coronavirus scare in India: All film, TV, web shoots cancelled|date=15 March 2020|work=Livemint|access-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 25 March, all video streaming services, jointly decided to offer only SD quality content on cellular networks. They also decided to lower the bitrates to 480p to lower the stress on telecom networks throughout the 21-day lockdown during which there would be an unprecedented surge in mobile internet consumption since people were confined to their homes.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.economictimes.com/industry/media/entertainment/video-streaming-services-like-netflix-hotstar-suspend-hd-service-on-cellular-networks/articleshow/74807392.cms|title=Video streaming services like Netflix, Hotstar suspend HD streaming on cellular networks|date=|work=Economic Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The release of ''[[Sooryavanshi]],'' which was initially scheduled to release on 24 March, was postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/movies/bollywood/story/sooryavanshi-release-date-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-will-be-back-when-the-time-is-right-1654909-2020-03-12|title=Sooryavanshi release date postponed due to coronavirus: Will be back when the time is right|date=March 12, 2020|work=India Today|accessdate=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312173945/https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/movies/bollywood/story/sooryavanshi-release-date-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-will-be-back-when-the-time-is-right-1654909-2020-03-12|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  The [[Indian Broadcasting Foundation]] (IBF) said that four major broadcasting networks in the country have decided to waive all fees for four channels for two months. The IBF is an organisation promoting the Indian television industry.\nIn a statement, the foundation said that [[Sony Pal]], run by [[Sony]], [[Star Utsav]], run by Star India, Viacom18's [[Colors Rishtey]] run by colors and [[Zee Anmol]] run by [[Zee TV]] will be available for two months free to all viewers in the country. This offer is for all DTH and cable networks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Impact: IBF members waive all charges of four pay channels for two months| url=https://www.financialexpress.com/brandwagon/coronavirus-impact-ibf-members-waives-all-charges-of-four-pay-channels-for-two-months/1912071/|website=financial express|author=| date=29 March 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Events===\n{{see also|List of major events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nOn 6 March, the [[Border Security Force]] announced that the [[Wagah-Attari border ceremony]] would be conducted without any spectators as a precautionary measure, effective from 7 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-attari-border-ceremony-to-be-conducted-without-public-presence/amp-11583503640550.html|title=Coronavirus: Attari border ceremony to be conducted without public presence|work=Livemint|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref> The 21st [[IIFA Awards]] ceremony, which was scheduled to be held in [[Indore]] on 29 March, was postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/iifa-awards-2020-postponed-over-coronavirus-scare-new-dates-awaited-2190996?amp=1&akamai-rum=off|title=IIFA Awards 2020 Postponed Over Coronavirus Scare. New Dates Awaited|work=NDTV|accessdate=6 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306102131/https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/iifa-awards-2020-postponed-over-coronavirus-scare-new-dates-awaited-2190996?amp=1&akamai-rum=off|archive-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> The [[India Fashion Week]], scheduled to begin on 11 March in New Delhi, was put off.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indulgexpress.com/fashion/2020/mar/06/fdci-postpones-lotus-makeup-india-fashion-week-amidst-covid-19-fears-22914.html|title=FDCI postpones Lotus Makeup India Fashion Week amidst COVID-19 fears|work=Indulge Express|accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Orders, decorations, and medals of India|Padma Awards]] ceremony that was scheduled to be held on 3 April was postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/rashtrapati-bhavan-padma-awards-postponed-coronavirus-outbreak-1655564-2020-03-14|title=Upcoming Padma Awards ceremony postponed in wake of coronavirus outbreak|first=Jitendra Bahadur |last=Singh |date=14 March 2020|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Historical buildings===\nOn 17 March, All the historic buildings in the country will remain closed till 31 March. According to Union Tourism Minister [[Prahlad Patel]] the [[Taj Mahal]], [[Red Fort]] and [[Qutub Minar]] and all the National Monuments and Museums under the Archaeological Department of India will remain closed till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Outbreak: ASI shuts monuments; Taj Mahal, Hampi, Ajanta closed| url=https://www.financialexpress.com/lifestyle/travel-tourism/coronavirus-outbreak-asi-shuts-monuments-taj-mahal-hampi-ajanta-closed/1900158/lite/|website=financial express|author=| date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Statue of Unity]] will be closed to visitors till 25 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus scare in Gujarat: Sardar Patel's Statue Of Unity| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/vadodara/coronavirus-scare-in-gujarat-worlds-tallest-statue-closes/articleshow/74665311.cms|website=Times of India|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus impact: Statue of Unity closed for public; ASI shuts all monuments| url=https://m.businesstoday.in/story/coronavirus-impact-statue-of-unity-closed-for-public-asi-shuts-all-monuments/1/398477.html|website=Business standard|author=}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion}}\n\n[[File:20200402 - The Times of India - COVID-19 lockdown - Ram Temple in Bhubaneswar wears a deserted look on Ram Navami.webm|thumb|thumbtime=0:28|Temple [[Ram Mandir, Bhubaneswar|Ram Mandir]] in the heart of Bhubaneswar.]]\n\nOn 17 March, [[Mumbai]]'s [[Siddhivinayak Temple, Mumbai|Siddhivinayak Temple]] was closed till further notice.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Scare: Siddhivinayak Temple Closed For Devotees Till Further Notice| url=https://www.mumbailive.com/en/civic/siddhivinayak-temple-closed-due-to-corona-virus-46730|website=mumbailive|author=}}</ref> The next day, the [[Vaishno Devi|Mata Vaishno Devi]] pilgrimage in [[Jammu and Kashmir (union territory)|Jammu and Kashmir]] was called off.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19: Mata Vaishno Devi Shrine Board appeals pilgrims to postpone their visit to temple| url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/covid-19-mata-vaishno-devi-shrine-board-appeals-pilgrims-to-postpone-their-visit-to-temple20200317224905/|website=aninews|author=}}</ref> Apart from this, the operation of all interstate buses coming to from Jammu and Kashmir has also been stopped. Shri Mata Vaishno Devi Shrine Board (SMVDSB), issued a consultation for foreigners not to visit the temple until 28 days after their arrival in [[India]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Journey of Mata Vaishno Devi closed from today due to coronavirus| url=https://news.abplive.com/videos/news/india-journey-of-mata-vaishno-devi-closed-from-today-due-to-coronavirus-1177683|website=abplive|author=}}</ref> Entry restrictions are also in place for the aarti held at the Ganges Ghat in [[Varanasi]]; the organisers have been asked to complete the Ganga Aarti in a simple way.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Varanasi district administration bans Ganga Arti| url=https://news.abplive.com/videos/news/india-coronavirus-varanasi-district-administration-bans-ganga-arti-1177641|website=abplive|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ganga Aarti have been suspended in Varanasi in wake of Covid-19 scare| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/ganga-aarti-have-been-suspended-in-varanasi-in-wake-of-covid-19-scare/videoshow/74689654.cms|website=Economic times|author=}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, entry at [[Har Ki Pauri]], Ganga Ghat, in [[Haridwar]] was closed till 31 March. However, the aarti at Har Ki Pauri Ghat continued and shown to devotees through live streaming.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus scare: Ganga Aarti at Har ki Pauri - Haridwar administration restricts entry of visitors| url=https://www.timesnownews.com/india/article/coronavirus-scare-ganga-aarti-at-har-ki-pauri-haridwar-administration-restricts-entry-of-visitors/566472|website=timesofindia|author=}}</ref> [[Jagannath Temple, Puri]] was closed for visitors till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Covid-19 in Odisha: Puri Jagannath temple to shut from Friday |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bhubaneswar/covid-19-in-odisha-puri-jagannath-temple-to-shut-from-friday/articleshow/74708952.cms |website=Times of India |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, the [[Government of Andhra Pradesh]] closed visits to [[Venkateswara Temple, Tirumala]] until 31 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/covid-19-andhra-govt-closes-tirupati-tirumala-temple-visitors-till-march-31-120632|title=COVID-19: Andhra govt closes Tirupati Tirumala temple to visitors till March 31|website=www.thenewsminute.com|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> [[Sabarmati Ashram|Gandhi Ashram]] in [[Ahmedabad]] will also be closed to visitors from 19 to 29 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sabarmati Ashram closes doors to visitors till March 29 in light of coronavirus outbreak| url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/india/story/sabarmati-ashram-closes-doors-to-visitors-till-march-29-in-light-of-coronavirus-outbreak-1657186-2020-03-19|website=indiatoday|author=}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, [[Ramanathaswamy Temple|Rameswaram Ramanathan Swamy Temple]] in [[Tamil Nadu]] was closed till 31st. During this period, devotees were banned from entering the temple.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rameswaram Ramanathaswami Temple to remain closed till March 31| url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/rameswaram-ramanathaswami-temple-to-remain-closed-till-march-31-120032100630_1.html|website=Business standard|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Rameswaram Ramanathaswami Temple to remain closed till March 31| url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/rameswaram-ramanathaswami-temple-to-remain-closed-till-march-3120200321161022/|website=aninews|author=}}</ref> On 26 March, The [[Makkah Masjid, Hyderabad|Mecca Masjid]] of Hyderabad was closed to devotees.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19: Mecca Masjid management asks people not to come for prayers| url=https://telanganatoday.com/covid-19-mecca-masjid-management-asks-people-not-to-come-for-prayers|website=telanganatoday|author=| date=27 March 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany Christian churches have suspended in-person [[Mass (liturgy)|mass]] and have offered worship for their congregants through livestreaming, radio and television.<ref name=\"Sharad2020\">{{cite web |last1=Sharad |first1=Arpita |title=Followers catch up on church service streaming live on various platforms |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/aurangabad/followers-catch-up-on-church-service-streaming-live-on-various-platforms/articleshow/74764511.cms |publisher=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=English}}</ref> The [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Ranchi]] has appealed to the Christian faithful to aid refugees from the Indian state of [[Jharkhand]] who have been stranded since the lockdown.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gomes |first1=Robin |title=Coronavirus: Ranchi Archdiocese urges Indian Church not to abandon stranded migrants - Vatican News |url=https://www.vaticannews.va/en/church/news/2020-03/india-ranchi-archdiocese-appeal-stranded-migrants-coronavirus.html |publisher=[[Vatican News]] |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=English |date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\n{{see also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nThe 2020 [[ISSF World Cup]], which was to commence on 15 March in New Delhi, was postponed.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/virus-hits-indian-sports/articleshow/74519560.cms|title=Virus hits Indian sports|date=6 March 2020|work=Economic Times|accessdate=7 March 2020|url-status=live|agency=PTI}}</ref> The [[India Open|Indian Open]] badminton tournament which was scheduled to be held in New Delhi from 24 to 29 March was suspended until 12 April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/sports-news-coronavirus-india-open-badminton-tournament-cancelled/348760|title=Coronavirus: India Open Badminton Tournament Cancelled|last=|first=|date=14 March 2020|website=Outlook|agency=PTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIndia's [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|FIFA World Cup qualification]] match on 26 March against Qatar in [[Bhubaneswar]] was postponed.<ref>{{cite news |title=India's FIFA World Cup qualifier against Qatar postponed due to coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/football/story/india-vs-qatar-fifa-world-cup-2020-qualifiers-coronavirus-bhubaneswar-postponed-1653414-2020-03-07 |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=India Today |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308222645/https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/football/story/india-vs-qatar-fifa-world-cup-2020-qualifiers-coronavirus-bhubaneswar-postponed-1653414-2020-03-07 |archive-date=8 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[All India Football Federation]] suspended all matches of [[I-League]] and [[I-League 2nd Division]] from 15 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-in/news/coronavirus-i-league-matches-suspended-from-march-15/1ujkopnrik7ww11yarhfvjhxxj|title=Coronavirus: I-League matches suspended from March 15|last=Mukherjee|first=Soham|date=14 March 2020|website=Goal.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 14 March, the [[2020 Indian Super League Final]] was played [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiansuperleague.com/news/refund-process-for-hero-isl-2019-20-final-ticket-holders|title=Refund process for Hero ISL 2019-20 final ticket holders|website=Indian Super League|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/coronavirus-isl-final-to-be-held-behind-closed-doors/articleshow/74605305.cms|title=Coronavirus: ISL final to be held behind closed doors - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] announced that the opening of [[2020 Indian Premier League]] was postponed from 29 March to 15 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=It's official: IPL 2020 postponed to April 15 due to coronavirus |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/ipl/top-stories/its-official-ipl-2020-postponed-to-mid-april-due-to-coronavirus/articleshow/74609776.cms |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Times of India}}</ref> Later that day, it cancelled the [[South African cricket team in India in 2019\u201320|ODI matches between India and South Africa]] on 15 and 18 March, which were originally announced to be played without spectators.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rao|first=Rakesh|url=https://www.thehindu.com/sport/cricket/coronavirus-india-south-africa-series-called-off-due-to-covid-19-threat/article31061061.ece|title=India-South Africa series called off due to COVID-19 threat|date=13 March 2020|work=The Hindu|accessdate=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[World 10K Bangalore|TCS World 10 Bengaluru]], the [[IAAF Road Race Label Events|IAAF Gold Label Road Race]] scheduled to be held on 17 May was postponed to 13 September.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Biji Babu Cyriac |title=TCS World 10K Bengaluru postponed |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/more-sports/athletics/tcs-world-10k-bengaluru-postponed/articleshow/74831080.cms |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Times of India |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Transportation===\n'''Flights'''\n\n[[IndiGo]] cancelled its [[Delhi]]-[[Istanbul]] and [[Chennai]] - [[Kuala Lumpur]] flights starting 18 March to prevent international travel from [[Turkey]] and [[Malaysia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article-amp/pti-stories/indigo-cancels-flights-on-delhi-istanbul-chennai-kuala-lumpur-route-from-march18-31-120031701637_1.html|title=IndiGo cancels flights on Delhi-Istanbul, Chennai-Kuala Lumpur route from March18\u201331|author=|first=|date=17 March 2020|website=Business Standard|agency=PTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> This ban will continue till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/corona-impact-indigo-to-cancel-flights-to-turkey-malaysia/1771423|title=Corona Impact: IndiGo to cancel flights to Turkey, Malaysia|author=|first=|date=17 March 2020|website=Outlook India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> On 17 March 2020, [[GoAir|Go Air]] suspended its international flights till further notice.<ref>{{cite web |title=GoAir suspends international operations| url=https://www.livemint.com/companies/news/goair-suspends-international-operations-sends-staff-on-leave-without-pay-11584451946542.html|website=Mint|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 19 March, the [[Government of India]] announced that no [[international flight]]s will be allowed to land in India from 22 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=No international commercial flight will be allowed to land India from March 22| url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/no-international-commercial-flight-will-be-allowed-to-land-india-from-march-22-599644|website=indiatvnews|author=}}</ref> On 23 March, the [[Government of India|union government]] announced the suspension of all [[domestic flight]]s in the country starting 25 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-india-suspends-domestic-flights-from-25-march-11584962827845.html|title=Coronavirus: India suspends domestic flights from 25 March|date=|work=Livemint|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''Railways'''\n\nOn 14 March, [[Western Railway (India)|Western]] and [[Central Railways]] removed curtains and blankets from AC coaches.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Central, Western Railway withdraw curtains, blankets from AC coaches| url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/coronavirus-central-western-railway-withdraw-curtains-blankets-from-ac-coaches-120031401174_1.html|newspaper=Business Standard India| date=14 March 2020| last1=India| first1=Press Trust of}}</ref> On 17 March, [[Western Railway (India)|Western Railways]] hiked platform ticket charges from Rs. 10 to Rs. 50 across 250 stations.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.cnbctv18.com/healthcare/coronavirus-impact-railway-platform-ticket-price-hiked-to-rs-50-in-250-stations-5501061.htm|title=Coronavirus impact: Railway platform ticket price hiked to Rs 50 in 250 stations|date=|work=CNBC TV18|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Central Railway zone|Central Railways]] cancelled 23 trains.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://zeenews.india.com/india/live-updates/breaking-news-march-17-latest-updates-2269902|title=Live: Central Railways cancel 23 trains amid coronavirus scare|date=|work=Zee News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 19 March, [[Tejas Express]] running between [[Lucknow]] Junction to [[New Delhi]] and [[Varanasi]] to [[Indore]] will remain canceled till 31 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tejas Express cancelled| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/lucknow/tejas-express-cancelled-due-to-low-occupancy-and-mass-cancellations/amp_articleshow/74696379.cms|website=timesofinfia|author=}}</ref> On 20 March, [[Delhi Metro]] was scheduled to remain closed on 22 March due to [[Janata Curfew]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Delhi Metro To Be Closed On Sunday As Part Of PM's \"Janata Curfew\" Move| url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/delhi-metro-to-remain-closed-on-sunday-as-part-of-pms-janta-curfew-move-to-fight-coronavirus-2197994|website=ndtv|author=}}</ref> On 22 March, metro services across India were suspended till 31 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Metro services shut across India till March 31 |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/metro-services-shut-across-india-till-march-31/articleshow/74760183.cms |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Economic Times |agency=PTI |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> On 21 March, in view of [[Janata curfew]], Indian Railways announced the cancellation of 3,700 trains across the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Janata curfew: 3,700 trains cancelled on Sunday| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/janata-curfew-3700-trains-cancelled-on-sunday/articleshow/74740006.cms|website=timesofindia|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Janta curfew: Railways cancels 3700 trains on Sunday| url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/covid-19-janta-curfew-railways-cancels-3700-trains-on-sunday-11584723537011.html|website=Livemint|author=}}</ref> On 22 March, the [[Government of India|union government]] cancelled all train services in the country baring goods trains, that is around 12,500 trains, and all non-essential passenger transport including interstate transport buses.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/after-trains-interstate-bus-services-suspended-till-31st-march/articleshow/74758323.cms|title=After trains, interstate bus services suspended till 31st March|date=|work=Economic Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Indian Railway Catering and Tourism Corporation|IRCTC]] suspended the bookings for 3 private trains till 30 April.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://sarkaripaper.co.in/irctc-suspends-bookings-for-its-3-private-trains-till-april-30-amid-nationwide-lockdown-due-to-coronavirus-covid-19/|title=IRCTC suspends bookings for its 3 private trains till April 30, amid nationwide lockdown due to coronavirus COVID-19|date=|work=sarkaripaper.co,in|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''Road'''\n\nOn 19 March, bus services between the cities of [[Maharashtra]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]] have been postponed from 21 to 31 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bus services between Indore and Maharashtra to be suspended| url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/bus-services-between-indore-and-maharashtra-to-be-suspended-1657078-2020-03-18|website=indiatoday|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Bus services between Indore and Maharashtra to be suspended| url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/bus-services-between-indore-and-maharashtra-to-be-suspended/1772086|website=outlookindia|author=}}</ref> [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] government imposed a ban on [[public transport]] including [[buses]], [[auto rickshaws]] and [[tempos]] from 21 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Punjab to ban public transport from March 21 |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/coronavirus/punjab-to-ban-public-transport-from-march-21/ |website=The Indian Express |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> Public transport including buses, mini buses, maxi cabs and auto services were banned in [[Srinagar]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Govt bans public transport in Srinagar to prevent spread of Coronavirus |url=https://www.greaterkashmir.com/news/srinagar/govt-bans-public-transport-in-srinagar-to-prevent-spread-of-coronavirus/ |website=Greater Kashmir |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Exodus of migrant workers===\nAn estimated 139 million migrant workers from the countryside work in India's cities and towns. With factories and workplaces shut down, they were left with  no livelihood. In the first few days of the lockdown, television screens captured long processions of migrant workers walking miles to go back to their native villages, often with families and young children on shoulders.<ref>Ismat Ara, [https://thewire.in/labour/watch-no-work-no-money-thousands-stranded-on-anand-vihar-bus-stand Watch | 'No Work, No Money': Thousands Stranded on Anand Vihar Bus Stand], The Wire, 29 March 2020.</ref> Two days later, the Uttar Pradesh government decided to arrange buses at Delhi's [[Anand Vihar ISBT|Anand Vihar bus station]] to take the migrants back to their villages. Large crowds gathered at the bus station awaiting buses. The central government issued a press statement stating that it had asked state governments to set up immediate relief camps for the migrant workers returning to their native states.<ref>[https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/fighting-covid-19-after-the-long-walk-jobless-migrants-head-home-by-bus-120032900041_1.html Fighting Covid-19: After the long walk, jobless migrants head home by bus], Business Standard, 29 March 2020.</ref> On 29 March, the government issued sweeping orders directing that the landlords should not demand rent during the period of the lockdown and that employers should pay wages without deduction. The people that violated the lockdown were to be sent to government-run quarantine facilities for 14 days.<ref>[https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/coronavirus-centre-warns-lockdown-violators-of-14-day-quarantine/article31198038.ece Coronavirus | Migrant workers to be stopped, quarantined at borders, says Centre], The Hindu, 29 March 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/coronavirus-crisis-landlords-can-not-ask-rent-from-students-workers-for-1-month/story/399551.html Coronavirus crisis: Landlords can't ask rent from students, workers for 1 month], Business Today, 29 March 2020.</ref> The [[Supreme Court of India]] agreed to hear a petition on behalf of the migrant workers on 30 March.<ref>[https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/petition-seeking-food-shelter-for-migrants-amid-coronavirus-lockdown-to-be-heard-in-supreme-court-to-2202655?pfrom=home-topstories Supreme Court To Hear Petition On Migrants Amid Lockdown Tomorrow], NDTV, 29 March 2020.</ref>\n[[File:Migrant workers stand in a queue for food at Delhi Govt school during COVID-19 Lockdown at Delhi IMG 20200331 132400.jpg|thumb|Migrant workers stand in a queue for food at Delhi Govt school during COVID-19 Lockdown at Delhi]]\n\n===Unemployment===\nThe coronavirus lockdown in India has left tens of millions of [[migrant worker]]s unemployed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: India's pandemic lockdown turns into a human tragedy |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52086274 |publisher=BBC News |date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Hungry, desperate: India virus controls trap its migrant workers |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/ajimpact/hungry-desperate-india-virus-controls-trap-migrant-workers-200402031123631.html |work=Al Jazeera |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Help==\n===Immediate relief===\nOn 19 March, [[Kerala]] [[Chief minister (India)|chief minister]] (CM) [[Pinarayi Vijayan]] announced a stimulus package of {{INRConvert|20000|c|lk=|year=2020}} to help the state overcome both the Covid-19 epidemic and economic hardship caused by it.<ref>{{cite news|last = | title = Kerala government announces Rs 20,000 crore package to tackle coronavirus outbreak| newspaper = Hindustan Times | location = | pages = | language = English | date = 20 March 2020 | url = https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/kerala-government-announces-rs-20-000-crore-package-to-tackle-coronavirus-outbreak/story-KzGvehTH4HXjhnkTBLU49M.html | access-date = 25 March 2020}}</ref> On 21 March, [[Uttar Pradesh]] CM [[Yogi Adityanath]] announced {{INRConvert|1000||lk=|year=2020}} to all daily wage labourers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Yogi Adityanath announces relief measures for UP's daily wage earners| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/yogi-adityanath-announces-relief-measures-for-ups-daily-wage-earners/articleshow/74744711.cms|website=Economic times|author=}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] CM [[Amarinder Singh]] announced {{INRConvert|3000||lk=|year=2020}} to all registered construction workers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Rs 3,000 relief for construction workers, says Punjab CM Amarinder Singh |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/coronavirus-rs-3000-relief-for-construction-workers-says-punjab-cm-amarinder-singh/articleshow/74754595.cms |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Times of India |agency=TNN |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> [[Telangana]] CM [[K. Chandrashekar Rao]] announced that white [[Ration card (India)|ration card]] holders will be provided {{INRConvert|1500||lk=|year=2020}} per family through [[ration shop]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://telanganatoday.com/telangana-lockdown-12-kg-free-rice-per-person-rs-1500-per-family-to-be-supplied-for-each-white-ration-card|title=Telangana Lockdown: 12 kg free rice per person {{INRConvert|1500||lk=|year=2020}} per family to be supplied for each white ration card|date=|work=Telangana Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 March, Union Finance Minister [[Nirmala Sitharaman]] announced an economic relief package of {{INRConvert|1.7|lc|lk=|year=2020}}, which would be a mix of food security and direct cash transfer, primarily for [[Migrant worker|migrant labourers]] and daily wage labourers.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/finance-minister-nirmala-sitharaman-live-updates-economic-relief-package-india-coronavirus-1659912-2020-03-26 | title = Coronavirus: FM Sitharaman announces package worth Rs 1,70,000 crore for poor, daily wagers | date = March 26, 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200326224738/https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/finance-minister-nirmala-sitharaman-live-updates-economic-relief-package-india-coronavirus-1659912-2020-03-26 | archive-date = 26 March 2020 | url-status = live | access-date = 26 March 2020 }}</ref> [[Prime Minister's National Relief Fund]] received several donations - {{INRConvert|3381|c|lk=|year=2020}} from the [[Central Reserve Police Force]],<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/covid19-crpf-contributes-rs-3381-cr-fund-from-jawans-oneday-salary/1781014|title=COVID-19: CRPF contributes Rs 33.81 cr fund from jawan''s one-day salary|date=|work=Outlook|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |title=Sachin Tendulkar donates Rs 50 lakh for COVID 19 relief fund |url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/sachin-tendulkar-donates-rs-50-lakh-for-covid-19-relief-funds/articleshow/74839144.cms |accessdate=27 March 2020 |publisher=Mumbai Mirror |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> and a month's salary from [[Vice President of India|Vice President]] [[Venkaiah Naidu]], [[Law Minister]] [[Ravi Shankar Prasad]] and [[Nationalist Congress Party|NCP]]'s [[Member of parliament (India)|MP]]<nowiki/>s.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/venkaiah-naidu-ravi-shankar-prasad-donate-their-one-month-s-salary-in-fight-against-covid-19-818322.html|title=Venkaiah Naidu, Ravi Shankar Prasad donate their one month's salary in fight against COVID-19|date=|work=Deccan Herald|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/ncp-legislators-to-donate-salary-for-coronavirus-relief/1781131|title=NCP legislators to donate salary for coronavirus relief|date=|work=Outlook|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Nationalist Congress Party|NCP]] President [[Sharad Pawar]] announced that his party's [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLAs]] would donate their one month's salary to Maharashtra CM's Reief Fund.<ref name=\"auto\"/> [[Reserve Bank of India|RBI]] Governor [[Shaktikanta Das]] permitted all banks to provide a [[Moratorium (law)|moratorium]] on all [[loans]] for three months without having to worry about [[Non-performing asset|NPAs]] and keeping their books healthy. He also laid down various measures for injecting {{INRConvert|3.74|lc|lk=|year=2020}} [[liquidity]] into the system.<ref>{{cite news |title=RBI Governor Shaktikanta Das: Interest rates cut by 75 bps, EMIs put on hold |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/rbi-governor-shaktikanta-das-live-rate-cut-expected-11585280776382.html |accessdate=27 March 2020 |publisher=Livemint |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> Saibaba Sansthan Trust, [[Shirdi]] donated {{INRConvert|51|c|lk=|year=2020}} to [[Maharashtra]] [[Chief minister (India)|CM]]'s relief fund.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shri Saibaba Sansthan Trust donates Rs 51 cr to combat COVID-19| url=https://www.bignewsnetwork.com/news/264441730/shri-saibaba-sansthan-trust-donates-rs-51-cr-to-combat-covid-19|website=bignewsnetwork|author=| date=27 March 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The Union Government released {{INRConvert|4431|c|lk=|year=2020}} pay off the pending wages of daily wage labourers who come under MGNREGA scheme.<ref>{{cite web |title=Centre releases Rs 4431 crore to clear pending wages under MGNREGA, to pay all dues by April 10| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/economy/finance/centre-releases-rs-4431-crore-to-clear-pending-wages-under-mgnrega-to-pay-all-dues-by-april-10/articleshow/74849430.cms|website=Economic Times|author=| date=27 March 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Centre releases 4,431 crore to clear pending wages under MGNREGA| url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/coronavirus-centre-releases-4431-crore-to-clear-pending-wages-under-mgnrega/article31185034.ece/amp/|website=The Hindu|author=| date=27 March 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> In Delhi, [[Arvind Kejriwal]] announced that if a doctor, nurse or hygiene worker dies during treatment, their family will be provided Rs 1 crore.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rs 1 Crore For Families Of COVID-19 Warriors If They Die: Arvind Kejriwal| url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/arvind-kejriwal-announces-rs-1-crore-for-families-of-health-personnel-if-they-lose-their-lives-while-2204204|website=ndtv|author=| date= 1 April 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n===PM CARES Fund===\n\nOn 28 March, the [[PM CARES Fund|Prime Minister's Citizen Assistance and Relief in Emergency Situations Fund]] (PM CARES Fund) was set up to provide relief to the affected people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsonair.com/Main-News-Details.aspx?id=384047|title=People urged to donate generously in PM CARES fund; PM Modi says every contribution matters|website=newsonair.com|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Several large business groups contributed to the relief fund, including [[Tata Sons]] and [[Sir Ratan Tata Trust|Tata Trusts]] ({{INR}}1,500 crore),<ref>{{cite news |title=Tata Sons' Rs 1,000 cr top-up takes group coronavirus fund to Rs 1,500 cr - India's biggest |url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/corporate/tata-sons-announces-additional-rs-1000-crore-support-towards-coronavirus-fund/story/399506.html |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=Business Today}}</ref> [[Wipro]] and [[Azim Premji]] Foundation ({{INR}}1,125 crore),<ref>{{cite news |title=Azim Premji\u2019s foundation, Wipro commit Rs 1,125 crore as India battles with coronavirus |url=https://www.financialexpress.com/industry/azim-premjis-foundation-wipro-commit-rs-1125-crore-as-india-battles-with-coronavirus/1916114/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=Financial Express}}</ref> [[Reliance Industries]] ({{INR}}500 crore)<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Reliance Industries announces Rs 500 crore contribution to PM-CARES fund, |url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/coronavirus-outbreak-reliance-industries-announces-rs-500-crore-contribution-to-pm-cares-fund-8207531.html |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=Firstpost}}</ref> and [[Aditya Birla Group]] ({{INR}}500 crore).<ref>{{cite news |title=Covid-19: Aditya Birla Group donates Rs 500 crores in PM-CARES fund |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/covid-19-aditya-birla-group-donates-rs-500-crores-in-pm-cares-fund-1663117-2020-04-04 |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=India Today}}</ref> In addition, power and renewable energy [[Public sector undertakings in India|PSUs]] contributed a total of {{INR}}925 crore,<ref>{{cite news |title=Power, renewable energy PSUs to contribute Rs 925 cr to PM CARES fund |url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/power-renewable-energy-psus-to-contribute-rs-925-cr-to-pm-cares-fund-820963.html |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=Deccan Herald}}</ref> whereas oil and gas PSUs contributed more than {{INR}}1,031 crore.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus {{!}} ONGC, IOC and other oil cos contribute over \u20b91,031 cr to PM CARES Fund |url=https://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/coronavirus-ongc-ioc-and-other-oil-cos-contribute-over-1031-cr-to-pm-cares-fund/article31219474.ece |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\n===Gas cylinders===\nOn 26 March, finance minister [[Nirmala Sitharaman]] announced free gas cylinders for three months to beneficiaries of [[Pradhan Mantri Ujjwala Yojana]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus relief package: Free gas cylinders to Ujjwala beneficiaries for next 3 months| url=https://m.businesstoday.in/story/coronavirus-relief-package-free-gas-cylinders-to-ujjwala-beneficiaries-for-next-3-months/1/399313.html|website=Business Standard|author=}}</ref>\n\n===Rations===\nOn 21 March, [[Delhi]] [[Chief minister (India)|CM]] [[Arvind Kejriwal]] increased free ration from 5 kilograms to 7.5 kilograms for the 7.2 million people who are dependent on the [[Rationing|ration scheme]].<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 causing financial stress to poor, ration per person increased: Arvind Kejriwal| url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pension-for-elderly-widows-specially-abled-being-doubled-in-view-of-covid-19-announces-arvind-kejriwal/articleshow/74747399.cms|website=economic Times|author=}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Karnataka]] CM [[BS Yediyurappa]] announced two months of free ration for all the people.<ref>{{cite web |title=Karnataka Seals its Borders, Announces Free Ration for All for 2 Months as Covid-19 Cases Reach 20| url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/karnataka-seals-its-borders-announces-free-ration-for-all-for-2-months-as-covid-19-cases-reach-20-2546273.html|website=News18|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> [[Andhra Pradesh]] CM [[Y. S. Jaganmohan Reddy]] announced free ration for the poor.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/ap-announces-lockdown-till-march-31/1776396|title=AP announces lockdown till March 31|date=|work=Outlook India|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Telangana]] CM announced that white [[Ration card (India)|ration card]] holders will be provided with 12 kilograms of free rice per person (against a monthly supply of 6 kilograms per card person) through [[ration shop]]s. On 23 March, [[Bihar]] [[Chief minister (India)|CM]] [[Nitish Kumar]] announced one month of free ration for all ration card holders.\n\nOn 25 March, Union Minister [[Prakash Javadekar]] announced that 80[[Crore|{{Nbsp}}crore]] (800[[Crore|{{Nbsp}}]]<nowiki/>million) people would be given wheat at the rate of Rs 2 per kg, and rice at Rs 3 per kg. He also said that three months ration advance would be given.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cabinet Meet Live Updates: Centre To Provide 7 Kg Ration To 80 Crore| url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/economy-finance/cabinet-meet-live-updates-government-to-announce-decisions-taken-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-nirmala-sitharaman-narendra-modi-labour-minister-workforce-financial-plan-measures-direct-benefit-transfer-gdp-economy|website=bloombergquint|author=}}</ref>\n\n===Masks and supplies===\nOn 25 March, [[Vivo (technology company)|Vivo]] said that they would be donating 1 lakh [[Medical mask|surgical]] and 5,000 [[NIOSH air filtration rating|N95 masks]] to [[Maharashtra]] government.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/industry/technology/coronavirus-outbreak-vivo-to-donate-1-lakh-protective-masks-to-maharashtra-govt-xiaomi-suspends-local-manufacturing/1909019/|title=Coronavirus outbreak: Vivo to donate 1 lakh protective masks to Maharashtra Govt, Xiaomi suspends local manufacturing|date=|work=Financial Express|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 March, former Indian [[cricketers]], [[Irfan Pathan]] and [[Yusuf Pathan]], made a donation of 4,000 masks.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/coronavirus-outbreak-former-india-cricketers-irfan-pathan-yusuf-pathan-donate-4000-masks-amidst-rising-covid-19-cases-8180911.html|title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Former India cricketers Irfan Pathan, Yusuf Pathan donate 4,000 masks amidst rising COVID-19 cases|date=|work=Firstpost|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, [[Hyundai Motor India Limited|Hyundai India]] announced placing an order for 25,000 COVID-19 Advanced Diagnostic Testing Kits from [[South Korea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://auto.ndtv.com/news/coronavirus-lockdown-hyundai-orders-advanced-covid-19-testing-kits-for-india-2202063|title=Coronavirus Lockdown: Hyundai India Orders Advanced COVID-19 Testing Kits From Korea|last=|first=|date=|website=CarandBike|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIndia hasn't experienced [[Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 related shortages]] so far.\n\n{{As of|2020|April|3}}, [[Indian Railways]] had produced total of 2[[Lakh|{{Nbsp}}lakh]] (200,000) masks and 25,000 sanitisers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Railway workers produce sanitisers & masks| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/hyderabad/rly-workers-produce-sanitisers-masks/articleshow/74957651.cms|website=timesofindia|author=| date= 3 April 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date= 3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Situation==\n===Panic buying===\n{{See also|Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nHyderabad witnessed panic buying throughout 20 and 21 March.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nanisetti |first1=Serish |title=Panicky shoppers clear out grocery shops |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/panicked-shoppers-clear-out-grocery-shops/article31131827.ece |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Panic buying of milk and other dairy products was also reported.<ref>{{cite news |title=No need for panic buying of milk |url=https://ahmedabadmirror.indiatimes.com/ahmedabad/others/no-need-for-panic-buying-of-milk/articleshow/74754049.cms |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Ahmedabad Mirror |date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=No need for panic buying of milk, other dairy products, says Amul MD |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/no-need-for-panic-buying-of-milk-other-dairy-products-says-amul-md/articleshow/74750809.cms |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Economic Times |agency=PTI |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> Online grocery delivery service [[Grofers]] also witnessed panic buying across states.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haq |first1=Haq |last2=Chitlangia |first2=Risha |title=Coronavirus: Govt monitors supplies to ease panic buying crunch |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/coronavirus-govt-monitors-supplies-to-ease-panic-buying-crunch/story-GKXs9RkVgkkyfcRv1ZNFuN.html |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nRetailers and consumer goods firms saw their average daily sales more than double on 19 March as consumers rushed to buy essentials ahead of [[Prime minister|PM]] [[Narendra Modi|Modi]]\u2019s address to the nation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/panic-buying-goes-a-notch-up-ahead-of-pm-modis-address/articleshow/74721852.cms|title=Panic buying goes a notch up ahead of PM Modi's address|date=|work=Economic Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> In response to this, Modi assured the citizens that there was enough food and ration supplies and advised them against panic buying.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/coronavirus-outbreak-pm-modis-9-key-messages-for-indians/articleshow/74716261.cms|title=Janata curfew, avoid panic buying, stay at home: PM Modi's 9 key messages for Indians|date=|work=Times of India|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Escaping of suspected people ===\nSeveral cases are reported across the country, where people who are suspected to have come in contact with the virus, escaped from the quarantines and hospitals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/11-coronavirus-suspects-in-navi-mumbai-traced-readmitted20200316214213/|title=11 coronavirus suspects in Navi Mumbai traced, readmitted|website=ANI News|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/5-coronavirus-suspects-escape-from-isolation-ward-of-nagpur-hospital-all-traced/story-WqxUDicK8Ejeczq1yatULM.html|title=5 coronavirus suspects escape from isolation ward of Nagpur hospital, all traced|date=14 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Chhattisgarh]], a 35 yr-old man from Tagapani, Dhamtari, who was put under isolation home by the health dept after his return from [[Tamil Nadu]], committed suicide.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chhattisgarh: Covid-19 suspect under home quarantine commits suicide in Dhamtari| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/raipur/chhattisgarh-covid-19-suspect-under-home-quarantine-commits-suicide-in-dhamtari/articleshow/74899263.cms|website=timesofindia|author=| date=31 March 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Gujarat]], 93 people have broken self-isolation rules in 10 days. FIRs have been filed against 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/in-gujarat-93-flouted-self-isolation-rules-in-10-days-firs-against-10-6327258/|title=In Gujarat, 93 flouted self-isolation rules in 10 days, FIRs against 10|last=Ghosh|first=Sohini|last2=Jha|first2=Vaibhav|date=23 March 2020|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nTwo expats in Kasaragod district, [[Kerala]], who violated quarantine measures were subjected to punitive measures, including cancellation of their Indian passports.<ref>{{cite news |title=Passports of two NRIs to be cancelled for violating quarantine orders in Kasaragod |url=https://english.mathrubhumi.com/news/kerala/passports-of-two-nris-to-be-cancelled-for-violating-quarantine-orders-in-kasaragod-1.4640844 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Mathrubhumi |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, A case of 26-year-old woman suspected of being infected with the corona virus has been reported to have fled the hospital in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]. The woman, who hails from Mohali, recently returned from the US and was brought to a government hospital in [[Chandigarh]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus in India: Mohali woman who travelled to UK tests positive| url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-in-india-mohali-woman-who-travelled-to-uk-tests-positive-1657743-2020-03-20|website=indiatoday|author=}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March in [[Telangana]], one woman returned from [[Singapore]] has been missing, while a man who came from [[Doha]] went somewhere without telling hospital staff.<ref>{{cite web |title=Covidiots everywhere; cases of foreign returnees flouting home quarantine in rise| url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/230320/covidiots-everywhere-cases-of-foreign-returnees-flouting-home-quarant.html|website=Deccan chronicle|author=}}</ref>\n\n===Misinformation and discrimination===\n{{see also|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nDespite evidence to the contrary, a viral rumour spread online alleging that only people who eat meat were affected by coronavirus, causing \"#NoMeat_NoCoronaVirus\" to trend on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=3 March 2020|title='No Meat, No Coronavirus' Makes No Sense|url=https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|website=The Wire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303034133/https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|archive-date=3 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> To curb these rumours and combat declining sales, some poultry industry associations held a \"Chicken and Egg Mela\" in Hyderabad. Several Telangana state ministers were in attendance and ate some of the free eggs and fried chicken being distributed at the event to show their support for the industry.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=3 March 2020|title=Amid COVID-19 fears, KTR relishes chicken and eggs to dispel rumours|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/hyderabad/2020/feb/29/amid-covid-19-fears-ktr-relishes-chicken-and-eggs-to-dispel-rumours-2110056.html|website=The New Indian Express|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303034135/https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/hyderabad/2020/feb/29/amid-covid-19-fears-ktr-relishes-chicken-and-eggs-to-dispel-rumours-2110056.html|archive-date=3 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMuslim cleric Ilyas Sharafuddin has stated that [[Allah]] has punished the Chinese by unleashing Corona virus on them for their brutal crackdown on [[Uyghurs|Uighur]] Muslims. His claim was largely criticised and was condemned for passing such communal and insensitive comments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/india/article/allah-unleashed-coronavirus-on-chinese-for-persecuting-uighur-muslims-islamic-cleric-ilyas-sharafuddin/546408|title=Allah unleashed Coronavirus on Chinese for persecuting Uighur Muslims: Islamic cleric Ilyas Sharafuddin|website=www.timesnownews.com}}</ref>\n\nSome politicians like [[Swami Chakrapani]] and [[Suman Haripriya]] claimed that drinking cow urine and applying cow dung on the body can cure coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|title=Coronavirus: Can cow dung and urine help cure the novel coronavirus?|website=Times of India|accessdate=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206035509/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|archive-date=6 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|title=Novel coronavirus can be cured with gaumutra, gobar claims Assam BJP MLA Suman Haripriya|website=Firstpost|accessdate=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304051130/https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> WHO's chief scientist [[Soumya Swaminathan (scientist)|Soumya Swaminathan]] rubbished such claims and criticised these politicians for spreading misinformation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://swachhindia.ndtv.com/novel-coronavirus-outbreak-indias-response-and-surveillance-has-been-quite-robust-says-whos-chief-scientist-42015|title=Novel Coronavirus Outbreak: \"India's Response And Surveillance Has Been Quite Robust,\" Says WHO's Chief Scientist|website=NDTV|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51910099|title=India's coronavirus health myths fact-checked|first=Reality Check|last=team|date=19 March 2020|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\nReports of harassment of people from [[Northeast India]], which shares a border with [[Tibet Autonomous Region|Tibet]] and [[Myanmar]], in Chennai, Pune and Hyderabad have been reported following the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |title=Northeast community fends off racist attacks with coronavirus |url=https://punemirror.indiatimes.com/pune/cover-story/northeast-community-fends-off-racist-attacks-with-coronavirus-label/articleshow/74542293.cms |website=pune mirror |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=We are the Coronavirus for few Indians': says people from North-east in Hyderabad |url=https://newsmeter.in/we-are-the-coronavirus-for-few-indians-says-people-from-north-east/ |website=newsmeter |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Covid-19: Northeast India Welfare Association complains of racism |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-northeast-india-welfare-association-complains-of-racial-discrimination-in-chennai/articleshow/74733326.cms |website=timesofindia |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> Students from [[Kirori Mal College]] in Delhi, [[Tata Institute of Social Sciences]] in Mumbai and other institutes in Kolkata have also faced harassment and filed complaints with authorities.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus outbreak: NE students at TISS report incidents of 'racism, harassment' |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/coronavirus-outbreak-northeastern-students-at-tiss-report-incidents-of-racism-harassment-6272973/ |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=The Indian Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218172700/https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/coronavirus-outbreak-northeastern-students-at-tiss-report-incidents-of-racism-harassment-6272973/ |archive-date=18 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2 Students Allegedly Faced Racial Taunts Linked To Coronavirus In Kolkata |url=https://www.ndtv.com/kolkata-news/coronavirus-outbreak-2-students-allegedly-faced-racial-taunts-linked-to-coronavirus-in-kolkata-2196428 |website=ndtv |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus outbreak: NE students at TISS report incidents of 'racism, harassment' |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/coronavirus-outbreak-northeastern-students-at-tiss-report-incidents-of-racism-harassment-6272973/ |website=Indianexpress |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMisinformation that the government is spreading \"anti-corona\" drug in the country during Janata curfew went viral on social media.<ref>{{cite news |title=Is government spraying coronavirus vaccine using airplanes? No, it\u2019s fake news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/is-government-spraying-coronavirus-vaccine-using-airplanes-no-it-s-fake-news/story-QmSDrfLW8SkSghT2TUf5cK.html |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |date=20 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Film actor [[Mohanlal]] and many others shared the fake news that, the vibration generated by clapping together during Janata curfew will kill the virus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/mohanlal-many-others-share-fake-info-clapping-may-kill-virus-pib-debunks-120844 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |title=Mohanlal, many others share fake info that \u2018clapping may kill virus\u2019, PIB debunks |work=[[The News Minute]]}}</ref> One viral message says that the lifetime of coronavirus is only 12 hours and staying home for 14 hours during Janata curfew break the chain of transmission.<ref name=indiatoday1>{{cite news |last1=DelhiMarch 21 |first1=Ratna New |last2=March 21 |first2=Ratna New |last3=Ist |first3=Ratna New |title=Fact Check: Social media users give misleading twist to PM Modi's concept of 'Janta curfew' |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/fact-check/story/social-media-users-give-misleading-twist-pm-modi-janta-curfew-1658195-2020-03-21 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref> Another message claimed that observing Janata curfew will result in the reduction of coronavirus cases by 40%.<ref name=indiatoday1/> Tweet by [[Rajinikanth]] claiming that a 14-hour stay home can stop the coronavirus disease going from \"stage 2\" to \"stage 3\" was classified as misinformation and was taken down by Twitter for violating community guidelines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=ChennaiMarch 21 |first1=India Today Web Desk |last2=March 21 |first2=India Today Web Desk |last3=Ist |first3=India Today Web Desk |title=Twitter takes down Rajinikanth's Janata Curfew video for spreading misinformation |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/regional-cinema/story/twitter-takes-down-rajinikanth-s-janata-curfew-video-for-spreading-misinformation-1658282-2020-03-21 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref> [[Amitabh Bachchan]] was heavily criticised for one of his tweets, which claimed vibrations from clapping, blowing conch shells as part of Sunday's Janata Curfew would have reduced or destroyed coronavirus potency as it was \u2018[[amavasya]]\u2019, the darkest day of the month.<ref>{{cite news |title=Amitabh Bachchan deletes post on \u2018clapping vibrations destroy virus potency\u2019 after being called out |url=https://trib.al/Bcqp2dp |work=The Hindu |date=23 March 2020 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\nResidents of a village named ''Korauna'' in [[Sitapur district]] in [[Uttar Pradesh]] faced discrimination due to similarity in name of the village with the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/people-confuse-ups-korauna-for-corona-outsiders-even-wont-take-a-phone-call-from-village20200329195919|title=People confuse UP's Korauna for Corona; outsiders even won't take a phone call from village|work=ANI|date=29 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome doctors and medical workers were evicted from their homes over fears they may be carrying coronavirus. In cases reported across the country, healthcare professionals described the growing stigma they are facing from their neighbours and landlords, resulting in many being refused taxis, barricaded from their own homes, or made homeless.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/30/indian-doctors-being-evicted-from-homes-over-coronavirus-fears |title=Indian doctors being evicted from homes over coronavirus fears |work=The Guardian |date=30 March 2020 |authors=Hannah Ellis Petersen |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/bengal-kolkata-landlords-evict-medical-professionals-coronavirus-1659333-2020-03-25 |title=Kolkata landlords evict medical professionals, Resident Doctor's Association steps in |work=India Today |date=25 March 2020 |authors=Romita Datta |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, foreigners from countries such as UK, US and Israel were facing hostility, including evictions from rented homes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/foreign-tourists-face-hostility-india-coronavirus-panic-200324083648362.html|title=Foreign tourists face hostility in India amid coronavirus panic|work=[[Al Jazeera]]|date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome patients, in different quarantine facilities of [[Uttar Pradesh]], refused to eat food because the cooks in these facilities were [[Dalit]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/coronavirus-outbreak-untouchability-even-in-quarantine/cid/1764186 |title=Untouchability, even in quarantine |work=The Telegraph |date=12 April 2020 |author=Piyush Srivastava |access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://thestateindia.com/2020/04/12/patient-admitted-to-quarantine-center-in-kushinagar-refuses-to-eat-food-cooked-by-dalit |title=Patient admitted to quarantine center in Kushinagar refuses to eat food cooked by Dalit |work=The State |date=12 April 2020 |access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nMuslim gatherings organised by the [[Tablighi Jamaat]] has resulted in a large increase in COVID-19 cases, which has triggered [[Islamophobia|Islamophobic]] reactions and increased [[Communalism (South Asia)|communal tension]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-india-islam-insigh/the-religious-retreat-that-sparked-indias-major-coronavirus-manhunt-idUSKBN21K3KF |title=The religious retreat that sparked India's major coronavirus manhunt |author1=Devjyot Ghoshal |author2=Aftab Ahmed |author3=Alasdair Pal |work=Reuters |access-date=3 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403134104/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-india-islam-insigh/the-religious-retreat-that-sparked-indias-major-coronavirus-manhunt-idUSKBN21K3KF |archive-date=3 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-52147260 |title=Coronavirus: Islamophobia concerns after India mosque outbreak |date= 3 April 2020 |work=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/33017d73-d526-42ea-a2ee-b09078684534 |title=Muslims fear backlash of India's coronavirus fury |work=Financial Times |date=3 March 2020 |author1=Amy Kazmin |author2=Edward White |author3=Stefania Palma |access-date=3 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403112048/https://www.ft.com/content/33017d73-d526-42ea-a2ee-b09078684534 |archive-date=3 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Islamophobic hashtags began circulating shortly after the news broke in late March.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://time.com/5815264/coronavirus-india-islamophobia-coronajihad/ |title=It Was Already Dangerous to Be Muslim in India. Then Came the Coronavirus |work=Time Magazine |date=3 April 2020 |author=Billy Perrigo |url-status=live }}</ref> Videos falsely claiming to show members of Tablighi Jamaat spitting on police and other such allegations quickly went viral on social media.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.altnews.in/coronavirus-video-of-an-undertrial-in-mumbai-falsely-viral-as-nizamuddin-markaz-attendee-spitting-at-cop/ |title=Coronavirus: Video of an undertrial in Mumbai falsely viral as Nizamuddin markaz attendee spitting at cop |publisher=[[Altnews.in]] |date=2 April 2020 |first=Pooja| last=Chaudhuri |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.altnews.in/old-video-from-philippines-where-dilivery-boy-was-caught-taking-pieces-of-bread-from-packets-viral-with-communal-angle/ |title=Old video from Philippines shared with false claim of Muslim man spitting on bread |publisher=[[AltNews.in]] |date=9 April 2020 |first=Archit| last=Mehta |url-status=live }}</ref> A tribal boy in [[Jharkhand]] was killed over a clash over such rumours.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://scroll.in/latest/958611/jharkhand-one-dead-after-clashes-over-rumours-of-muslim-men-spitting-to-spread-coronavirus |title=Jharkhand: One dead after clashes over rumours of Muslim men spitting to spread coronavirus |work=Scroll |date=8 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In [[North West Delhi]], a mob attacked a Muslim man and told him to renounce [[Islam]] as they believed that he was part of a so-called Islamic conspiracy to spread [[SARS-CoV-2|coronavirus]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/13/coronavirus-conspiracy-theories-targeting-muslims-spread-in-india |title=Coronavirus conspiracy theories targeting Muslims spread in India |work=The Guardian |date=13 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n\nThe numbers are from data published by [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare]] on their website.{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India medical cases}} {{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India medical cases summary}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Confirmed Indian cases abroad===\nThe Ministry of External Affairs has confirmed that there are 276 confirmed Indians cases abroad as of 18 March. Most of them were in Iran (255), with others in United Arab Emirates, Italy, Kuwait, Sri Lanka, Rwanda and Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/indians-including-iran-test-positive-for-coronavirus-abroad-confirms-mea-1656927-2020-03-18|title=276 Indians including 255 in Iran test positive for coronavirus abroad, confirms MEA|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> One Indian died in Iran on 20 March 2020.<ref name=\"Iran\">{{Cite news|last=Chaudhury|first=Dipanjan Roy|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-one-indian-in-iran-dead-government-gives-local-help-to-254-others/articleshow/74722021.cms|title=Covid-19: One Indian in Iran dead, Government gives local help to 254 others|date=20 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> A 3-year-old Indian girl tested positive in Singapore on 26 March, taking total to 277.<ref name=singapore>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/india/article/3-yr-old-indian-girl-among-73-new-coronavirus-cases-in-singapore-tally-of-infected-people-crosses/569723|title=3-yr-old Indian girl among 73 new coronavirus cases in Singapore, tally of infected people crosses 600|website=www.timesnownews.com|agency=PTI|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> In Kuwait, a 46-year-old Indian died on 4 April.<ref name=\"Kuwait\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=2884135&language=en|title=Kuwait reports 1st coronavirus death, 62 new cases|website=Kuwait News Agency|date=4 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:90%;\"\n|+\n