ice 2014 |url=http://www.teenchoiceawards.com/votetv.aspx |website=[[Teen Choice Awards]] |publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company]] |accessdate=July 27, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2014 Young Hollywood Awards|Young Hollywood Awards]]\n| colspan=\"1\" | Breakthrough Actor\n| Himself\n| {{won}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=List of Nominees |url=http://yhawards.com/nominees/ |website=[[Young Hollywood Awards]] |publisher=PMC |accessdate=July 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2014/07/28/young-hollywood-awards-2014-list-award-winner/ |title=Young Hollywood Awards Winners 2014 \u2013 Full List: Justin Bieber & More |last=Thompson |first=Avery |date=July 28, 2014 |website=Hollywood Life |accessdate=August 27, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\" |2015\n|Melty Future Awards\n|Prix International Masculin\n| Himself\n| {{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.melty.fr/melty-future-awards-2015/ |title=Prix Internacional Masculin |website=Melty |language=French |accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[2015 MTV Movie Awards|MTV Movie Awards]]\n| [[MTV Movie Award for Best Hero|Best Hero]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Maze Runner, The\" |''The Maze Runner''\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" |<ref>{{cite web |title=MTV Movie Awards |url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/ |website=MTV.com |publisher=[[MTV]] |accessdate=March 4, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[MTV Movie Award for Best Fight|Best Fight]] <small>(shared with [[Will Poulter]])</small>\n| data-sort-value=\"Maze Runner, The\" |''The Maze Runner''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Movie Award for Best Scared-As-S**t Performance|Best Scared-As-S**t Performance]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Maze Runner, The\" |''The Maze Runner''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Movie Award for Best Breakthrough Performance|Breakthrough Performance]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Maze Runner, The\" |''The Maze Runner''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[2015 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Movie Actor: Action/Adventure\n| data-sort-value=\"Maze Runner, The\" | ''The Maze Runner''\n| {{nominated}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=Teen Choice 2015 Wave 1 Nominees |url=http://www.teenchoice.com/article/wave-1-nominees |website=Teen Choice Awards |publisher=Fox Broadcasting Network |accessdate=February 6, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322152635/http://www.teenchoice.com/article/wave-1-nominees |archivedate=March 22, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| Choice Movie Chemistry <small>(shared with [[Thomas Brodie-Sangster]])</small>\n| data-sort-value=\"Maze Runner, The\" |''The Maze Runner''\n| {{nominated}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | <ref>{{cite web |title=Teen Choice 2015 Wave 2 Nominees |url=http://www.teenchoice.com/article/wave-2-nominees |website=Teen Choice Awards |publisher=Fox Broadcasting Network |accessdate=July 8, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709080549/http://www.teenchoice.com/article/wave-2-nominees |archivedate=July 9, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| Choice TV: Scene Stealer\n| ''Teen Wolf''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2016\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[2016 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n|Choice AnTEENcipated Movie Actor\n|''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]''\n| {{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teenchoice.com/article/vote-now-for-wave-3-teen-choice-nominees |title=Teen Choice 2016 Wave 3 Nominees |website=Teen Choice Awards |publisher=Fox Broadcasting Network |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710032755/http://www.teenchoice.com/article/vote-now-for-wave-3-teen-choice-nominees |archivedate=July 10, 2016 |accessdate=July 7, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| Choice Movie Actor: Action/Adventure\n| data-sort-value=\"Scorch Trials, The\" | ''[[Maze Runner: The Scorch Trials|The Scorch Trials]]''\n| {{won}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=Teen Choice 2016 Wave 1 Nominees |url=http://www.teenchoice.com/article/first-wave-of-%E2%80%9Cteen-choice-2016%E2%80%9D-nominees-announced-and-1-voted-surfboard-revealed |website=Teen Choice Awards |publisher=Fox Broadcasting Network |accessdate=May 25, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| Choice Movie Chemistry <small>(shared with [[Thomas Brodie-Sangster]])</small>\n| data-sort-value=\"Scorch Trials, The\" |''The Scorch Trials''\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=2 | <ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |title=Teen Choice 2016 Wave 2 Nominees |url=http://www.teenchoice.com/article/vote-now-for-wave-2-teen-choice-nominees |website=Teen Choice Awards |publisher=Fox Broadcasting Network |accessdate=June 9, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620081726/http://www.teenchoice.com/article/vote-now-for-wave-2-teen-choice-nominees |archivedate=June 20, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Summer TV Star: Male|Choice Summer TV Actor]]\n| ''Teen Wolf''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2017\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[2017 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice TV Actor Fantasy/Sci-Fi|Choice Sci-Fi/Fantasy TV Actor]]\n| ''Teen Wolf''\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | <ref>{{cite web |title=Teen Choice Awards 2017 winners list |url=http://ew.com/tv/2017/08/13/teen-choice-awards-winners-2017/ |website=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=August 14, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| Choice TV Ship <small>(shared with [[Holland Roden]])</small>\n|''Teen Wolf''\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2018\n| [[BreakTudo Awards]]\n| International Actor\n| data-sort-value=\"Death Cure, The\" | ''[[Maze Runner: The Death Cure|The Death Cure]]''\n| {{won}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=Tiffany Young Wins K-pop Female Artist at the 2018 BreakTudo Awards |url=https://www.allkpop.com/article/2018/10/tiffany-young-wins-k-pop-female-artist-at-the-2018-breaktudo-awards |work=[[Allkpop]] |accessdate=October 25, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[2018 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Action Movie Actor\n| data-sort-value=\"Death Cure, The\" | ''The Death Cure''\n| {{nominated}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | <ref>{{cite web |title=Teen Choice Awards 2018: See the full list of winners |url=https://ew.com/awards/2018/08/12/teen-choice-awards-winners-list/ |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Choice Movie Ship <small>(shared with [[Kaya Scodelario]])</small>\n| data-sort-value=\"Death Cure, The\" | ''The Death Cure''\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n*[http://www.mtv.com/celebrity/dylan-obrien/#cast=teen_wolf Dylan O'Brien] profile on [[MTV]]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Dylan O'Brien\n|list =\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Breakthrough Performance}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Fight}}\n{{Teen Choice Award for Choice TV Actor Fantasy/Sci-Fi}}\n{{Teen Choice Award Choice TV Villain}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:OBrien, Dylan}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Los Angeles County, California]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:Male actors of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:People from Hermosa Beach, California]]\n[[Category:People from Springfield Township, Union County, New Jersey]]\n", "name_user": "Amyadams7777", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling error on New Jersey", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dylan_O%27Brien"}
{"title_page": "Church of Saint-Sulpice, Jumet", "text_new": "{{About|the church in Jumet|the Parisian church|Church of Saint-Sulpice, Paris}}\n{{Other uses|Saint-Sulpice (disambiguation)}}\n{{Short description|church in Jumet, Belgium}}\n{{cleanup translation|French|listed=yes}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n| building_name         = Church of Saint-Sulpice\n| infobox_width         =\n| image                 = Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - 2019-07-13 - 01.jpg\n| image_size            =\n| alt                   =\n| caption               =\n| map_type              =\n| map_size              =\n| map_caption           = \n| location              = [[Charleroi]], [[Hainaut (province)|Hainaut]], Belgium\n| geo                   = {{coord|50.450875|4.425897|region:BE|display=inline,title}}\n| religious_affiliation = [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]\n| rite                  =\n| region                = {{BE-REG-WAL}} \n| province              = {{BE-PROV-HT}}\n| district              = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tournai|Diocese of Tournai]]\n| cercle                =\n| municipality          = [[File:Drapeau ville be Charleroi.svg|22px]] [[Charleroi]]\n| consecration_year     =\n| status                = Church\n| functional_status     = Active\n| heritage_designation  = 1949\n| leadership            =\n| website               =\n| architecture          =\n| architect             =\n| architecture_type     = \n| architecture_style    =\n| founded_by            =\n| funded_by             =\n| general_contractor    =\n| facade_direction      =\n| groundbreaking        = 1750\n| year_completed        = 1753\n| construction_cost     =\n| specifications        =\n| capacity              =\n| length                =\n| width                 =\n| width_nave            =\n| height_max            =\n| spire_quantity        =\n| spire_height          =\n| materials             =\n| nrhp                  =\n| added                 =\n| refnum                =\n| designated            =\n}}\n\nThe '''Church of Saint Sulpice''' ({{lang-fr|\u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice}}; {{IPA-fr|s\u025b\u0303sylpis}}) is a [[Roman Catholic]] church in [[Jumet]], a neighborhood of the [[Belgium|Belgian]] town of [[Charleroi]] in [[Hainaut (province)|Hainaut]], [[Wallonia]].{{sfn|PMDB|1994|p=126}} It is dedicated to [[Sulpitius the Pious]]. The oldest material traces of a religious building on the site date back to the 10th century. Three churches preceding the current construction were identified during excavations carried out in 1967. The current building was built between 1750 and 1753 in a classical style, by an anonymous architect.<ref name=\"ref1\">{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=33}}</ref> The brick and limestone church is quite homogeneous. It's composed of six [[bay (architecture)|bay]]ed [[nave]]s flanked by [[aisle]]s, a three-sided [[transept]] and a [[choir (architecture)|choir]] with a polygonal [[ambulatory]] with a [[sacristy]] in its axis. The [[chamfer]]ed [[Foundation (architecture)|base]] is in [[dimension stone]] on the frontage, in rubble stones and [[sandstone]] for the rest. All the angles of the building are toothed and every second stone is [[Boss (architecture)|bossed]]. The church has been listed as a [[Heritage registers in Belgium|Belgian cultural heritage]] site since 1949.\n\n== Historical context ==\nBoth the church and Jumet itself were cited in 868 in the [[Polyptych (document)|polyptych]] of [[Lobbes Abbey]].<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=10}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=100}}</ref> Despite its age, it is rarely mentioned in records. Most of the relevant documents were probably lost in the destruction of the [[State Archives in Belgium|State Archives]] in [[Mons]] and of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tournai|episcopal archives of Tournai]] at the beginning of the [[Second World War]].<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=12}}</ref>\n\nBefore the [[French Revolution]], Jumet was part of the [[Prince-Bishopric of Li\u00e8ge]]; the [[abbot]] of [[Lobbes Abbey|Lobbes]] was [[Sovereignty|sovereign]] [[Manorialism|lord]] by appointment of the [[List of bishops and prince-bishops of Li\u00e8ge|Prince-bishop]].<ref>{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=52}}</ref> However, its neighbouring states, [[County of Hainaut|Hainaut]] and [[Duchy of Brabant|Brabant]], challenged Li\u00e8ge's claim to Jumet. Over time, Brabant gained in influence, which seemed in accordance with the local population's wish.<ref>{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=53}}</ref> By the 1730s, Brabant was acting as if it completely owned Jumet. During the 1740s, Duchess [[Maria Theresa]] of Austria and the [[Council of Brabant]] instituted administrative reforms at the request of the [[mayor]] and the magistrate. On 28 June 1780, Prince-Bishop [[Fran\u00e7ois-Charles de Velbr\u00fcck]] officially yielded the lordship of Jumet to Brabant.<ref>{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=61}}</ref> During the [[History of Belgium#French control|period of French rule]], Jumet belonged to the [[Jemmape (department)|department of Jemappes]], which became part of the [[Hainaut (province)|province of Hainaut]] after the fall of [[Napoleon]].\n\nThe church's predecessors, whose [[patron saint]] remains unknown, belonged to a [[parish]] of the old [[deanery]] of [[Fleurus]], part of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Li\u00e8ge|diocese of Li\u00e8ge]]. In 1559, during reforms of the episcopal hierarchy of the [[Low Countries]], this parish was first assigned to the newly created [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Namur|diocese of Namur]],<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|pp=11\u201312}}</ref> and later to the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Namur|diocese of Tournai]] in the [[Concordat of 1801]].\n\n== The excavation of 1967 ==\nIn 1967, the church underwent a major restoration led by {{ill|Simon Brigode|fr}}, architect and professor at the [[Catholic University of Leuven (1834\u20131968)|University of Leuven]]. During this restoration, [[excavation (archaeology)|excavation]]s were conducted by {{ill|Luc-Francis Genicot|fr}}, [[assistant professor]] at the University of Leuven, from 16\u201322 August 1967.\n\n[[File:Jumet - \u00e9glise saint-Sulpice - fouilles de 1967 - tranch\u00e9es-en.svg|upright=1.5|alt=Layout of excavation|thumb|left|Layout of the August 1967 excavation]]\nThese excavations were conducted in a limited area which turned out to be of significance.<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=9}}</ref> although the restoration work had already destroyed some of the ancient foundations.<ref name=\"gen18\">{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=18}}</ref>\n\nThe construction of the current church had already profoundly modified the earlier site. The 18th-century flooring is lower than earlier levels; only the lowest levels of the old [[foundation (engineering)|foundation]] still remained. During the excavations they found no foundation, no under-pavement, no lime mortar runoff, and no [[altar (Catholicism)|altar]] base.<ref name=\"gen18\"/> The sepulchre lay {{convert|19|cm|in}} under the current flooring level only.<ref name=\"gen19\">{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=19}}</ref>\n\nThe work done in the 19th and 20th centuries removed ancient traces. A thin brick gutter to hold [[gas lighting]] pipes was installed during the second half of the 19th century, cutting across the ''B'' trench.<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=22}}</ref> An early 20th-century gutter, constructed roughly along the lengthwise axis of the current church, cut through the old foundations.<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=20}}</ref>\n\nThese surveys made it possible to correctly locate the building's successive stages of growth.<ref name=\"gen19\"/>\n{{Clear|left}}\n\n== The successive churches ==\nThree religious buildings that preceded the current church were uncovered during the excavations.\n\n[[File:Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - fouilles de 1967-en.svg|alt=|thumb|left|upright=2|Superimposed plans of churches 1, 3 and 4.]]\n{{Clear|left}}\n\n=== First church ===\n[[Pre-Romanesque art and architecture|Pre-Romanesque]], the first building was formed of a rectangular chamber composed of a plain [[nave]] {{convert|4.7|m|yd}} wide, whose length the excavations did not manage to determine. It is possible that as in other small churches of the [[early Middle Ages]], the length of the church was double its width. This edifice may have been the church consecrated between 959 and 971 by Eraclus, abbot of [[Lobbes Abbey|Lobbes]] and bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Li\u00e8ge|Li\u00e8ge]], which was mentioned in the \"Eraclus charter\".<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=25}}</ref>\n\n=== Second church ===\n[[File:Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - fouilles de 1967 - phase 2-en.svg|alt=|upright=1.2|thumb|left|Superimposed plans of churches 2 and 3.]]\nDuring the excavation, the only trace of the second church that was found is the foundation of an irregular three-sided [[apse]]. It is unclear how the building developed towards the [[narthex]]. We do know that this side ended with a tower because Jehan Camal, the local [[priest]], in his will of 1517, bequeathed 50 [[French livre|livres]] towards the repairing of the tower and the installation of a [[Church bell|bell]].<ref>{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=102}}</ref> The tower is probably the same one that was mentioned in the 17th century and that was subsequently demolished for the construction of the 18th century church.<ref name=\"ref2\">{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=30}}</ref> The size of the [[Choir (architecture)|choir]] suggests a three-apsed construction, maybe similar to the third church.<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=27}}</ref> As well as the main altar, a [[Pouill\u00e9 (ecclesiastical register)|''Pouill\u00e9'']] ecclesiastical register from 1445 mentioned an altar devoted to [[Saint Nicholas]], and another from 1518 mentions an altar devoted to the [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Virgin Mary]].<ref>{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=101}}</ref>\n\nNoting the similarities to the choir in Saint-Martin's church at [[Marcinelle]], rebuilt at the end of the 15th century, Luc-Francis Genicot hypothesised that it took inspiration from Jumet's earlier design, possibly from the 14th century.<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=28}}</ref>\n\nIn the choir lies a burial place containing a skeleton in a nailed oak coffin. The presence of embroidered cloth and the location suggests that it is the tomb of a priest, probably the local [[parson]].<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|pp=38\u201339}}</ref>\n{{Clear|left}}\n\n=== Third church ===\n[[File:Jumet_-_%C3%A9glise_Saint-Sulpice_-_fa%C3%A7ade_nord_-_fondations_des_%C3%A9difices_pr%C3%A9c%C3%A9dents.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Foundations of previous buildings]]\nThe choir of the third edifice probably dates back to the middle of the 17th century.<ref name=\"ref3\">{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=36}}</ref> This church is eight times bigger than the first. The choir is of a [[pentagon]]al design {{convert|8.25|m|yd}} deep. It is consolidated by four [[buttress]]es, suggesting that it was once covered by a solid [[Vault (architecture)|vault]], probably of [[Gothic architecture|gothic]] design. The nave, {{convert|22|m|yd}} long and of an estimated width of {{convert|20|m|yd}}, is slightly [[Trapezoid|trapezium]]-shaped<ref>Considering that the restitution is correct, because the south-west angle hasn't been maintained {{harv|Genicot|1969|p=30}}.</ref> and has two [[aisle]]s. The scale of the aisles lets us imagine a building of the [[hall church]] type, like many that existed in Hainault in the 15th and 16th century.\n\nThe tower stands against the church frontage. It underwent an important restoration in 1670 and a clock was installed in 1681. This bell-tower was probably square and roughly {{convert|6.4|m|yd}} long on each side. It was capped by an octagonal pointed spire, topped by a big [[finial]] cross and a weathercock reaching to {{convert|38|m|yd}} high.<ref name=\"ref1\" />\n\nIn 1710, the state of the church again called for serious repairs, and Jumet's [[bailiff]], Jean de Vigneron, asked the abbot of Lobbes, a big [[tithe]] collector, to build a new church. The abbey could not meet the expense.<ref name=\"ref4\">{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=103}}</ref> Finally, after a lawsuit{{clarify|date=August 2017}}, an agreement was reached for the repairs to the church including the choir, the tower and the roof of the nave.<ref name=\"ref5\">{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=15}}</ref>\n\n=== Present church ===\n[[File:Jumet - \u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice - Plan, coupes transversale et verticale, et \u00e9l\u00e9vation des fa\u00e7ades principale et lat\u00e9rale - feuille E - coup\u00e9e.jpg|alt=|thumb|upright|Section and elevation of the first draft of the 18th century with the old tower held (sheet ''E'').]]\nThe present church was built between 1750 and 1753 by an anonymous architect. The original plans consist of five coloured sheets.<ref>Kept at [[State Archives in Belgium]] {{harv|Genicot|1969|p=16}}</ref> They have been numbered from ''A '' to ''E'' without any obvious order, probably after the completion of the construction. The ''C'' sheet did not belong to the first file, but the five drawings are from the same author. The ''E'' sheet has notes on the back where the name of ''D. De Lados'' appears twice, suggesting that it could be the name of the architect.<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|pp=16\u201317}}</ref>\n\nBefore 1750, the old church was demolished and the ground levelled.<ref name=\"gen18\"/> This levelling is probably why the present church isn't correctly [[Orientation of churches|oriented]], unlike the original church, whose choir perfectly faced east.<ref name=\"ref6\">{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=104}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - fa\u00e7ade nord - remploi.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Details of materials reused in the current facing of the north facade.]]\nThe design was ambitious and excessive for the locals of the time. Tensions took place between the architect and the sponsors, including the abbot of Lobbes, Th\u00e9odulphe Barnab\u00e9 (abbot from 1728 to 1752).<ref name=\"ref5\" /> Construction lagged and, even though old materials were re-used in the base and the pavements,<ref name=\"ref3\" /> the cost was five times the original estimate : {{centered pull quote|We have been greatly wronged for the erection of this church[...]because the church building, instead of costing us twenty thousand [[Florin (Italian coin)|florin]]s, is now costing us at least a hundred thousand [...] The architect has deceived us by increasing the length of the so-mentioned church by twenty-nine feet, and many other things|author=Complaint quoted by L-F. Genicot|source=<ref name=\"ref5\" />}}\n\nThe initial plan intended to re-integrate the old tower. An amendment definitely scrapped all the past.<ref name=\"ref3\" /> This project of a new tower probably belonged to that part of the ''many other things'' that were mentioned in the complaint.\n[[File:Jumet - \u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice - Plan, coupes transversale et verticale, et \u00e9l\u00e9vation des fa\u00e7ades principale et lat\u00e9rale - feuille C.jpg|thumb|upright|18th century drawing of a proposed new facade (sheet'' C'')]]\nThis conflict ended with a trial before the Sovereign Council of Brabant. The architect was forced to reduce the scale of the project. This is evident by examining the successive frontage projects<ref name=\"ref6\" /> and comparing the size of the achieved high parts and the planned size on the original elevation drawing. The construction continued but with some delay. The church was finished in 1753.<ref name=\"ref3\" />\n\nThe steeple was designed to receive three bells. Two bells are attested, and there is no formal proof of the existence of the third.<ref name=\"ref8\">{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=104 ; 106}}</ref>\n\nOn the east side, a bell from 1590 is adorned with the image of the Virgin and has the inscription: ''Micael Willelmus coadiutor Lobiensis me fecit<ref>Michel Willame was co-helper from 1580 to 1598 of the abbey of Lobbes, Ermin Fran\u00e7ois, he was elected himself in 1598 and died in 1600 {{harv|Genicot|1969|p=16}}.</ref> \u2013 1590 \u2013 Ma\u00eetre Jean Grongnart, founder''<ref name=\"ref8\" /><ref>Jean Grongnart belongs to a dynasty of founders that worked in Hainaut during the 16th and 17th century {{harv|Genicot|1969|p=16}}.</ref>\n\nOn the west side, the second bell was probably in bad shape because it was remelted in 1772, as the inscription attests : ''+ In the year 1772 I was remelted at the expense of the community of Jumet by Simon Chevresson and Deforest.''<ref name=\"ref8\" />\n\nIt's probable that the [[French revolution]] induced structural damage because a budget was allocated by the local administration for the repair of window panes and the roof in 1797.<ref name=\"ref9\">{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=105}}</ref> In 1808, three new altars were built.<ref name=\"ref7\">{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=41}}</ref>\n\nIn 1835, the church underwent an important restoration. Part of the pavement was replaced, a new set of furniture was put in, the altars transformed<ref name=\"ref9\" /> and the master altar re-dedicated.<ref name=\"ref7\" />\n\nIn the brickwork of the master altar, removed during the 1968 restorations, a wooden [[reliquary]] casket with a glass lid was discovered. It contained two bones held together by a copper thread. Between them was a paper document in a very bad shape, nearly unreadable, dated 1835. Possibly that the reliquary is older than that and was put there when the altar was re-devoted.<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|pp=40\u201341}}</ref><ref>[http://balat.kikirpa.be/photo.php?path=B205941&objnr=10048113 Photography of the reliquary] on the website of the [[Royal Institute for Cultural Heritage]]</ref>\n\nIn 1840, a [[pipe organ]] was installed, the work of [[organ builder]] Hypolite Loret of [[Brussels]]. The instrument was upgraded in 1873.<ref name=\"ref9\" />\n\nIn 1943, German occupation authorities commandeered the bells. The 1590 bell was taken down and shipped to Germany.<ref>{{harvnb|Maerten|Colignon|2012|pp=38\u201339}}</ref> After the [[Second World War|war]], it was found and re-installed in the steeple.<ref name=\"ref6\" /><ref>[http://balat.kikirpa.be/photo.php?path=A45010&objnr=10048181 Photograph of the bell] on the website of the Royal Institute for Cultural Heritage</ref>\n\n== Architecture and furniture ==\n[[File:\u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice de Jumet - chevet.jpg|alt=|thumb|left|[[Chevet]] of the church.]]\nOf [[classic architecture|classic]] conception, the brick and [[limestone]] church is very homogeneous. It's composed of six [[bay (architecture)|bay]]ed [[nave]]s flanked by [[aisle]]s, a three-sided [[transept]] and a [[choir (architecture)|choir]] with a polygonal [[ambulatory]] with a [[sacristy]] in its axis. The [[chamfer]]ed [[Foundation (architecture)|base]] is in [[dimension stone]] on the frontage, in rubble stones and [[sandstone]] for the rest. All the angles of the building are toothed and every second stone is [[Boss (architecture)|bossed]].{{sfn|PMDB|1994|p=126}}\n[[File:Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - trois trav\u00e9es nord.jpg|thumb|upright|droite|alt=|Exterior elevation of the first three bays of north aisle.]]\nThe windows, except those of the tower, all have a gouged limestone frame cut with protruding teeth, with a curved arch and window aprons joined together by a limestone band going around the whole building. Similarly conceived half-windows are found on the second level in the background, under the [[cornice]].{{sfn|PMDB|1994|p=126}}\n\nThe frontage has two levels, with above them a curved [[pediment]]. On the first level, two belts proceed further than the central part to the side frontages under the [[volute]]d ailerons placed on both sides of the second level. Above the pediment, a square tower is made up of two stories separated by a belt. The tower has a polygonal steeple on a pyramidal base. The limestone portal is preceded by several steps. It's flanked by [[pilaster]]s with crosswalls that hold an [[entablature]] and a curved pediment. There is an arched door.{{sfn|PMDB|1994|p=126}}\n\nA secondary door, preceded by ten steps, is pierced by the first north aisle bay.\n\nThe interior is quite bright, painted in white and grey. It is covered by [[barrel vault]]s. The [[column]]s of the nave are of [[Tuscan order|tuscan]] style. The [[Pier (architecture)|piers]] of the choir and of the transept are crowned with a [[volute]]d [[Capital (architecture)|capital]]s.{{sfn|PMDB|1994|p=126}}\n\nThe church contains noted [[panelling]] and furniture.<ref name=\"paysdecharleroi.be\">\n{{cite web |url= http://www.paysdecharleroi.be/index.php?option=com_flexicontent&view=items&cid=157:patrimoine-religieux&id=203231:eglise-saint-suplice-%C3%A0-jumet&Itemid=716&lang=en |title= Saint-Suplice church in Jumet |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= Le pays de Charleroi |publisher= |accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the church is a [[baptismal font]] from the 11th or 12th century. It consists of a stone bowl slightly flared but circular, flanked by four engaged columns on a base. The columns end with a roughly cut human head, of which two out of four are missing. The style is Romanesque and the font archaic: straight nose and barely cleared, skin-deep eyes, mouth expressionless. These details are characteristic of Romanesque workshops from the 11th and 12th centuries. However, the disposal of Jumet differs from other fonts known by the feature that the heads are borne directly by columns. Usually, the head is supported in cantilever by a kind of console, as is the case, for example, in [[Gerpinnes]].{{sfn|Brigode|1936|p=6-8}}\n\nThe furniture also contains an altar devoted to [[Basilica of Our Lady of Tongre|Our-Lady of Tongre]] and a [[communion bench]], both dating from the 17th century.<ref name=\"paysdecharleroi.be\"/>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Jumet - \u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice - vue depuis le jubet.jpg|General view of the nave from the [[choir loft]].\nFile:Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - bas-c\u00f4t\u00e9.jpg|The north aisle and tuscan columns, towards the choir.\nFile:Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - nef - 02.jpg|The nave and organs as seen from the choir.\nFile:Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - ch\u0153ur.jpg|The choir with ambulatory, the tabernacle and the altar.\nFile:Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - fonts baptismaux - 01.jpg|The baptismal font.<ref name=\"ref9\"/>\nFile:Jumet - \u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice - autel Notre-Dame de Tongre.jpg|Altar devoted to our-Lady of Tongre.\nFile:Jumet - \u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice - banc de communion - d\u00e9tail 2.jpg|Communion bench.\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|\u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice (Jumet)|Church of Saint-Sulpice, Jumet}}\n* [[List of protected heritage sites in Charleroi]]\n* [[Jumet]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://balat.kikirpa.be/results.php?typesearch=advanced&city=Jumet&institute=%C3%A9glise+saint-sulpice&objectnr=&inventorynr=&cliche=&objectname=&material=&technique=&creator=&rolecreator=&title=&schoolstyle=&productionplace=&origin=&subject=&period_start=&period_end=&style=col4&sort=unsorted&limit=24 Old photographs of the Saint-Sulpice church] on the website of the [[Royal Institute for Cultural Heritage]] (KIK-IRPA)\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book |last1= |first1= |authorlink1= |last2= |first2= |authorlink2= |editor1-first= |editor1-last= |editor1-link= |others= |title= Le patrimoine monumental de la Belgique, Wallonie, Hainaut, Arrondissement de Charleroi|trans-title=|url= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |format= |accessdate= |type= |edition= |series= |volume= 20|date= |year= 1994|month= |origyear= |publisher= Pierre Mardaga, \u00e9diteur|location= |language= French|isbn= 2-87009-588-0|oclc= 312155565|doi= |id= |page= |pages= |at= |trans-chapter=|chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= |ref= {{harvid|PMDB|1994}}|bibcode= |layurl= |laysource= |laydate= |author-mask= |author-name-separator= |author-separator= |display-authors= |separator= |postscript= |lastauthoramp=}}\n* {{cite book |last1= Arcq|first1= Robert|authorlink1= |last2= |first2= |authorlink2= |editor1-first= |editor1-last= |editor1-link= |others= |title= Jumet, Pages d'histoire|trans-title=|url= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |format= |accessdate= |type= |edition= |series= |volume= |date= |year= 1973|month= |origyear= |publisher= |location= Jumet|language= French|isbn= |oclc= 704497631|doi= |id= |page= |pages= |at= |trans-chapter=|chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= |ref= harv|bibcode= |layurl= |laysource= |laydate= |author-mask= |author-name-separator= |author-separator= |display-authors= |separator= |postscript= |lastauthoramp=}}\n* {{cite journal |last= Brigode|first= Simon|author= |authorlink= |last2= |first2= |author2= |authorlink2= |date= |year= 1936|month= |title= Notes sur quelques sculptures anciennes conserv\u00e9es \u00e0 Jumet|trans-title= |journal= Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 royale d'arch\u00e9ologie et de pal\u00e9ontologie de Charleroi|volume= |series= |issue= |pages= 6\u201310|at= |chapter= |location= |publisher= |editor1-first= |editor1-last= |editor1-link= |language= French|format= |type= |arxiv= |id= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |pmid= |pmc= |bibcode= |doi= |accessdate= |url= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |layurl= |laysource= |laydate= |quote= |ref= harv|separator= |postscript= }}\n* {{cite book |last1= Brutsaert|first1= Emmanuel|authorlink1= |last2= Menne|first2= Gilbert|authorlink2= |last3= De Meester|first3= Johan|authorlink3= |editor1-first= |editor1-last= |editor1-link= |others= |title= Province du Hainaut, Histoire et patrimoine des communes de Belgique|trans-title=|url= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |format= |accessdate= |type= |edition= |series= |volume= |date= |year= 2009|month= |origyear= |publisher= \u00c9ditions Racine|location= Bruxelles|language= French|isbn= 978-2-87386-599-3|oclc= 690552502|doi= |id= |page= |pages= |at= |trans-chapter=|chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= |ref= {{harvid|HPCB|2009}}|bibcode= |layurl= |laysource= |laydate= |author-mask= |author-name-separator= |author-separator= |display-authors= |separator= |postscript= |lastauthoramp=}}\n* {{cite journal |last= Genicot|first= Luc-Francis|author= |authorlink= |last2= |first2= |author2= |authorlink2= |date= |year= 1969|month= |title= Fouilles en l'\u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice de Jumet|trans-title= |journal= Documents et rapports de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 royale d'arch\u00e9ologie et de pal\u00e9ontologie de Charleroi|volume= LIV|series= |issue= |pages= 10\u201339|at= |chapter= |location= |publisher= |editor1-first= |editor1-last= |editor1-link= |language= French|format= |type= |arxiv= |id= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |pmid= |pmc= |bibcode= |doi= |accessdate= |url= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |layurl= |laysource= |laydate= |quote= |ref= harv|separator= |postscript= }}\n* {{cite book |last1= Maerten|first1= Fabrice|authorlink1= |last2= Colignon|first2= Alain|authorlink2= |editor1-first=|editor1-last= |editor1-link= |others= |title= La Wallonie sous l'Occupation, 1940-1945|trans-title=|url= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |format= |accessdate= |type= |edition= |series= Villes en guerre|volume= |date= |year= 2012|month= |origyear= |publisher= SOMA-CEGES \u2013 Renaissance du Livre |location= Bruxelles-Waterloo|language= French|isbn= 978-2-5070-5062-7|oclc= 821263376|doi= |id= |page= |pages= |at= |trans-chapter=|chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= |ref= harv|bibcode= |layurl= |laysource= |laydate= |author-mask= |author-name-separator= |author-separator= |display-authors= |separator= |postscript= |lastauthoramp=}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Charleroi]]\n[[Category:Churches in Hainaut (province)]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches completed in 1753]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the church in Jumet|the Parisian church|Church of Saint-Sulpice, Paris}}\n{{Other uses|Saint-Sulpice (disambiguation)}}\n{{Short description|church in Jumet, Belgium}}\n{{cleanup translation|French|listed=yes}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n| building_name         = Church of Saint-Sulpice\n| infobox_width         =\n| image                 = Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - 2019-07-13 - 01.jpg\n| image_size            =\n| alt                   =\n| caption               =\n| map_type              =\n| map_size              =\n| map_caption           = \n| location              = [[Charleroi]], [[Hainaut (province)|Hainaut]], Belgium\n| geo                   = {{coord|50.450875|4.425897|region:BE|display=inline,title}}\n| religious_affiliation = [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]\n| rite                  =\n| region                = {{BE-REG-WAL}} \n| province              = {{BE-PROV-HT}}\n| district              = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tournai|Diocese of Tournai]]\n| cercle                =\n| municipality          = [[File:Drapeau ville be Charleroi.svg|22px]] [[Charleroi]]\n| consecration_year     =\n| status                = Church\n| functional_status     = Active\n| heritage_designation  = 1949\n| leadership            =\n| website               =\n| architecture          =\n| architect             =\n| architecture_type     = \n| architecture_style    =\n| founded_by            =\n| funded_by             =\n| general_contractor    =\n| facade_direction      =\n| groundbreaking        = 1750\n| year_completed        = 1753\n| construction_cost     =\n| specifications        =\n| capacity              =\n| length                =\n| width                 =\n| width_nave            =\n| height_max            =\n| spire_quantity        =\n| spire_height          =\n| materials             =\n| nrhp                  =\n| added                 =\n| refnum                =\n| designated            =\n}}\n\nThe '''Church of Saint Sulpice''' ({{lang-fr|\u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice}}; {{IPA-fr|s\u025b\u0303sylpis}}) is a [[Roman Catholic]] church in [[Jumet]], a neighborhood of the [[Belgium|Belgian]] town of [[Charleroi]] in [[Hainaut (province)|Hainaut]], [[Wallonia]].{{sfn|PMDB|1994|p=126}} It is dedicated to [[Sulpitius the Pious]]. The oldest material traces of a religious building on the site date back to the 10th century. Three churches preceding the current construction were identified during excavations carried out in 1967. The current building was built between 1750 and 1753 in a classical style, by an anonymous architect.<ref name=\"ref1\">{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=33}}</ref> The brick and limestone church is quite homogeneous. It's composed of six [[bay (architecture)|bay]]ed [[nave]]s flanked by [[aisle]]s, a three-sided [[transept]] and a [[choir (architecture)|choir]] with a polygonal [[ambulatory]] with a [[sacristy]] in its axis. The [[chamfer]]ed [[Foundation (architecture)|base]] is in [[dimension stone]] on the frontage, in rubble stones and [[sandstone]] for the rest. All the angles of the building are toothed and every second stone is [[Boss (architecture)|bossed]]. The church has been listed as a [[Heritage registers in Belgium|Belgian cultural heritage]] site since 1949.\n\n== Historical context ==\nBoth the church and Jumet itself were cited in 868 in the [[Polyptych (document)|polyptych]] of [[Lobbes Abbey]].<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=10}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=100}}</ref> Despite its age, it is rarely mentioned in records. Most of the relevant documents were probably lost in the destruction of the [[State Archives in Belgium|State Archives]] in [[Mons]] and of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tournai|episcopal archives of Tournai]] at the beginning of the [[Second World War]].<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=12}}</ref>\n\nBefore the [[French Revolution]], Jumet was part of the [[Prince-Bishopric of Li\u00e8ge]]; the [[abbot]] of [[Lobbes Abbey|Lobbes]] was [[Sovereignty|sovereign]] [[Manorialism|lord]] by appointment of the [[List of bishops and prince-bishops of Li\u00e8ge|Prince-bishop]].<ref>{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=52}}</ref> However, its neighbouring states, [[County of Hainaut|Hainaut]] and [[Duchy of Brabant|Brabant]], challenged Li\u00e8ge's claim to Jumet. Over time, Brabant gained in influence, which seemed in accordance with the local population's wish.<ref>{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=53}}</ref> By the 1730s, Brabant was acting as if it completely owned Jumet. During the 1740s, Duchess [[Maria Theresa]] of Austria and the [[Council of Brabant]] instituted administrative reforms at the request of the [[mayor]] and the magistrate. On 28 June 1780, Prince-Bishop [[Fran\u00e7ois-Charles de Velbr\u00fcck]] officially yielded the lordship of Jumet to Brabant.<ref>{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=61}}</ref> During the [[History of Belgium#French control|period of French rule]], Jumet belonged to the [[Jemmape (department)|department of Jemappes]], which became part of the [[Hainaut (province)|province of Hainaut]] after the fall of [[Napoleon]].\n\nThe church's predecessors, whose [[patron saint]] remains unknown, belonged to a [[parish]] of the old [[deanery]] of [[Fleurus]], part of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Li\u00e8ge|diocese of Li\u00e8ge]]. In 1559, during reforms of the episcopal hierarchy of the [[Low Countries]], this parish was first assigned to the newly created [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Namur|diocese of Namur]],<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|pp=11\u201312}}</ref> and later to the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Namur|diocese of Tournai]] in the [[Concordat of 1801]].\n\n== The excavation of 1967 ==\nIn 1967, the church underwent a major restoration led by {{ill|Simon Brigode|fr}}, architect and professor at the [[Catholic University of Leuven (1834\u20131968)|University of Leuven]]. During this restoration, [[excavation (archaeology)|excavation]]s were conducted by {{ill|Luc-Francis Genicot|fr}}, [[assistant professor]] at the University of Leuven, from 16\u201322 August 1967.\n\n[[File:Jumet - \u00e9glise saint-Sulpice - fouilles de 1967 - tranch\u00e9es-en.svg|upright=1.5|alt=Layout of excavation|thumb|left|Layout of the August 1967 excavation]]\nThese excavations were conducted in a limited area which turned out to be of significance.<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=9}}</ref> although the restoration work had already destroyed some of the ancient foundations.<ref name=\"gen18\">{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=18}}</ref>\n\nThe construction of the current church had already profoundly modified the earlier site. The 18th-century flooring is lower than earlier levels; only the lowest levels of the old [[foundation (engineering)|foundation]] still remained. During the excavations they found no foundation, no under-pavement, no lime mortar runoff, and no [[altar (Catholicism)|altar]] base.<ref name=\"gen18\"/> The sepulchre lay {{convert|19|cm|in}} under the current flooring level only.<ref name=\"gen19\">{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=19}}</ref>\n\nThe work done in the 19th and 20th centuries removed ancient traces. A thin brick gutter to hold [[gas lighting]] pipes was installed during the second half of the 19th century, cutting across the ''B'' trench.<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=22}}</ref> An early 20th-century gutter, constructed roughly along the lengthwise axis of the current church, cut through the old foundations.<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=20}}</ref>\n\nThese surveys made it possible to correctly locate the building's successive stages of growth.<ref name=\"gen19\"/>\n{{Clear|left}}\n\n== The successive churches ==\nThree religious buildings that preceded the current church were uncovered during the excavations.\n\n[[File:Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - fouilles de 1967-en.svg|alt=|thumb|left|upright=2|Superimposed plans of churches 1, 3 and 4.]]\n{{Clear|left}}\n\n=== First church ===\n[[Pre-Romanesque art and architecture|Pre-Romanesque]], the first building was formed of a rectangular chamber composed of a plain [[nave]] {{convert|4.7|m|yd}} wide, whose length the excavations did not manage to determine. It is possible that as in other small churches of the [[early Middle Ages]], the length of the church was double its width. This edifice may have been the church consecrated between 959 and 971 by Eraclus, abbot of [[Lobbes Abbey|Lobbes]] and bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Li\u00e8ge|Li\u00e8ge]], which was mentioned in the \"Eraclus charter\".<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=25}}</ref>\n\n=== Second church ===\n[[File:Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - fouilles de 1967 - phase 2-en.svg|alt=|upright=1.2|thumb|left|Superimposed plans of churches 2 and 3.]]\nDuring the excavation, the only trace of the second church that was found is the foundation of an irregular three-sided [[apse]]. It is unclear how the building developed towards the [[narthex]]. We do know that this side ended with a tower because Jehan Camal, the local [[priest]], in his will of 1517, bequeathed 50 [[French livre|livres]] towards the repairing of the tower and the installation of a [[Church bell|bell]].<ref>{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=102}}</ref> The tower is probably the same one that was mentioned in the 17th century and that was subsequently demolished for the construction of the 18th century church.<ref name=\"ref2\">{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=30}}</ref> The size of the [[Choir (architecture)|choir]] suggests a three-apsed construction, maybe similar to the third church.<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=27}}</ref> As well as the main altar, a [[Pouill\u00e9 (ecclesiastical register)|''Pouill\u00e9'']] ecclesiastical register from 1445 mentioned an altar devoted to [[Saint Nicholas]], and another from 1518 mentions an altar devoted to the [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Virgin Mary]].<ref>{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=101}}</ref>\n\nNoting the similarities to the choir in Saint-Martin's church at [[Marcinelle]], rebuilt at the end of the 15th century, Luc-Francis Genicot hypothesised that it took inspiration from Jumet's earlier design, possibly from the 14th century.<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=28}}</ref>\n\nIn the choir lies a burial place containing a skeleton in a nailed oak coffin. The presence of embroidered cloth and the location suggests that it is the tomb of a priest, probably the local [[parson]].<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|pp=38\u201339}}</ref>\n{{Clear|left}}\n\n=== Third church ===\n[[File:Jumet_-_%C3%A9glise_Saint-Sulpice_-_fa%C3%A7ade_nord_-_fondations_des_%C3%A9difices_pr%C3%A9c%C3%A9dents.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Foundations of previous buildings]]\nThe choir of the third edifice probably dates back to the middle of the 17th century.<ref name=\"ref3\">{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=36}}</ref> This church is eight times bigger than the first. The choir is of a [[pentagon]]al design {{convert|8.25|m|yd}} deep. It is consolidated by four [[buttress]]es, suggesting that it was once covered by a solid [[Vault (architecture)|vault]], probably of [[Gothic architecture|gothic]] design. The nave, {{convert|22|m|yd}} long and of an estimated width of {{convert|20|m|yd}}, is slightly [[Trapezoid|trapezium]]-shaped<ref>Considering that the restitution is correct, because the south-west angle hasn't been maintained {{harv|Genicot|1969|p=30}}.</ref> and has two [[aisle]]s. The scale of the aisles lets us imagine a building of the [[hall church]] type, like many that existed in Hainault in the 15th and 16th century.\n\nThe tower stands against the church frontage. It underwent an important restoration in 1670 and a clock was installed in 1681. This bell-tower was probably square and roughly {{convert|6.4|m|yd}} long on each side. It was capped by an octagonal pointed spire, topped by a big [[finial]] cross and a weathercock reaching to {{convert|38|m|yd}} high.<ref name=\"ref1\" />\n\nIn 1710, the state of the church again called for serious repairs, and Jumet's [[bailiff]], Jean de Vigneron, asked the abbot of Lobbes, a big [[tithe]] collector, to build a new church. The abbey could not meet the expense.<ref name=\"ref4\">{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=103}}</ref> Finally, after a lawsuit{{clarify|date=August 2017}}, an agreement was reached for the repairs to the church including the choir, the tower and the roof of the nave.<ref name=\"ref5\">{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=15}}</ref>\n\n=== Present church ===\n[[File:Jumet - \u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice - Plan, coupes transversale et verticale, et \u00e9l\u00e9vation des fa\u00e7ades principale et lat\u00e9rale - feuille E - coup\u00e9e.jpg|alt=|thumb|upright|Section and elevation of the first draft of the 18th century with the old tower held (sheet ''E'').]]\nThe present church was built between 1750 and 1753 by an anonymous architect. The original plans consist of five coloured sheets.<ref>Kept at [[State Archives in Belgium]] {{harv|Genicot|1969|p=16}}</ref> They have been numbered from ''A '' to ''E'' without any obvious order, probably after the completion of the construction. The ''C'' sheet did not belong to the first file, but the five drawings are from the same author. The ''E'' sheet has notes on the back where the name of ''D. De Lados'' appears twice, suggesting that it could be the name of the architect.<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|pp=16\u201317}}</ref>\n\nBefore 1750, the old church was demolished and the ground levelled.<ref name=\"gen18\"/> This levelling is probably why the present church isn't correctly [[Orientation of churches|oriented]], unlike the original church, whose choir perfectly faced east.<ref name=\"ref6\">{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=104}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - fa\u00e7ade nord - remploi.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Details of materials reused in the current facing of the north facade.]]\nThe design was ambitious and excessive for the locals of the time. Tensions took place between the architect and the sponsors, including the abbot of Lobbes, Th\u00e9odulphe Barnab\u00e9 (abbot from 1728 to 1752).<ref name=\"ref5\" /> Construction lagged and, even though old materials were re-used in the base and the pavements,<ref name=\"ref3\" /> the cost was five times the original estimate : {{centered pull quote|We have been greatly wronged for the erection of this church[...]because the church building, instead of costing us twenty thousand [[Florin (Italian coin)|florin]]s, is now costing us at least a hundred thousand [...] The architect has deceived us by increasing the length of the so-mentioned church by twenty-nine feet, and many other things|author=Complaint quoted by L-F. Genicot|source=<ref name=\"ref5\" />}}\n\nThe initial plan intended to re-integrate the old tower. An amendment definitely scrapped all the past.<ref name=\"ref3\" /> This project of a new tower probably belonged to that part of the ''many other things'' that were mentioned in the complaint.\n[[File:Jumet - \u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice - Plan, coupes transversale et verticale, et \u00e9l\u00e9vation des fa\u00e7ades principale et lat\u00e9rale - feuille C.jpg|thumb|upright|18th century drawing of a proposed new facade (sheet'' C'')]]\nThis conflict ended with a trial before the Sovereign Council of Brabant. The architect was forced to reduce the scale of the project. This is evident by examining the successive frontage projects<ref name=\"ref6\" /> and comparing the size of the achieved high parts and the planned size on the original elevation drawing. The construction continued but with some delay. The church was finished in 1753.<ref name=\"ref3\" />\n\nThe steeple was designed to receive three bells. Two bells are attested, and there is no formal proof of the existence of the third.<ref name=\"ref8\">{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=104 ; 106}}</ref>\n\nOn the east side, a bell from 1590 is adorned with the image of the Virgin and has the inscription: ''Micael Willelmus coadiutor Lobiensis me fecit<ref>Michel Willame was co-helper from 1580 to 1598 of the abbey of Lobbes, Ermin Fran\u00e7ois, he was elected himself in 1598 and died in 1600 {{harv|Genicot|1969|p=16}}.</ref> \u2013 1590 \u2013 Ma\u00eetre Jean Grongnart, founder''<ref name=\"ref8\" /><ref>Jean Grongnart belongs to a dynasty of founders that worked in Hainaut during the 16th and 17th century {{harv|Genicot|1969|p=16}}.</ref>\n\nOn the west side, the second bell was probably in bad shape because it was remelted in 1772, as the inscription attests : ''+ In the year 1772 I was remelted at the expense of the community of Jumet by Simon Chevresson and Deforest.''<ref name=\"ref8\" />\n\nIt's probable that the [[French revolution]] induced structural damage because a budget was allocated by the local administration for the repair of window panes and the roof in 1797.<ref name=\"ref9\">{{harvnb|Arcq|1973|p=105}}</ref> In 1808, three new altars were built.<ref name=\"ref7\">{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|p=41}}</ref>\n\nIn 1835, the church underwent an important restoration. Part of the pavement was replaced, a new set of furniture was put in, the altars transformed<ref name=\"ref9\" /> and the master altar re-dedicated.<ref name=\"ref7\" />\n\nIn the brickwork of the master altar, removed during the 1968 restorations, a wooden [[reliquary]] casket with a glass lid was discovered. It contained two bones held together by a copper thread. Between them was a paper document in a very bad shape, nearly unreadable, dated 1835. Possibly that the reliquary is older than that and was put there when the altar was re-devoted.<ref>{{harvnb|Genicot|1969|pp=40\u201341}}</ref><ref>[http://balat.kikirpa.be/photo.php?path=B205941&objnr=10048113 Photography of the reliquary] on the website of the [[Royal Institute for Cultural Heritage]]</ref>\n\nIn 1840, a [[pipe organ]] was installed, the work of [[organ builder]] Hypolite Loret of [[Brussels]]. The instrument was upgraded in 1873.<ref name=\"ref9\" />\n\nIn 1943, German occupation authorities commandeered the bells. The 1590 bell was taken down and shipped to Germany.<ref>{{harvnb|Maerten|Colignon|2012|pp=38\u201339}}</ref> After the [[Second World War|war]], it was found and re-installed in the steeple.<ref name=\"ref6\" /><ref>[http://balat.kikirpa.be/photo.php?path=A45010&objnr=10048181 Photograph of the bell] on the website of the Royal Institute for Cultural Heritage</ref>\n\n== Architecture and furniture ==\n[[File:\u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice de Jumet - chevet.jpg|alt=|thumb|left|[[Chevet]] of the church.]]\nOf [[classic architecture|classic]] conception, the brick and [[limestone]] church is very homogeneous. It's composed of six [[bay (architecture)|bay]]ed [[nave]]s flanked by [[aisle]]s, a three-sided [[transept]] and a [[choir (architecture)|choir]] with a polygonal [[ambulatory]] with a [[sacristy]] in its axis. The [[chamfer]]ed [[Foundation (architecture)|base]] is in [[dimension stone]] on the frontage, in rubble stones and [[sandstone]] for the rest. All the angles of the building are toothed and every second stone is [[Boss (architecture)|bossed]].{{sfn|PMDB|1994|p=126}}\n[[File:Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - trois trav\u00e9es nord.jpg|thumb|upright|droite|alt=|Exterior elevation of the first three bays of north aisle.]]\nThe windows, except those of the tower, all have a gouged limestone frame cut with protruding teeth, with a curved arch and window aprons joined together by a limestone band going around the whole building. Similarly conceived half-windows are found on the second level in the background, under the [[cornice]].{{sfn|PMDB|1994|p=126}}\n\nThe frontage has two levels, with above them a curved [[pediment]]. On the first level, two belts proceed further than the central part to the side frontages under the [[volute]]d ailerons placed on both sides of the second level. Above the pediment, a square tower is made up of two stories separated by a belt. The tower has a polygonal steeple on a pyramidal base. The limestone portal is preceded by several steps. It's flanked by [[pilaster]]s with crosswalls that hold an [[entablature]] and a curved pediment. There is an arched door.{{sfn|PMDB|1994|p=126}}\n\nA secondary door, preceded by ten steps, is pierced by the first north aisle bay.\n\nThe interior is quite bright, painted in white and grey. It is covered by [[barrel vault]]s. The [[column]]s of the nave are of [[Tuscan order|tuscan]] style. The [[Pier (architecture)|piers]] of the choir and of the transept are crowned with a [[volute]]d [[Capital (architecture)|capital]]s.{{sfn|PMDB|1994|p=126}}\n\nThe church contains noted [[panelling]] and furniture.<ref name=\"paysdecharleroi.be\">\n{{cite web |url= http://www.paysdecharleroi.be/index.php?option=com_flexicontent&view=items&cid=157:patrimoine-religieux&id=203231:eglise-saint-suplice-%C3%A0-jumet&Itemid=716&lang=en |title= Saint-Suplice church in Jumet |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= Le pays de Charleroi |publisher= |accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the church is a [[baptismal font]] from the 11th or 12th century. It consists of a stone bowl slightly flared but circular, flanked by four engaged columns on a base. The columns end with a roughly cut human head, of which two out of four are missing. The style is Romanesque and the font archaic: straight nose and barely cleared, skin-deep eyes, mouth expressionless. These details are characteristic of Romanesque workshops from the 11th and 12th centuries. However, the disposal of Jumet differs from other fonts known by the feature that the heads are borne directly by columns. Usually, the head is supported in cantilever by a kind of console, as is the case, for example, in [[Gerpinnes]].{{sfn|Brigode|1936|p=6-8}}\n\nThe furniture also contains an altar devoted to [[Basilica of Our Lady of Tongre|Our-Lady of Tongre]] and a [[communion bench]], both dating from the 17th century.<ref name=\"paysdecharleroi.be\"/>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Jumet - \u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice - vue depuis le jubet.jpg|General view of the nave from the [[choir loft]].\nFile:Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - bas-c\u00f4t\u00e9.jpg|The north aisle and tuscan columns, towards the choir.\nFile:Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - nef - 02.jpg|The nave and organs as seen from the choir.\nFile:Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - ch\u0153ur.jpg|The choir with ambulatory, the tabernacle and the altar.\nFile:Jumet - \u00e9glise Saint-Sulpice - fonds baptismaux - 01.jpg|The baptismal font.<ref name=\"ref9\"/>\nFile:Jumet - \u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice - autel Notre-Dame de Tongre.jpg|Altar devoted to our-Lady of Tongre.\nFile:Jumet - \u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice - banc de communion - d\u00e9tail 2.jpg|Communion bench.\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|\u00c9glise Saint-Sulpice (Jumet)|Church of Saint-Sulpice, Jumet}}\n* [[List of protected heritage sites in Charleroi]]\n* [[Jumet]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://balat.kikirpa.be/results.php?typesearch=advanced&city=Jumet&institute=%C3%A9glise+saint-sulpice&objectnr=&inventorynr=&cliche=&objectname=&material=&technique=&creator=&rolecreator=&title=&schoolstyle=&productionplace=&origin=&subject=&period_start=&period_end=&style=col4&sort=unsorted&limit=24 Old photographs of the Saint-Sulpice church] on the website of the [[Royal Institute for Cultural Heritage]] (KIK-IRPA)\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book |last1= |first1= |authorlink1= |last2= |first2= |authorlink2= |editor1-first= |editor1-last= |editor1-link= |others= |title= Le patrimoine monumental de la Belgique, Wallonie, Hainaut, Arrondissement de Charleroi|trans-title=|url= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |format= |accessdate= |type= |edition= |series= |volume= 20|date= |year= 1994|month= |origyear= |publisher= Pierre Mardaga, \u00e9diteur|location= |language= French|isbn= 2-87009-588-0|oclc= 312155565|doi= |id= |page= |pages= |at= |trans-chapter=|chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= |ref= {{harvid|PMDB|1994}}|bibcode= |layurl= |laysource= |laydate= |author-mask= |author-name-separator= |author-separator= |display-authors= |separator= |postscript= |lastauthoramp=}}\n* {{cite book |last1= Arcq|first1= Robert|authorlink1= |last2= |first2= |authorlink2= |editor1-first= |editor1-last= |editor1-link= |others= |title= Jumet, Pages d'histoire|trans-title=|url= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |format= |acce